<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> gave <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leaders what they wanted, a front-runner, but the history of their roller-coaster process made many reluctant to declare that <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had the nominaton locked up. `` We no longer have the winner-a-week syndrome,'' <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruvolo </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Ohio </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said Tuesday. But he quickly added, `` I do n't think you can say it's over.'' One of the few party leaders willing to describe <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as the nominee was <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Cutler </PERSON>, deputy chair of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` I think we have a nominee,'' said <PERSON> Cutler </PERSON>. But she warned that the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign must be `` very careful not to look as though it's a done deal.'' <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, said many of the elected and party officials, designated as super delegates to the nominating convention, may be reluctant to jump too quickly onto the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> bandwagon. `` They're going to want to be real careful about angering <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and his supporters,'' said <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON>. `` I, for one, am very sensitive about offending that constituency.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' big victory in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> essentially knocked Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> out of the race, finally paring the Democratic field down to a two-man contest _ <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> versus <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. The <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> governor was assured of a big delegate harvest in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> next Tuesday after <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> filled only about 65 percent of the 178 delegate slots at stake. But caution stemmed in part from the fact that for months every time a candidate was on verge of claiming front-runner status, the voters knocked him down a peg. An even stronger factor was the formidable presence of <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> and the need now to seriously confront the often-asked question, `` What does <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> want?'' On the campaign trail, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> relishes ridiculing that question, responding with a recitation of the basic liberal <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> agenda _ a higher minimum wage, health care, housing, a shifting of priorities away from those of the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. Repeatedly, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has also said he wanted to `` enable our party to win'' and was determined to `` play a role in making that happen.'' When a questioner at a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> breakfast asked <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> what he would do if he did n't get the nomination, the candidate replied that it was important to `` put the nation first and party second and your role third.'' Among the established leaders of the party there was concern about what <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s large constituency, so essential to Democratic victories in general elections, would do if he failed to get the nomination. <PERSON> Ruvolo </PERSON> said it was important for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> to continue campaigning hard in <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> and other upcoming primary states, to avoid being embarrassed, but also because the contest `` has to be perceived as a fair fight'' by <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s supporters. <PERSON> Said </PERSON> <PERSON> Cutler </PERSON>, `` I think we have to be very careful in these next weeks that Rev. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s candidacy continues to be treated with respect, well-earned credit for everything that he's done for the party.''
