<HEAD>AIDS Cases Likely to Multiply Five Times in Next Three Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The number of full-blown AIDS cases in the world is likely to increase fivefold in the next three years, and hundreds of millions of people probably engage in activity that leaves them vulnerable, says the head of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>'s AIDS program. `` While it has become fashionable to reassure and state that AIDS will never threaten large populations, we believe that virology, immunology, sociology and epidemiology require us to take the long view, and a more somber view,'' Dr. <PERSON> Jonathan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> AIDS commission Monday. `` Let us remember that we are still in the early phases of a global epidemic whose first decade gives us every rational reason for concern about the global future of AIDS,'' he said. `` HIV -LRB- the AIDS virus -RRB- does not need to spread rapidly in a population to have a tremendous and gradually expanding cumulative effect.'' <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> said that while no precise figures are available, `` it is likely that several hundred million people around the world may have behaviors which make them potentially vulnerable to infection with HIV.'' While he did not spell out such behavior at that point in his testimony, it was clear he was referring primarily to unprotected sex with potentially infected partners and, secondarily, to drug users sharing needles with people who may be carrying the virus. `` Individual behavior is responsible for most HIV transmission,'' he said. `` This transmission requires the active participation of two persons. Therefore, the chain of transmission can be broken by the individual behavior of either the infected or the non-infected person. For this reason, the proper focus of prevention is behavior.'' He said education is essential to combating the epidemic. `` If intravenous drug users do not understand the words you use to describe needles, syringes and other drug equipment, they can not learn prevention. If adolescents are convinced that AIDS is being used to deprive them of sexual freedom, they may refuse to listen to prevention messages and even counterreact in ways that further endanger their lives,'' <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> said. More than 81,000 AIDS cases were reported to the organization as of the end of February, but the actual number of AIDS cases is believed to be twice the reported total. WHO estimates that between 5 million and 10 million people are infected with the virus and that 150,000 new cases of fully developed AIDS will be reported during the coming year. `` If we adopt the conservative estimate then 5 million people are infected today with HIV -LRB- the AIDS virus -RRB-, a cumulative total of 1 million AIDS cases would be expected by 1991,'' he said. `` Thus, the period 1988-91 will likely witness over five times more AIDS cases than have thus far occurred.'' Dr. <PERSON> Jean </PERSON> <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Pape </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Cornell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> told the panel the epidemic in <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION> is shifting dramatically to one of heterosexual transmission. Whereas only 26 percent of the cases reported in <LOCATION> Haiti </LOCATION> 1983 were believed to have resulted from heterosexual sex, the number jumped to 64 percent last year. In <LOCATION> Trinidad </LOCATION>, he said, only 12 percent of the cases reported in 1985 were attributed to likely heterosexual sex, compared to 58 percent last year.
</TEXT>
