<SECOND>PM-Patriots' Day,0500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Modern-Day Revere Rides To Lexington Dodging Manholes, Battling
Laryngitis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Revere </PERSON>'s laryngitis made it hard for him to shout, `` The British are coming.'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Dawes </PERSON> got locked in a men's room during a rest stop. And the rain made slippery manholes treacherous for the patriots' horses. Otherwise, Patriots' Day on Monday was the occasion of a satisfactory re-staging of the 13-mile mission to <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> 213 years ago that alerted revolutionary colonists that British troops were heading their way. `` I'm ready to go back,'' <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Snow </PERSON> said in a cracking voice at the end of the 2 -LCB- - hour horseback ride from <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> It was the seventh portrayal of <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Revere </PERSON> for the 72-year-old entrepreneur from <LOCATION> Wellesley </LOCATION> who is a brigadier general in the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lancers </ORGANIZATION>. For decades, the ceremonial militia of 30 men has roughly recreated in daytime the horseback ride that <PERSON> Revere </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dawes </PERSON> and Dr. <PERSON> Samuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Prescott </PERSON> made in the late hours of April 18, 1775. By alerting the insurrectionary colonists that British troops were on their way to <LOCATION> Concord </LOCATION>, the 18th century trio set in motion the next day's confrontation that started the American Revolution. Monday, <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Dougherty </PERSON>, a lieutenant in the lancers who portrayed <PERSON> Dawes </PERSON>, was freed from a men's room in <LOCATION> Arlington </LOCATION> in time to meet up with Snow for their grand finale in <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> where they were met by a cheering crowd estimated at 500 people. This year's journey was considerably harder than the one taken the first time around. Just before Snow left <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> with a send-off from Mayor <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON>, he groused about the rain. His costume of three-cornered hat, wig, cloak and boots made for a hot ride compared to <PERSON> Revere </PERSON>'s, who had the advantage of a cool, clear night and his own clothes. Snow also had to watch out for slippery manholes. But Snow said he enjoyed himself and was grateful for the audience along the way that ignored the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Marathon </LOCATION>. When Snow left <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> End </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Revere </PERSON> lived in a house that still stands, a throng of spectators stood under store awnings and a makeshift canopy of umbrellas. There were grinning toddlers, graying baby-boomers taking off for the state holiday and elderly Italian widows. `` This is how <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> was founded,'' said <PERSON> Patti </PERSON> <PERSON> Gant </PERSON>, an accountant from <PERSON> Everett </PERSON>, who recommended historical re-enactments as a way to understand this country. `` You've got to get the concept of where you come from to know where you go from here,'' said Ms. <PERSON> Gant </PERSON>, 50. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Federico </PERSON>, 35, a pharmacist who grew up in the old, narrow streets of the <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> End </LOCATION>, said he's been coming to see <PERSON> Revere </PERSON> ride off his entire life. That's why he brought his 10-year-old son, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, he said. `` It's a family tradition,'' the elder <PERSON> Federico </PERSON> said with a nod toward his son. `` It's important to see what you read about in the classroom.''
</TEXT>
