<HEAD>Ballet Theater Opens Season with Panache</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: No PMs Planned</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 American Ballet Theater opened its two-month season at the <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opera </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> with panache _ the kind of dancing, style and brio that expects, deserves and receives bravos. Monday's program began with <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> Baryshnikov </PERSON>'s new production and staging of `` Raymonda -LRB- Grand Pas Classique -RRB-.'' <PERSON> Martine </PERSON> <PERSON> van </PERSON> <PERSON> Hamel </PERSON>, a commanding stage presence as well as a glorious ballerina, was partnered superbly by <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> McKenzie </PERSON>. <PERSON> Amanda </PERSON> <PERSON> McKerrow </PERSON>, who danced the fourth solo variation, which requires lightness, long extension and some difficult balances, has blossomed into the ballerina her early promise predicted. <PERSON> Baryshnikov </PERSON> staged the ballet after <PERSON> Marius </PERSON> <PERSON> Petipa </PERSON>, incorporating the grand pas de dix from Act 3 and several variations from the full-length `` Raymonda.'' Music is by <PERSON> Glazounov </PERSON>. <PERSON> Antony </PERSON> <PERSON> Tudor </PERSON>, who died last year, choreographed `` The Leaves Are Fading'' for American Ballet Theater in 1975. The music is by <PERSON> Dvorak </PERSON>. Sometimes this seems merely an overlong, pretty ballet, in which the women's thin skirts ripple as the men lift them and they seem to float. On Monday, it was a beautiful ballet. The various moods were strongly defined. There is much more than a pastel sense of autumn and saying goodby. Exquisite dancing _ which was seen opening night _ is important. Dim lighting instead of very noticeable dappled lighting helps, too, allowing the dancers and the music to hold prominence. <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Browne </PERSON> and <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Hill </PERSON> were the nimble leading couple, their virtuosic dancing having a carefree air about it. The evening ended with the first <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> performance of the company's production of <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Balanchine </PERSON>'s `` Ballet Imperial.'' The company looks comfortable with this <PERSON> Balanchine </PERSON> piece, which is more classical than his usual _ he based it on the Petipa style. Also, in this 1941 ballet, there are intertwinings which are <PERSON> Balanchine </PERSON> trademarks. `` Ballet Imperial'' is as visually regal as the `` Raymonda'' which began the evening and the dancing was as glittering as the women's small crowns. <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaffe </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Stretton </PERSON> were the impressive leading couple and Miss <PERSON> McKerrow </PERSON> distinguished herself again in solos. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Boriskin </PERSON> was the thundering soloist in <PERSON> Tchaikovsky </PERSON>'s `` Second Piano Concerto'' for `` Ballet Imperial. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Everly </PERSON> conducted the entire evening.
