<SECOND>PM-Timbering Dispute,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conservationists Cite Report on National Forest Timbering Losses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A congressional study is giving fresh ammunition to conservationists and lawmakers who want to end the big-bucks losses sustained by taxpayers from timber sales in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s largest national forest. Weighing in on the side of the sales program's critics, the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> says <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should scrap the 1980 law requiring the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to market a minimum amount of timber from <ORGANIZATION> Tongass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, the investigative wing of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, said in a study released Monday that the requirement cost the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> $ 22.1 million in 1986 and has not created the lumbering jobs it was supposed to in southeast <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>. The 1980 law directs the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> to offer to sell at least 4.5 billion board feet of Tongass timber each decade and guarantees at least $ 40 million in spending a year to support the sales program. The law resulted from a compromise worked out by conservationists and <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> lawmakers. In return for the guarantee program, conservationists would get 5.4 million of the forest's 16.8 million acres declared wilderness, putting them off-limits to commercial use The Tongass is the only national forest with a minimum sales goal set by law, although Sen. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> McClure </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Idaho </LOCATION>, has proposed a similar guarantee for the <ORGANIZATION> Panhandle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> in his state. Last month, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> approved legislation to repeal the Tongass guarantee. A similar bill is pending in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The proposals are being pushed by environmental and conservation groups who say the guarantee leads to lost tax dollars, unnecessary roadbuilding by the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and needless harvesting of 400-year-old trees. The <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> study, requested by <PERSON> Sens </PERSON>. <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, D-Wis., and <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Alaska </LOCATION>, said sales of Tongass timber should be subject to market supply-and-demand forces <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said that from 1981 through 1986, sales of Tongass timber averaged 245 million board feet a year, some 205 million below the yearly average needed to meet the 10-year goal. Focusing on 1986, <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> spent $ 47.9 million on the <ORGANIZATION> Tongass </ORGANIZATION> and realized only $ 3.3 million in revenues. The net loss was $ 22.1 million because some spending was for timber production in future years, according to the study. From 1981 through 1986, $ 131 million was spent to prepare for timber sales that were not needed to meet existing demand, the study said. `` The timber supply provision should be revised so that the amount supplied would be based on the anticipated demand for timber and on the data currently being formulated by the <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> ... rather than on a rigid per-decade requirement,'' the study said. <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> said Tongass-related timber jobs declined from 2,700 in 1980 to 1,420 in 1986 `` primarily because of the decreased harvest levels resulting from declining demand for timber and increased production by the <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> native corporations that directly compete with the Tongass timber industry.'' The <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> chief, <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dale </PERSON> <PERSON> Robertson </PERSON>, said in a letter to <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> that the proposal to scrap the <ORGANIZATION> Tongass </ORGANIZATION> guarantee `` has merit.'' <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> said in a prepared statement that <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> focused on a low-demand portion of an economic cycle and that timber has since rebounded. He said money must be spent on the <ORGANIZATION> Tongass </ORGANIZATION> even in slack periods in order to meet peak demand. He also said the study is flawed because it focused only on the guarantee, not on the other side of the 1980 compromise: prohibiting commercial activities in nearly one-third of the Tongass.
