<FIRST>r w PM-EuropeanTrade     04-19 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-European Trade,650</SECOND>
<HEAD>Freer Trade in Europe Would Help US, Other Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Knocking down barriers to trade among the 12 countries of the European Community by 1992 will also benefit outside countries such as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, a researcher says. The main advantage to outside trading partners from greater unification would be in having only a single set of rules to deal with, instead of a dozen, said <PERSON> Paolo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cecchini </PERSON>, assigned by the Community to study the issue. `` A foreign company that sells to only one of the 12 will have jumped over the culture gap,'' he said Monday. <PERSON> Ella </PERSON> <PERSON> Krucoff </PERSON>, press officer for the Community's <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> office, gave labeling requirements on European imports as an example. Now each of the 12 governments has its own rules. <PERSON> Cecchini </PERSON> added that since there would be no official discrimination against subsidiaries of foreign firms within the Community, they too would benefit from any additional growth. <PERSON> Cecchini </PERSON> said that over the `` medium term'' _ about five years _ new measures of unification also could create as many as 5 million new jobs in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, where unemployment is higher than in this country.. He said about 200 people have contributed to his project called `` The Cost of Non-Europe'' _ the cost of not having unified the economy of the Community yet. In addition to <PERSON> Cecchini </PERSON>'s own <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, members include <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. Together, these countries have as many people as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> has also asked to join, and Community officials say <LOCATION> Norway </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION> are possibilities. The European Common Market program is conducted under the auspices of the Community. <PERSON> Cecchini </PERSON> noted that in some matters the Community already has more unity than the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. For example, a doctor licensed in one of the 12 countries is qualified to practice in all of them, unlike the rules here which differ from state to state. Next month <PERSON> Cecchini </PERSON> will start publishing more than 6,000 pages of research. He said his study has found that European economic gains from greater unification could be worth more than $ 300 billion and prices paid by consumers could be 6 percent less than in a divided continent. `` Five million new jobs would cover half of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s unemployed, or all the young unemployed,'' he added. He also cited the example of Japanese auto exporters, whose sales to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> are limited under a quota imposed by the Italian government. The effort is now being made to `` Europeanize'' this quota, so that Japanese sales could go to any of the 12 countries on the same terms. Community officials emphasized there would have to be some hard bargaining with <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> first. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Calingaert </PERSON> is a <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official on leave to study the European effort for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a private group. He said the European plans are moving ahead fast. `` In 1957 industrialists were frightened of the possible results and opposed it,'' he said. `` Now they are in favor.'' He said the private sector is acting as if the effort will succeed, and that attitude could be self-fulfilling. The idea of a unified <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, which dates back centuries, got a boost after World War II when Americans held up the economic advantages of a `` common market'' like that of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. West European countries had to organize themselves to distribute the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> aid offered in the Marshall Plan, and began to eliminate import quotas in trade with one another. In 1957 six of the present 12 members signed the Treaty of <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>, pledging the removal of all barriers among them. Progress has been slow. `` Now things are accelerating,'' <PERSON> Cecchini </PERSON> said. `` Six months ago nobody was even talking about a central bank for the Community. Now the prospect is that the summit meeting in <LOCATION> Hanover </LOCATION> -LRB- <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> -RRB- in June will set up a study of something like the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Federal Reserve system.''
