<FIRST>r w PM-ArmsTreaty     04-19 0530</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Arms Treaty,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Sends Senate Report Urging That INF Treaty Be Passed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Critics of the U.S.-Soviet treaty banning medium-range missiles should be satisfied with Soviet assurances the pact covers both existing missiles and future weapons using exotic technologies, the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> says. The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> told the committee on Monday that the Soviet position was spelled out last week in a conversation between Secretary of State <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shultz </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> Foreign Minister <PERSON> Eduard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>. The dispute centers on the treaty signed Dec. 8 by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, eliminating nuclear missiles with a range of 300 to 3,400 miles. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration said the treaty banned both existing missiles and any `` futuristic'' weapons, such as those using lasers or beam rays, as long as the weapons had a range covered by the treaty. But critics, including members of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, questioned whether the Soviets might have a different view of the treaty and suggested that the ambiguity should be cleared up. Sen. <PERSON> Claiborne </PERSON> <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-R.I. </LOCATION>, the chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said <PERSON> Shevardnadze </PERSON>'s `` unequivocal statement should allay concerns that have been raised about this subject.'' <PERSON> Pell </PERSON>'s committee sent the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> a report Monday that said the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> should approve the treaty and protect its constitutional rights by blocking presidential attempts to change the way treaties are interpreted. The 515-page report sums up the panel's three months of hearings and its votes on the historic pact. The report was approved by the same 17-2 majority which recommended two weeks ago that the treaty should be ratified by the full <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. The opposition votes were cast by <PERSON> Sens </PERSON>. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Pressler </PERSON>, R-S. Ratification requires a vote of 67 of the 100 senators. Leaders of both parties estimate that 90 or more senators will support the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty when it finally comes to a vote. Publication of the committee report means the way is finally clear for formal consideration on the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> floor. Republicans say the most contentious issue will likely be the Democratic-backed amendment that would bar the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> from changing the interpretation of the INF treaty. The amendment, approved 12-7 by the committee, arises from a fight over the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile treaty. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> has asserted that the White House can unilaterally change how the ABM pact is viewed, a move that would permit expanded `` Star Wars'' testing, but congressional Democrats dispute that claim. `` A presidential right to adopt a different interpretation of a treaty, irrespective of the understanding on which the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> based its consent, would tend to nullify the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s share of the treaty power and thus undermine a basic provision of the Constitution,'' the report said. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s only recourse, to prevent its share of the treaty power being nullified, would be to attach elaborate and numerous conditions to treaties in order to have the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s understanding become an integral and explicit part of the ratification documents,'' the report said. `` Such procedures could easily overburden the treaty process to the point of paralysis,'' it warned.
