<FIRST>r w PM-CommunityColleges     04-19 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Community Colleges,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commission Says Community Colleges Get Short Shrift</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's community colleges meet ambivalence about their role and often `` receive the state's budget leftovers'' when they can be of great help both to their neighborhoods and the nation, an educational commission said today. `` The community college, at its best, can be a center for problem-solving in adult illiteracy or the education of the disabled,'' said a report by the <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on the Future of Community Colleges. `` It can also be the place where education and business leaders meet to talk about the problems of displaced workers. `` It can bring together agencies to strengthen services for minorities, working women, single parent heads of households and unwed teenage parents. ... The community college can take the lead in long-range planning for community development and it can serve as the focal point for improving the quality of life in the inner city.'' Community colleges enroll 43 percent of the nation's undergraduates and 51 percent of all first-time freshmen, but the schools `` encounter ambivalence in the larger community about their role and mission, and competing priorities within the college,'' the report said Such schools `` are threatened by excessive fragmentation and division'' and increasing cultural separations and racial tensions, the report said. `` We propose therefore, that the theme ` Building Communities' become the new rallying point for the community college in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> We define the term ` community' not only as a region to be served but also as a climate to be created.'' The commission was headed by <PERSON> Ernest </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Boyer </PERSON>, former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> commissioner of education and president of the <ORGANIZATION> Carnegie </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Teaching. It conducted the study for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> and Junior Colleges. The panel said community colleges must help solve the dropout problem or minority students will continue to leave. It recommended that every college develop an aggressive outreach plan for disadvantaged students. Among other recommendations: _ An `` early warning system'' to spot and help students who are at risk of dropping out. _ Each community college should commit itself to recruiting and retaining a top-quality faculty and increase the percentage of members who are black, Hispanic and Asian. _ Careful assessment of reading, writing and mathematical ability of all first-time community college students and an intensive developmental education program for those who need it _ Completion of a core curriculum by all associate degree students
