<FIRST>r w PM-ATVs     04-19 0561</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-ATVs,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Debates Whether Flawed Ban Is Better Than No Ban At All</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge says he must decide whether to approve a flawed consent decree regulating all-terrain vehicles or do nothing to regulate the vehicles blamed for 900 deaths in five years. `` Is it best to move in the direction of doing what one can do to reduce it as opposed to doing nothing about it?'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Gerhard </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said after a hearing on a proposed out-of-court settlement between the <ORGANIZATION> Consumer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Product </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and five manufacturers. Opponents of the consent decree argued at Monday's hearing that the agreement between federal regulators and manufacturers is flawed because it does n't provide for refunds to people who purchased the vehicles, popularly known as ATVs. Lawyers for consumer groups and 32 states said the consent decree also fails to protect children from the hazards of the four-wheel machines, particularly smaller models marketed for children, which would still be sold. `` We do n't believe these child-sized ATVs should be sold at all,'' said <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Shannon </PERSON>, who called ATVs `` some of the most dangerous consumer products sold in this country.'' The decree would ban future sales of three-wheel ATVs unless the manufacturers devised performance standards that would be approved by the <ORGANIZATION> CPSC </ORGANIZATION>. It would also require warning labels on four-wheel models and distributors would have to offer training about the safe use of the machines to owners of vehicles currently in use. <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> appeared troubled by the decree's ban on further action by the <ORGANIZATION> CPSC </ORGANIZATION> against ATVs during the 10-year period the agreement is in effect. `` The mechanism provided by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> is stymied by the consent decree,'' <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> told a lawyer for the manufacturers. `` As I understand the decree, the agency represented here _ <ORGANIZATION> CPSC </ORGANIZATION> _ is not able to issue a rule under the statute which would be in many respects more severe'' than the sanctions imposed by the consent decree, <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> said. `` You take the agency out of the game, you ca n't tell me with quite the same assurance the agency is going to continue to perform its function,'' the judge said. Sen. <PERSON> Alfonse </PERSON> <PERSON> D'Amato </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, who is sponsoring legislation to force manufacturers to give refunds, called that provision `` a wolf in sheep's clothing.'' The senator urged <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> to modify the decree to give the agency the option of taking further action after a year or 18 months if the agreement has not led to safer use of ATVs. But <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said the agreement allows the government to avoid a lengthy court battle during which it would be difficult to prove the allegations that the ATVs are an `` imminent hazard'' as defined by the consumer protection statute. `` This is an outstanding resolution of the matter in light of the facts as they exist and the law as it exists,'' <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> told <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON>. `` The government will get some of what it asked for, the other alternative is the government will get none of what it asked for.'' <PERSON> Gesell </PERSON> also expressed concern about the mechanics for supervising the decree's enforcement, saying he was particularly dismayed that it empowered the <ORGANIZATION> CPSC </ORGANIZATION>'s general counsel to extend deadlines. Nevertheless, the judge said the unprecedented decree could be `` a technique that could be of great value to consumers.''
