<HEAD>Scallops Make New Bedford Nation's Richest Fish Port</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bedford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, was the nation's richest fishing port last year thanks to a banner year for scallops, government and industry officials say. Other <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> fishing cities slumped because of a decrease in fin fish such as cod and haddock, and some ports around the Gulf of <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> suffered from problems in the shrimp industry, analysts said Monday. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bedford </LOCATION> led in 1987 with catches valued at $ 143.7 million, up nearly 36 percent from $ 106 million in 1986, according to the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Oceanic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atmospheric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>. The 1987 figure was a record, the agency said. <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Weddig </PERSON>, executive vice president of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fisheries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, a trade association, attributed <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bedford </ORGANIZATION>'s big increase to strong scallop harvests and scallop price increases. <ORGANIZATION> NOAA </ORGANIZATION> said scallops accounted for nearly half of <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bedford </ORGANIZATION>'s total dollar value, but made up only 21 percent of the port's catch in weight Alaskan ports also enjoyed a profitable year. <LOCATION> Kodiak </LOCATION> was second to <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bedford </LOCATION> with catches valued at $ 132.1 million, up from $ 89.8 million, and <ORGANIZATION> Dutch </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Harbor-Unalaska </ORGANIZATION> was up from $ 37.2 million to $ 62.7 million, <ORGANIZATION> NOAA </ORGANIZATION> reported. <PERSON> Weddig </PERSON> said the healthy <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION