<HEAD>Trade Lawmakers Deadlock Over Foreign Investment Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Lawmakers are nearing final action on a sweeping, 1,000-page trade bill, still uncertain if it will contain a plan to force public disclosure by foreign investors of their <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> holdings. `` If you're interested in passing a trade bill, which I am, then I think the best course of action is to drop the <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> amendment,'' Sen. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Exon </PERSON>, D-Neb., said Monday after lawmakers failed to break a deadlock over the issue A House-Senate panel has been stalemated for more than a month over the amendment sponsored by Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, which would require public disclosure of much foreign investment within the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> states. <PERSON> Exon </PERSON> said that dropping the plan would reduce the chance of a presidential veto, or if President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> vetoes the bill anyway, increase the chance of an override. He noted there already are presidential veto threats over a separate provision that would require 60-day notice of plant closings and large-scale layoffs. The foreign ownership dispute is the last unresolved controversy in fashioning the trade bill, which <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said could come to the floor as early as Wednesday. Most of the compromise provisions were drawn up by <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> conferees before the congressional recess Easter week but they left farm items, the plant closings feature and the foreign disclosure plan until the last minute. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> told reporters he was pushing for inclusion of the <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> provision. But he added he would not seek to attach the measure to the trade bill if it would `` put its life in jeopardy.'' The speaker said that if conferees would not accept the plan `` I would be inclined to give <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON> a run on its own merits'' by bringing it to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor later as a separate bill. Under the plan, foreign investors would be required to register with the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> if they owned 5 percent or more of any <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> company or real estate in this country if such assets were worth at least $ 5 million. Some of this information already must be filed with the department but is not public record. That would change under <PERSON> Bryant </PERSON>'s plan. Companies with a 25 percent share in a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> business or property with assets or annual sales of more than $ 20 million would have to disclose much of the detailed information required of corporations by the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on its 10-K form. The items range from a list of directors and officers to a financial balance sheet. Critics say the measure would reduce new capital from overseas that helps prime the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic pump; proponents say it would put a spotlight on foreign investment that could be harmful to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> interests. Most lawmakers believe the trade bill itself will clear both the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> without much difficulty. The question is whether it will get the two-thirds support it would need for a veto override. Three major petroleum industry associations called on <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> to sign the bill because it would repeal the windfall profits tax on oil companies. `` We can not allow the stagnation of domestic oil exploration and production to continue,'' the groups said in a letter. The letter was sent by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Independent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Midcontinent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Oil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>.
