<HEAD>Jackson Adjusts Stance On Some Issues; Aide Calls It `Evolution'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> told a business group he favors continued research on the Star Wars missile defense system and then told an <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> audience a few hours later: `` We do not need Star Wars. We need decent housing and education and day care.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Borosage </PERSON>, a top adviser to <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s presidential campaign, said the former civil rights activist has always supported research on Star Wars. But it was not until the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> primary campaign that <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> began to readily discuss his support for that research. `` Keep the research; we do n't need to deploy it,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> told the Association for a <ORGANIZATION> Better </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION>, an organization of business and civic leaders, a few hours before his East Harlem appearance. An even more publicized shift in position was <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s statement that he would not meet with <PERSON> Yasser </PERSON> <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON>, the leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> Ten years ago, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> embraced <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> at a meeting that became a focus of Jewish opposition to his candidacy. During an interview on the CBS show, `` Face the Nation,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> was an `` extreme element'' in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> and that it would be a mistake to negotiate with him. On the same program, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said he had no plans to scrap existing weapons in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arsenal, including many he opposed in the past. Is <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> shifting toward the mainstream as he has become a credible challenger to <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' claim on the Democratic presidential nomination? <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON>, a top <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> adviser, called the shifts part of a `` two-way evolution.'' She said that as <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has been taken more seriously as a presidential candidate he has been asked more substantive policy questions and they have forced him to re-examine many of his views. `` His position on <ORGANIZATION> Star </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wars </ORGANIZATION> has been the same since <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> launched it,'' said <PERSON> Borosage </PERSON>. But he conceded the candidate's stance on any <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> role in <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> negotiations has changed `` He believes you've got to deal with the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Borosage </PERSON>. But, he added, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> also has come to believe that <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> is too `` inciteful'' to be included in peace negotiations. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has explained his earlier meeting with <PERSON> Arafat </PERSON> as an effort to persuade the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> leader to accept <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s right to exist. He repeatedly told <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> audiences that <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> must be guaranteed secure borders. He also has advocated an independent Palestinian state. In the <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> interview, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> also denied having advocated elimination of such systems as the MX missile. `` We've got to keep the systems we have,'' said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. In a letter published in Monday's <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Borosage </PERSON> took issue with a story on <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s views that had appeared in the newspaper. `` Mr. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has never stated he ` would scrap a range of weapons systems' already deployed,'' wrote <PERSON> Borosage </PERSON>. However he went on to say that the candidate would oppose further development of the Stealth bomber `` because we have just spent billions purchasing the B-1 for the same mission.'' In speeches, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> advocates a freeze in the military budget.
