<FIRST>r w BC-Aviation-Glance     04-19 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Aviation-Glance,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>Air Safety Panel Report at a Glance</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Aviation Safety Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are highlights from the report by the President's <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Aviation Safety: _ The nation's air transportation system is `` safe, for now,'' but the government regulatory structure `` designed to ensure aviation safety is inadequate to deal with future growth and technological change.'' _ A `` major structural overhaul'' of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> is needed, making it an independent agency outside the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>. _ An independent aviation `` safety czar'' should be appointed as part of the new <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> and given authority to oversee safety matters. With a seven-year term, the new aviation safety director could initiate new safety rules and block proposed regulations. _ No need has been demonstrated for re-imposing federal regulation of the airline industry, although the government must streamline its regulatory activities to deal with rapidly changing events in a deregulated industry. _ Surveillance of airlines should be improved with heavier reliance on in-depth inspections, surprise inspections and closer examination of airlines undergoing major changes. _ Safety requirements for commuter airlines should elevated gradually to the same level as those for larger commercial airlines. _ Small private planes flying near major airports should be required to have equipment that informs ground controllers of their altitude.
