<BYLINE>By JUAN MALTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The government and rebel leaders adjourned peace talks Monday without reaching agreement after four days, but they agreed to meet again in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> at the end of the month. Gen. <PERSON> Humberto </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, the defense minister and head of the Sandinista government's negotiating team, read a statement signed by both parties saying they would meet in the capital April 28-30 to continue talks on a permanent truce in the 6 -LCB- - year-old war <PERSON> Adolfo </PERSON> <PERSON> Calero </PERSON>, a leader of the rebels known as Contras, told reporters the two sides were `` on the road to an understanding.'' He refused to elaborate on what they discussed during the talks. `` This is n't an automobile race in <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> to run at 200 miles per hour,'' <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said. `` Our interest is to negotiate the definitive cease-fire, but it ca n't be reached overnight, for which we consider that what was discussed here was an advance and not a failure.'' He claimed the rebels' political directorate was being pressured to avoid signing an agreement by the Contra military chief, <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON>. `` Our army will continue clutching their rifles to dissuade the enemies of <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION>, and I'm referring to <PERSON> Enrique </PERSON> <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> and the guerrillas, so that they do n't continue sabotaging the accords,'' <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Sapoa </LOCATION> is the town where the two sides signed a cease-fire agreement last month. President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON>, the defense minister's brother, told a rally Monday night that the Contra political leaders should not cave in to what he said was pressure from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON>. Addressing thousands of Sandinista supporters in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Plaza </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> de </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> la </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolucion </ORGANIZATION>, the president claimed <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON> had told <ORGANIZATION> Contra </ORGANIZATION> political leaders that if they signed a truce with the government the rebels `` would liquidate them.'' He said if the political leaders submit `` to the pressures of the <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION> administration and the threats of <PERSON> Bermudez </PERSON>, they would not continue to come to <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> and if they did it would be to break the Sapoa accords. `` If this happens, it would leave us no other road but to achieve a total victory in the military field.'' Negotiations between the rebels and government have been deadlocked over the so-called `` democratization'' issue. The <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> have insisted the rebels sign a permanent truce immediately. They say Contra delegates would then be allowed to take part in a `` national reconciliation dialogue'' with leaders of the country's 14 legally recognized political parties. Contra leaders are demanding that Sandinistas first carry out a series of democratic reforms, or at least pledge to do so. On Monday afternoon, <PERSON> Contra </PERSON> leader <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> told a cheering crowd the rebels will press for an end to the military draft and the release of thousands of political prisoners. `` We are in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> to negotiate with the Sandinistas the freedom of <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and the restoration of democracy and, as long as we do not achieve this, we will not lay down our weapons,'' <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> told about 800 supporters in the capital. He spoke outside La Prensa before he and other Contra leaders visited the editors of the only opposition newspaper. <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> and five directors of the rebel umbrella group, known as the <ORGANIZATION> Nicaraguan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resistance </ORGANIZATION>, traveled to <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> on Friday to try to negotiate with the government an end to the war that has killed an estimated 26,500 people. It was the first time the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> agreed to negotiate with their foes in the capital. The Contras' 20-minute visit to <PERSON> La </PERSON> <PERSON> Prensa </PERSON> was their first venture outside the Camino Real Hotel where they have been staying. Contra leaders visited with Cardinal <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> Obando </PERSON> y Bravo and other Roman Catholic church officials in the afternoon and said afterward they would free 40 government soldiers. `` At the request of the bishops we have decided to free the Sandinista prisoners that we have in our power as a show of good faith for national reconciliation,'' said <PERSON> Calero </PERSON>, highest-ranking official in the Contra directorate. Official <ORGANIZATION> Voice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nicaragua </ORGANIZATION> radio claimed the Contras had more Sandinista prisoners and releasing only 40 was `` ridiculous in seven years of war.'' The two sides signed a peace agreement March 23 which provided for a temporary cease-fire while they negotiated a permanent truce. The 60-day cease-fire went into effect April 1. The Contras on Monday proposed that the temporary cease-fire be extended another month while both sides seek agreement. There was no immediate response from the government. Soon after the March 23 accord was signed, the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> freed 100 of the 3,300 political prisoners and promised to release the rest as peace negotiations progressed. Among the Contra directors who visited <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> Monday was <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON>, whose mother, <PERSON> Violeta </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON>, is publisher. His publisher father, also named <PERSON> Pedro </PERSON> <PERSON> Joaquin </PERSON> <PERSON> Chamorro </PERSON>, was killed on Jan. 10, 1978. The assassination, widely blamed on the right-wing government in power at the time, unleashed a revolt that toppled President <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON> and swept the Sandinistas into power in July 1979.
