<SECOND>PM-Stock Study,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Program Trading Pushed January 8 Market Plunge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> believes that heavy program trading may have helped force down stock prices last Jan. 8, the day of the third-worst market plunge. In a report released Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> said it has detected high levels of computer-driven transactions late in that day's session, particularly in stocks frequently traded by institutional investors using programs. The Dow Jones Industrial Average plunged 140 points that day. The <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>, using information it obtained from the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, said that 75.4 million of the 197.3 million shares traded that day were sold after 2:30 p.m. Two-thirds of the decline occurred after 2:30 p.m. `` This heavy late selling activity occurred on relatively little fundamental economic news,'' the report said. The report stated that the role in the Jan. 8 plunge of index-related trading _ transactions involving baskets of stocks and futures _ `` was comparable to that during the week preceding Oct. 19.'' That was the day of the worst plunge in the stock market's history, a 508-point Dow Jones decline The study concluded that `` stock selling from index arbitrage may have accelerated the steepest portion of the market decline'' that day after 2:30 p.m. Index arbitrage is a strategy by which institutional traders, usually using computers, attempt to profit from price discrepancies between stocks and stock index futures. It and other forms of so-called program trading, in which computers guide huge transactions, have been called factors in the stock market's wildly surging price swings of recent months. The study said that only 13 percent of the shares traded Jan. 8 were generated by program selling. But more than one-third of the transactions after 2:30 p.m. involving stocks comprising the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500 stock index were made by program traders, the report said. Stocks in the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's index are frequently bought and sold by program traders. The report was released by Rep. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Markey </PERSON>, D-Mass., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> telecommunications and finance subcommittee <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> had requested the study, which was dated April 7 and sent to the congressman by <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruder </PERSON>. `` I am deeply concerned about the impact of this continued volatility on our capital formation process and long-term economic growth,'' <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> said in a prepared statement. <PERSON> Markey </PERSON> has been working on legislation designed to control market volatility.
</TEXT>
