minal after it touched down. <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> and co-pilot <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Hilstad </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> NTSB </ORGANIZATION> investigators Sunday in <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ore. </LOCATION>, that they applied full force to the brakes and locked the emergency brake, but could not avoid ramming the passenger ramp. They also said they pushed hard on the right rudder in an effort to steer the aircraft. The pilots' comments during a closed-door meeting were overheard by reporters outside. The pilots said the fire erupted so quickly they had little time to make an emergency landing. They said they realized they were going too fast and appeared to be coming down too high to adequately slow down, but had no choice except to land. Three of the injured passengers remained hospitalized Monday, including <PERSON> Brian </PERSON> <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON>, 26, of <LOCATION> Clarkston </LOCATION>, who was in serious but stable condition.
