<HEAD>Conviction Strains Relationship Of Ukrainian And Jewish Americans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOROTHY GAST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Supporters of retired autoworker <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> were outraged that <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> judges convicted him as the <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> death camp guard `` Ivan the Terrible,'' and said the decision will rouse anti-Semitism in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>, a Ukrainian immigrant to the <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Seven </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, was convicted Monday in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> of war crimes in connection with the deaths of 850,000 Jews at the <LOCATION> Treblinka </LOCATION> death camp in Nazi-occupied <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in 1942 and 1943. <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacyk </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> resident of Ukrainian descent who helped raise money for <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>, said Monday the effect the verdict has on the world view of the Jewish community will be similar to the `` crucifixion of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON>. `` I think people will be outraged because they know <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> is innocent,'' <PERSON> Jacyk </PERSON> said. `` In the long run, it will have a very negative effect on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and Jews. It will definitely be long-remembered.'' <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>, who could be sentenced to death or life imprisonment when the court reconvenes April 25, has gotten some of his strongest backing from <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> area residents of Ukrainian descent. More than 200 people gathered Sunday at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vladimir </ORGANIZATION>'s Cathedral in <ORGANIZATION> Parma </ORGANIZATION>, a Ukrainian Orthodox church, to pray for <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>, 68, and his family `` It -LRB- the conviction -RRB- is bound to have a negative effect on the American population's view of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Liscynesky </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Parma </ORGANIZATION>, who heads the Cleveland-area <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ukrainian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organizations </ORGANIZATION>. `` The majority of <LOCATION> Americans </LOCATION> feel that <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> is innocent.'' <PERSON> Liscynesky </PERSON> said `` telephones are probably very hot'' spreading the word among local Ukrainians about <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>'s conviction. He said his coalition has about 20,000 active members. There are an estimated 2 million people of Ukrainian descent in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` I understand very well why they -LRB- Ukrainians -RRB- are hurting very badly,'' said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Plax </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> director of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jewish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` It's like when someone gets cut and you yell ` ouch' and you start cursing. That's what they're doing right now. In time I suspect the dust will settle and we'll get back to doing things to bring the two communities together.'' <PERSON> Plax </PERSON> said he was `` profoundly shocked by the sternness of the judges' verdict.'' But a former <LOCATION> Cleveland </LOCATION> lawyer who helped win <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>'s extradition to <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> in 1986 said the conviction did n't surrprise him. `` I think there was no doubt that he was given a fair trial, that every possible defense was raised and thoroughly defended,'' said <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Lodish </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyer who practices in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. `` There can be no doubt who <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> really is.'' <PERSON> Abraham </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Foxman </PERSON>, national director of the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith, hailed the conviction of <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> as `` gratifying evidence that even 40 years after the Holocaust, justice can prevail over evil.'' <PERSON> Foxman </PERSON> said the year-long trial `` reflected <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s commitment to the <ORGANIZATION> democratic </ORGANIZATION> rule of law.'' In <LOCATION> Albany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Rausch </PERSON>, who attended the trial, said on behalf of her local chapter of Holocaust Survivors and Friends in Pursuit of Justice, `` We commend the state of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> for accepting this reponsibility and we hope they will continue to prosecute <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> war criminals who have found haven throughout the world.'' <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Holtzman </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> prosecutor who formerly sponsored legislation in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to allow for deportation of <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> war criminals, said the conviction `` sends the world a signal that Nazi war criminals can not escape.''
