<HEAD>Abortion Rights Advocates Sue To Block Parental Consent Provision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES WEBB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Opponents of new abortion restrictions sued in state and federal courts to head off provisions of a <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> law before it takes effect next week. `` The goal is to block the implementation of the nation's most restrictive abortion control law,'' <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinhardt </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION>, said of the lawsuit filed Monday. `` This law seeks to make an abortion as difficult to obtain as possible, physically, financially and emotionally,'' said <PERSON> Susan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cary </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON>, a lawyer for the Philadelphia-based Women's Law Project. Gov. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> P. </PERSON> <PERSON> Casey </PERSON> is confident the law, which he signed March 25, will stand up in court, said his press secretary, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Grotevant </PERSON>. `` We drafted it with the constitution in mind,'' said <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Viglietta </PERSON>, a spokesman for the anti-abortion <ORGANIZATION> Pennsylvania </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION>. `` It will pass the constitutional muster.'' The law is scheduled to take effect Sunday, but <PERSON> Steinhardt </PERSON> said lawyers would press this week for court injunctions to prevent that. `` We have a number of reasons for believing that this law will not go into effect as scheduled,'' said <PERSON> Steffan </PERSON> <PERSON> Presser </PERSON>, the state <ORGANIZATION> ACLU </ORGANIZATION> legal director. The suit filed in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> challenges the law's requirement that minors obtain parental or judicial consent before abortions The restrictions violate rights of privacy, due process and freedom of association guaranteed by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Constitution </ORGANIZATION> and other federal laws, the suit says. It also challenges reporting requirements that would force clinics and doctors that provide abortions to supply information to the state. Those provisions could open clinics, doctors and women seeking abortions to harassment and potentional violence from anti-abortion activists, Ms. <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> said. A companion suit filed in <ORGANIZATION> Commonwealth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> is aimed at a provision that would require indigent rape and incest victims to report the crimes to law-enforcement agencies before they could receive Medicaid funding for an abortion. The suit was filed on behalf of an unidentified Medicaid recipient who has twice been the victim of rape and was mistreated by police when she reported the crime, the suit says. Additional plaintiffs include Women Organized Against Rape, the <ORGANIZATION> Elizabeth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Blackwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> and the counseling organization, Choice. <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Beliveau </PERSON>, legislative coordinator for the <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pro-Life </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, said the lawsuit seeks to `` allow the abortion industry to keep parents in the dark'' about the health of their children. `` It is inconceivable that pro-abortion groups would challenge legislation that provides parents with the right to supervise the health care of their minor children,'' she added. In 1986, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> struck down key provisions of a 1982 law. Those provisions required doctors to make a record that could be made public of every abortion they performed; required doctors to inform women seeking abortions about potential risks and available benefits for prenatal care and childbirth; and required the presence of two doctors for abortions performed in the third trimester. In December, <PERSON> Casey </PERSON>, a Democrat, vetoed an abortion control bill that would have required notification of sexual partners or parental notification in the case of a minor.
