<HEAD>On Demanjuk Judgment Day, Jews Honor Treblinka Victims</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Demjanjuk, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES J. GANS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TREBLINKA, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The same day an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> court convicted <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> of war crimes, hundreds of Jews visited the <ORGANIZATION> Treblinka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> death camp where 850,000 Jews perished in the gas chambers he helped operate. As a cantor's mournful chant wafted across the vast open field covering the camp's remains, the visitors searched Monday among thousands of jagged memorial stones for the names of the Polish towns where the victims had lived. `` My parents were killed here, my sisters, my brothers, an uncle, an aunt were all killed here,'' said <PERSON> Jakub </PERSON> <PERSON> Silberstein </PERSON>, 64, of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, who was wearing a striped concentration camp inmate's cap `` All I know is that if I had a gun, I would shoot <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> with my own hands,'' <PERSON> Silberstein </PERSON>, a survivor of the <LOCATION> Buchenwald </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Auschwitz </LOCATION> concentration camps, said Monday. The court in <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> ruled on Monday that the Ukrainian-born <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>, a retired <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> autoworker, was the notorious guard `` <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> the Terrible,'' who helped operate the gas chambers at <LOCATION> Treblinka </LOCATION>. The emotional pilgrimage for hundreds of Jews from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and other countries followed observances of the 45th anniversary of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Ghetto Uprising. Accompanying the <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> delegation was <PERSON> Jacek </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilczur </PERSON>, an official with the Polish government's <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> war crimes investigation commission who assisted <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> prosecutors in gathering evidence for <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON>'s trial. `` Being here on this day has a symbolic significance,'' he said. `` It is not a trial of one <PERSON> Demjanjuk </PERSON> -LRB- that is important -RRB-. It's a trial of the German system of homicide.'' On Tuesday, the Jewish visitors followed the last route of the condemned Jews of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Ghetto, traveling to <LOCATION> Treblinka </LOCATION> after dedicating a new memorial at the <LOCATION> Umschlagplatz </LOCATION>, the site near the railroad siding from which 300,000 Jews were deported to Nazi death camps. Traveling by bus, they made the 53-mile trip to <LOCATION> Treblinka </LOCATION>, northeast of <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, in about 1 -LCB- hours. Forty-five years ago, the cattle cars packed with people sometimes took several days to travel the same route. In 1942-43, a whole trainload of people could be undressed, stripped of their belongings and killed in two hours. The 13 gas chambers could kill 2,000 people in 10 to 15 minutes. The <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> razed the camp to the ground after a bloody prisoners' revolt on Aug. 2, 1943, and planted trees to hide the traces of their crimes, which today give the site a strangely serene atmosphere The Polish government is now raising money to build a museum at <LOCATION> Treblinka </LOCATION>, where there is now only a memorial of stones, erected in 1963, built to resemble a symbolic graveyard. At the center of the 23-acre site is a massive granite column, resembling a tombstone, with a menorah, a traditional symbol of <ORGANIZATION> Judaism </ORGANIZATION>, hewn into one side. In front is a stone with the inscription in six languages: `` Never again.'' `` My feet are planted on this land which has mixed on it the ashes of 800,000 Jews who were brought here,'' said <PERSON> Chaika </PERSON> <PERSON> Grosman </PERSON>, a member of the Israeli <ORGANIZATION> Knesset </ORGANIZATION>, or parliament, and survivor of the 1943 Jewish ghetto uprising in the Polish city of <LOCATION> Bialystok </LOCATION>. `` My nation was destroyed before my eyes and I was helpless,'' she said, speaking at a memorial rally in front of the monument that was attended by about 1,000 Jews and Poles. `` I come here from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> as a pilgrim to the graves of my predecessors.'' Deputy Prime Minister <PERSON> Itzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Navon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> said the only positive answer to the Holocaust and <LOCATION> Treblinka </LOCATION> is `` increasing our numbers'' and `` strengthening the state of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>.'' People walked among the 17,000 stones scattered in the field surrounding the memorial column, 130 of which bear the names of Polish cities and towns such as <LOCATION> Biala </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Podlaska </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Ostrow </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON> whose Jewish inhabitants were transported to <LOCATION> Treblinka </LOCATION>. Other stone markers are inscribed with the names of the 10 countries from which Jews were sent here _ <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bulgaria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Czechoslovakia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Some of the Jewish visitors also prayed by an open pit, filled with melted black basalt, which stands in the place where the <ORGANIZATION> Nazis </ORGANIZATION> burned the bodies of their victims. Walking back to the buses on this sunny, warm spring day, with temperatures in the 70s, visitors could hear birds singing in the fir trees surrounding the field of stones, which evoke such terrible memories.
