<HEAD>Banks Reopen For First Time in 45 Days; Only For Deposits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Some Panamanian and foreign banks opened for the first time in 45 days, but only to accept deposits. One banker said the opening simply created the appearance that <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s financial system can recover. Business was brisk on Monday at a few major foreign banks, but slow at institutions owned and operated by Panamanians. The <ORGANIZATION> Panama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> ordered the reopening as a first step in the resumption of full banking services. Banks closed March 3 after a run on deposits, prompted by the ouster of President <PERSON> Eric </PERSON> <PERSON> Arturo </PERSON> <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> which was orchestrated by strongman Gen. <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>. Panamanians have been unable to cash paychecks or gain access to checking accounts since the closing and have conducted business on a cash-only basis. The manager of a foreign bank, speaking on condition his name not be used, said that Monday's limited reopening `` gives the illusion that things are becoming normal. I do n't know whether it will work or not.'' He said the move would `` allow circulation of checks _ reestablish the check as an acceptable payment in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>.'' He noted, however, that clients depositing checks still would not be able to draw cash from their accounts unless the banks resume full services. `` But if you owe money to someone and he will accept a check, you can write a check on your new balance,'' he said. Even such a transaction would be guaranteed only if the partial reopening works as envisioned under a complex set of rules issued by the banking commission. Bankers said customers who made deposits Monday should know by next week if the checks cleared and have been credited to their accounts. Some financial sources predicted the new system would n't work as long as <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s cash crunch continues and the government fails to resolve the political crisis that prompted the collapse of the banking system. The <ORGANIZATION> Panamanian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which represents most of the more than 120 banks doing business in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>, has said repeatedly that its members will not resume full service until the government can assure a steady, adequate supply of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollars, which <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> uses as its official currency. Panamanians began withdrawing large sums of money begining Feb. 26, the day <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> orchestrated the dismissal of <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> for trying to fire him as chief of the armed forces and police. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is the head of the 15,000-strong <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> and the power behind the civilian government. In retaliation, the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration ordered economic sanctions that included the freezing of Panamanian accounts in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> banks and withholding revenues from <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Canal </LOCATION> toll fees. <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> is under federal indictment in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> on drug trafficking charges, and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> recognizes <PERSON> Delvalle </PERSON> as <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s legitimate president. Word of Monday's partial bank reopening had been announced in newspapers through the weekend. About 30 people lined up outside the local office of <LOCATION> Chase </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> before opening time Monday and another 10 were outside the <ORGANIZATION> Citibank </ORGANIZATION> branch. <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s private and government banks, their solvency in question, appeared to be doing far less business. Except for the few who came with cash, customers said they were depositing checks they had accumulated since March 3. Some customers expressed optimism that the limited reopening might lead to the return of normal banking services in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>. `` They're trying something new,'' said <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON>, a former <LOCATION> Chase </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> employee who was depositing checks there. `` I do n't know if it'll work It might. We'll give it a try.'' But <PERSON> Farrell </PERSON>, like most others, was being cautious. `` Ill keep my cash at home. Later on, maybe, I'll deposit cash.'' A middle-aged Panamanian woman in the same line said she also was depositing only checks. `` I need the cash to eat,'' she said.
