<HEAD>Tibet Remains Closed To Individual Travelers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Chinese authorities do not plan to reopen <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> to the thousands of backpackers who streamed through before pro-independence protests began last year, a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official said. `` The thrust of the message is <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> is open and they intend to keep it open but they intend to keep it -LRB- travel -RRB- in groups,'' said <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Stapleton </PERSON> <PERSON> Roy </PERSON>, deputy assistant secretary of state, on Monday. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> said that in talks with authorities during a four-day visit to <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>, they did `` not rule out'' the possibility of further unrest in the region's capital, <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION>. He said he carried no message from the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government but expressed concern for human rights in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> and pressed authorities to allow more journalists and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> congressmen to visit. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> said he did not discuss Chinese conditions for the return of the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>'s spiritual and former political leader, who fled to <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> in 1959. Individual travel into <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> officially was halted shortly after three protests in September and October by <ORGANIZATION> Buddhist </ORGANIZATION> monks and others opposed to Chinese rule. Enforcement of the provision that all tourists to <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> join guided tour groups slackened early this year but has tightened since a protest March 5 in which at least five people died. Chinese authorities alleged after the protests in September and October that some foreigners joined in or encouraged participants. In 1987, 43,500 foreigners visited <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>, spending $ 15 million, according to official figures. Many arrived individually from <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION> in southwest <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> or overland from <LOCATION> Nepal </LOCATION>, which borders <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> said authorities told him future travelers would be required to travel in groups charging at least $ 27 per day for expenses. Such a restriction probably will discourage travel by youthful backpackers on tight budgets who in the past often spent one or two months at a time in <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> mingling with Tibetans without close official supervision. He said there were `` at most a handful'' of foreigners in <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> while he was there, Wednesday through Sunday. The Western-managed Lhasa Hotel, with 476 rooms, has had only about two dozen guests at a time since the protests began, he said. Nevertheless, <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> said local authorities claimed tourism had increased 133 percent in the first quarter of 1988, with 1,184 visitors. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> was not heavily patrolled by armed police, and he encountered no roadblocks. `` The general impression is one of surface normality, but you did n't have to dig deep to find views that there was ... potential for future problems,'' he said. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> said that when he raised the issue of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> concern over reported human rights violations in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>, `` the response was that we and the Chinese have differing views on the human rights question.'' <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has denounced any criticism of its human rights policy as interference in its internal affairs. It acknowledges holding some political prisoners in <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>, but denies charges they are mistreated or that religious rights are not respected. <PERSON> Roy </PERSON> said authorities responded positively to his request that more <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> congressmen be allowed to visit <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION>. Four visited <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> on April 7. He said officials told him journalists were allowed to visit if they apply for permission. In practice, almost all reporters' requests to visit <LOCATION> Lhasa </LOCATION> have been denied since last year's protests, when 14 foreign journalists were expelled from Chinese Communist troops entered <LOCATION> Tibet </LOCATION> in 1950, ending a theocracy headed by the <PERSON> Dalai </PERSON> <PERSON> Lama </PERSON>.
