 said. The hope for senators is that the public will make a candidate the inevitable nominee soon so the super delegates can simply ratify the popular choice. With few primaries left, a big win for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in today's <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> contest could lead many senators to conclude that the public choice has been made. `` I think if <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> manages to win ... the political conditions will be created for the vast bulk of super delegates to end up in the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> camp in time for a first-ballot victory,'' said <PERSON> Mann </PERSON>. `` If he wins the primary by a significant margin, it's all over,'' said <PERSON> Baucus </PERSON>. What if <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> surprises <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>? `` They're going to keep their powder dry certainly until the convention,'' <PERSON> Mann </PERSON> said. -- - EDITOR'S NOTE _ <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> Komarow </PERSON> covers politics in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for the <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>.
