<HEAD>Dollar Slightly Higher In Europe, Gold Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The dollar rose slightly in early European trading today as markets awaited developments in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. Gold prices were lower. Foreign exchange dealers said Monday's initial flurry of dollar-buying in response to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Iranian attacks in the gulf had calmed down. But one dealer at a major West German bank in <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> said any new reports or rumors of clashes were likely to boost the dollar significantly. Otherwise, traders said, the market's underlying bearishness toward the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> currency would likely reassert itself. In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends before <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar rose 0.59 yen to a closing 124.37 yen. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted fractionally lower at 124.35 yen. Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday's rates: _ 1.6624 West German marks, up from 1.6615 _ 1.3755 Swiss francs, up from 1.3745 _ 5.6495 French francs, up from 5.6410 _ 1.86495 Dutch guilders, up from 1.8630 _ 1,236.25 Italian lire, up from 1,234.37 _ 1.2335 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2322 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, the British pound fell back from It cost $ 1.8915 to buy one pound, cheaper than late Monday's $ 1.9015. Bullion dealers said trading was quiet as gold prices eased in response to the dollar's slight gains. Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 457.75 a troy ounce and at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 456.55. Both were down from Monday's late bid of $ 459.25. In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 456.75, down from $ 458.50 late Monday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell 39 cents to close at a bid $ 457.59. Silver also fell in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> where it was selling a bid price of $ 6.42 a troy o