<HEAD>Polish Officials, Israelis Honor Ghetto Fighters</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of people from around the world joined Polish officials today in offering flowers and prayers to the memory of fallen anti-Nazi warriors of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Jewish Ghetto Uprising. The 45th anniversary ceremony took place on a broad plaza in front of the Ghetto Fighters Monument in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, where the sounds of gunfire echoed on the morning of April 19, 1943. Heavily armed squadrons of German Nazi troops that day entered the walled Jewish quarter bent on quick, final annihilation of the last 70,000 inhabitants. Instead, they were routed, and the starving, poorly armed residents held off Nazi troops for three more weeks. `` We have to remember, yes, but not a paralyzing memory,'' <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> Deputy Prime Minister <PERSON> Itzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Navon </PERSON> told the crowd of about 4,000 people in English. `` Not only remember the past, but we should derive a new determination from that tragedy to continue living.'' <PERSON> Navon </PERSON>, whose visit to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> is considered private, expressed thanks to Polish authorities for the ceremony. The two countries do not have full-fledged diplomatic relations. Six million Jews were put to death in the World War II Holocaust, 3 million of them Polish. Earlier today, about 100 Arab and African students carrying <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> flags briefly marched through the city, also to commemorate the Ghetto fighters. The students drew parallels between the ghetto battles and the 4 -LCB- - month-old Palestinian uprising in the Israeli-occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION> The protesters distributed leaflets to passers-by, recounting what they said were Israeli cruelties. Before the official ceremony, <PERSON> Henryk </PERSON> <PERSON> Jablonski </PERSON>, chairman of the Polish veteran organization Zbowid which organized the observance, planted an oak tree on the plaza as a symbol of hope. Then, to the beat of military drums, delegations from veterans, Jewish, and Polish groups laid wreath after wreath of flowers at the foot of the monument, a relief of armed fighters crouched together facing their foes. The monument, near the city's heart, was the first erected on the destroyed left bank of <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> after the war. As Poles and Israelis stood side by side around the square, a cantor sang Kaddish, the Jewish song of mourning. Rabbi <PERSON> Isser </PERSON> <PERSON> Frankel </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION> prayed for the victims of the ghetto and the Nazi Holocaust in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Later, when the Polish officials and military honor guard withdrew, Israelis in the crowd burst into singing of their national anthem. About 3,000 people from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and around the world came to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> for the observance week, which began Thursday.
