<HEAD>Court Makes it Easier to Recover Debts Owed by Dead People in
Oklahoma Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today made it easier for creditors to recover debts owed by dead people. The justices, voting 8-1, revived a claim by an <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> bill collection agency that said it unfairly was denied the chance to recover part of a hospital bill owed by a former patient who died. The agency, <ORGANIZATION> Tulsa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Professional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Collection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, is seeking to collect $ 14,657 from the family of the late <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Everett </PERSON> <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>. <PERSON> Pope </PERSON> ran up a $ 142,000 bill at <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> John </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION> from Nov. 23, 1978, until he died the following April 2 Insurance covered all but the amount sought by the bill collector. <PERSON> Pope </PERSON>'s family published a newspaper notice to creditors after his will was admitted to probate in July 1979. <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> law requires that any creditor claiming money from an estate file such a claim within two months of the probate notice. <ORGANIZATION> Tulsa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Professional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Collection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, which missed the deadline, said it was denied due process because it was not notified directly of the probate proceedings. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today said the agency has a legitimate case. Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, in her opinion for the court, said if the Pope family knew about the collection agency or could have determined its identity by a reasonable effort it was required to notify the creditor directly _ by mail, for example _ about the probate proceedings. The court set aside a decision by the <ORGANIZATION> Oklahoma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in favor of the Pope family and ordered further lower court proceedings to determine whether the Pope family knew the collection agency was owed money or whether the agency's identity was `` reasonably ascertainable.'' Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> dissented. The case is <ORGANIZATION> Tulsa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Professional </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Collection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> vs. <PERSON> Pope </PERSON>, 86-1961.
