<HEAD>Judges Unhappy With Proposed Sentencing Guidelines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 New guidelines designed to eliminate disparity in sentencing will deprive judges of their independence, say some federal jurists who met to consider the issue. The <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. Sentencing Commission, organized in 1984 as an arm of the federal judiciary, adopted the sweeping guidelines last November in an attempt to end the disparities in criminal sentencing. `` They're cold and implacable and as immutable as a computer,'' said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Ideman </PERSON>, one of 20 federal judges who met Monday. <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Purdy </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, representing the commission, said the guidelines were developed to increase respect for the law by ensuring that defendants are sentenced fairly. He cited a 1974 study of 50 judges that found sentences for the same crime ranged from three to 20 years. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> will make the final determination on the guidelines. Several of the judges expressed irritation at the notion of any independent commission fixing sentencing options for federal judges. The guidelines, proposed at <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>' direction, established a range of penalties for all federal crimes that occurred after Nov. 1. Minimum and maximum penalties do not vary more than 25 percent and judges are n't permitted to deviate unless a case involves factors not considered by the commission. The controversial guidelines have prompted divided opinions from district judges throughout the country. Opponents have argued that the commission, as an arm of the judicial branch, did not have authority to assume what has been a function of the legislative branch. `` What it does is it destroys all the discretionary function of a judge and it gives an opportunity for prosecutorial misbehavior,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Dickran </PERSON> <PERSON> Tevrizian </PERSON> said Monday.
