<HEAD>Court Rules Against Minnesota Welfare Recipients</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> today ruled against a group of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> welfare recipients who said they were given inadequate notice about a change in their eligibility for federal benefits. The court, voting 5-3, said states are not required to provide advance written notice about the effects of 1981 changes in eligibility requirements of the Aid to Families with Dependent Children program. Under the AFDC program, states determine a family's eligibility after calculating its income and resources. Prior to 1981, when an AFDC recipient received a lump sum of money from any source _ such as an insurance settlement or lottery winnings _ the money was treated as income in the month received and as resources in succeeding months. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in 1981 changed that policy in an attempt to discourage quick spending of windfalls, providing that lump-sum income is to be prorated over a period of months. The change generally limits the eligibility after a family receives lump-sum income. A group of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> women who receive <ORGANIZATION> AFDC </ORGANIZATION> benefits sued state authorities in 1983, contending that they were not given advance notice about the lump-sum rule or the 1981 change in that rule. A 37-year-old <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> woman, <PERSON> Kathryn </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, is the lone remaining named plaintiff in the `` class action'' lawsuit. In October 1983, the <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> family received a $ 5,752 disability check. <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> bus driver, wrote checks the same day to cover back mortgage payments and an overdue car-repair bill. The family also spent about $ 600 on children's clothing and other items. Although the disability payment was quickly spent, the <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON> family was declared ineligible for <ORGANIZATION> AFDC </ORGANIZATION> benefits for eight months. The 8th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled in late 1986 that imposition of the lump-sum rule on the <ORGANIZATION> Jenkinses </ORGANIZATION> was unfair because no advance notice of the 1981 rule change had been received. Today, the nation's highest court disagreed and gave <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> authorities a legal victory by reversing the appeals court ruling on what a federal notice regulation requires. `` The regulation simply requires the state to publish a general description of the basic structure of the <ORGANIZATION> AFDC </ORGANIZATION> program and its availability,'' Justice <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Stevens </PERSON> wrote for the court. He was joined by Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON>, <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON>, <PERSON> Harry </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Blackmun </PERSON> and <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON>. Justices <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON>, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Thurgood </PERSON> <PERSON> Marshall </PERSON> dissented. Writing for the three, <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> said she thought the disputed notice regulation `` requires the -LRB- <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> -RRB- Department -LRB- of Human Services -RRB- to give applicants for AFDC benefits written notice at least of the existence of the lump-sum rule and of the need for recipients to consult with a social worker before spending any lump sum they might receive.'' Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> did not participate in the case. The case is Gardebring vs. <PERSON> Jenkins </PERSON>, 86-978.
