<TEXT>
 Band leader <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>'s career might not have been quite as successful had the founders of this <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> city picked a different name 150 years ago. After all, `` Pardon me, boy, is that the <LOCATION> Montevideo </LOCATION> choo choo?'' does n't really sing, does it? <LOCATION> Montevideo </LOCATION> was one of several possibilities considered by land commissioners when they were naming the new town at <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>'s Landing in 1838, says <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Livingood </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> Hamilton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> historian. Other nominees were Lookout City, <ORGANIZATION> Albion </ORGANIZATION> and the eventual winner, the Cherokee Indian word for `` rock coming to a point,'' a reference to Lookout Mountain. `` There was spirited debate,'' <PERSON> Livingood </PERSON> said Sunday during a program marking <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION>'s 150th birthday. The commissioners settled on <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Livingood </PERSON> said, because one observer noted that although the sound of the name was perhaps outlandish, the city's success would make the name `` pleasant and familiar, and, besides, there will be not another like it anywhere in the world.'' That prediction did n't exactly pan out _ there is a town in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> with the same name _ but <LOCATION> Chattanooga </LOCATION> has come a long way in the last century and a half, say those who have governed it in recent years.
