<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are the methods for picking delegates from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to attend the 1988 Democratic and Republican national conventions this summer.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DEMOCRATS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Method: Primary Date: Tuesday, April 19 Presidential filing deadline: Thursday, March 3, 1988 Pledged delegates :255 Super delegates: 20 TOTAL: 275 Delegates allocated: Tuesday, April 19 Selection of delegates: Dates not yet determined <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Democrats hold a direct-election primary to pick 167 pledged national convention delegates from congressional districts. The state's remaining 88 pledged national convention delegates will be allocated among presidential candidates in proportion to the results of the April 19 primary. Those delegates would be picked by the state committee at a meeting to be held between May 15 and June 14. Candidates for those slots have to file a statement of candidacy no later than five days before the state committee meeting.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>REPUBLICANS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
 Method: Primary Date: Tuesday, April 19 Presidential filing deadline: Thursday, March 3, 1988 Delegates: 136 Delegates allocated: Tuesday, April 19 and a date not yet determined. Selection of delegates: Dates not yet determined. <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Republicans elect 102 of their national convention delegates directly from the April 19 primary ballot. These delegates, three of whom are elected from each of 34 congressional districts, are pledged to a presidential candidate or they run uncommitted. The remaining 34 delegates from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> serve at large and are picked by the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. The date has not yet been determined.
