<FIRST>r w AM-NursingHomeInsurance     04-19 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nursing Home Insurance,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumer Reports: Nursing Home Insurance Not a Good Buy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Insurance to cover the costs of nursing home care has been promoted increasingly in the last few years, but probably is n't a good buy for most Americans, a national consumer group said Tuesday. And anyone considering such coverage should study the policy carefully, Consumers Union warned. Even insurance sales representatives are confused about what coverage is being offered, officials of the group said at a news conference. Consumers Union rates more than 50 long-term care policies in the May edition of its magazine, Consumer Reports, and finds some fault with every one of them. `` The private insurance system can not spread its costs over a large enough number of people to make coverage affordable to the millions who need it,'' Consumers Union President <PERSON> Rhoda </PERSON> <PERSON> Karpatkin </PERSON> said. Only the federal government can do that, she said, calling for congressional action to provide long-term care protection. <PERSON> Gail </PERSON> <PERSON> Shearer </PERSON> of the consumers group said policies providing long-term care are quite expensive and are not recommended for people of moderate income. Prices can range as high as $ 100 a month to $ 260 a month. And people under 60 should n't buy such policies unless there is some guarantee that benefits will rise to keep pace with inflation, Ms. <PERSON> Shearer </PERSON> added. Nonetheless, many policies are being offered and some people may be tempted to buy them, she said. Problems to watch out for include: _ Protection may not be available to people who need it most _ those with health problems already Check policies for exclusions that disallow coverage for pre-existing conditions. _ Some policies were found to cover only certain types of care, but not custodial care, potentially the longest and most costly type _ More than half of all nursing home patients are admitted without having been hospitalized first, but a majority of the long-term care policies checked required prior hospitalization before benefits could be provided _ Alzheimer's disease accounts for half of all nursing home patients, yet a majority of the policies did not specifically state that it was covered A company flooded with claims could decide to use the vague language of its policies to exclude Alzheimer's coverage, Consumers Union warned. In addition, the group noted that some policies require a confirmed diagnosis to provide coverage, and Alzheimer's can not always be confirmed except by autopsy.
</TEXT>
