<HEAD>Pope Urges Religious Freedom for Ukrainian Catholics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> on Tuesday called for religious freedom for Ukrainian Catholics in a letter marking the 1,000 anniversary of Christianity in what is now the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. `` No one ought to consider membership in the <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> as incompatible with the good of the homeland and with the heritage of Saint <PERSON> Vladmir </PERSON>,'' the <PERSON> pope </PERSON> said in a letter to Ukrainian Catholics around the world. Prince <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> introduced Christianity in Kievan Rus', the ancient name of the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION>, with a mass baptism on the banks of the <LOCATION> Dnieper </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in 988. The Ukrainian church was suppressed in 1946 by Soviet dictator <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> Stalin </PERSON>, who ordered it absorbed into the Russian Orthodox church. Ukrainian priests who refused to accept the state-dominated Orthodox church were shot or imprisoned, according to church historians. Today, Eastern Rite Ukrainian Catholics make up the largest underground church in the officially atheist <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. Ukrainian clerics say there are up to 4 million Ukrainian Catholics in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, including 10 secret bishops and more than 100 priests. Another 1.5 million Ukrainian Catholics live abroad. The pope, who has often expressed his desire to visit the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> but has not been invited, said he would instead make a `` spiritual pilgrimage'' to the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> for the millennium. The pope's letter was addressed to Cardinal <PERSON> Myroslav </PERSON> <PERSON> Ivan </PERSON> <PERSON> Lubachivsky </PERSON>, the Rome-based leader of Ukrainian Catholics, Ukrainian bishops and `` all the Ukrainian priests, religious and faithful.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> said the Ukrainian church `` has been tried by such great adversity in recent decades.'' `` May your great numbers of faithful enjoy true freedom of conscience and respect for their religious right to give public worship to God,'' the pontiff wrote. He said the main celebrations for the millennium would be held in <LOCATION> Rome </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Vatican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> has said the observance will include a Mass celebrated by the pope and Ukrainian bishops in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peter </LOCATION>'s Basilica on July 10 Last month, the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> announced the Russian Orthodox Church had invited the pope to send a <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION> delegation to attend the official millennium celebrations in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>. It said the pope would appoint the delegation for the trip to <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> in June. The pope has said he would visit the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> only if he is allowed to visit Catholics throughout the country, including the <LOCATION> Ukraine </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>.
