picks up 3rd graf pvs, ``Chrysler workers xxx; Version moved on
business wire</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> negotiators asked the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> today to support the automaker's efforts to organize plant workers into teams and help avoid increased assembly costs. The team plan would allow <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> greater flexibility in using different workers for different jobs, Vice President <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> said after a second morning of meetings with the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> on a new contract. St. <PERSON> John </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's No. 3 automaker, wants modifications to a pattern contract adopted last year at <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> to help avoid cost increases. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> wants to set a minimum retirement age to keep more workers active in their prime and increase the ratio of active workers to retirees. <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> workers now retire as early as age 48. Adopting a minimum retirement age, as well as encouraging workers to join prepaid health care plans, would help keep <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s per-car production cost from going as much as $ 3.50 above <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s, St. <PERSON> John </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Barbee </PERSON> said the union had no immediate comment on <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s proposals. On Monday, <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s senior executives will forgo bonuses in years when the No. 3 automaker earns too little to share profits with workers. The announcement came as the sides opened early talks on a contract covering 66,000 workers in 15 states. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> workers have no profit-sharing formula under the current contract, which expires Sept. 14. But union and company officials agree they will adopt an industry-pattern agreement established last fall at <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> that contains profit-sharing. Union officials will study St. <PERSON> John </PERSON>'s announcement before commenting, <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Laarman </PERSON> said, calling it `` a free gift, the kind you have to look at real close.'' <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> leaders have blasted <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest automaker, for paying millions of dollars in cash bonuses or stock awards to executives in the past two years while saying its earnings were insufficient to distribute profits to workers `` There is a public perception that it is unfair _ and we tend to agree with that,'' <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> said. `` In any year where profit-sharing payments are not made to <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> employees, the annual senior executive bonuses will also not be paid. We intend to work through that issue in a commitment form with the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION>,'' he said. St. <PERSON> John </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Owen </PERSON> <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> said they hope to reach a contract settlement in two to three weeks. Union bargainers presented their demands Monday. Company negotiators were scheduled to present proposals today before the release of a company proxy statement likely to show that <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> again exercised stock options granted in the early 1980s, when <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s stock was worth a fraction of its present value. In 1986, <PERSON> Iacocca </PERSON> earned more than $ 20 million in salary, benefits and exercised stock options. The pattern contract's profit-sharing formula resulted in a record $ 636 million distributed among 156,000 <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> workers last year. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> profit-sharing checks averaged about $ 4,000 per worker. <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> said pattern bargaining `` has always served our membership very well. It has been a stabilizing force within the companies and between them.'' <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> John </PERSON> also said <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> wants to set up a committee of union and company officials and outside participants to track the new contract's ability to protect jobs and increase efficiency and quality at <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> plants. The committee's findings would be used in drawing up a new contract in 1990, St. <PERSON> John </PERSON> said, apparently indicating <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> will agree to the union's demand for a two-year contract. <PERSON> Bieber </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> Vice President <PERSON> Marc </PERSON> <PERSON> Stepp </PERSON> said they want to put <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s contract expiration back in synch with the <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> pacts so that in 1990, all three will expire together for the first time in a decade. The talks, which normally would begin in mid-July, cover wages, benefits and working conditions. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> contract covers 51,600 hourly, 5,600 sal