has been resisting demands by management that it take significant wage concessions. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Bakes </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, said that he is confident the federal investigation of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> will conclude the airline is being operated safely. He said federal inspectors have examined all of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s jets at least once since the probe was announced last week and some planes have been examined five or six times as they operate in and out of different airports. Bakes accused the unions of a `` slanderous safety campaign'' which he said has been a `` major factor'' in recent financial losses by the airline. While some Eastern jets have been taken out of service after the inspections, he characterized such actions as routine and `` proof that the system is working.'' `` Everyday planes are being taken out of service'' briefly as part of the airline's normal operations when they have mechanical or other problems. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>, the country's largest airline company, has been reeling from a series of inspections announced last week by the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> into safety at the two airlines and the parent holding company's management and finances. The news conference also was attended by two members of <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors and by <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Borman </PERSON>, who was Eastern's chairman before the airline was sold to <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> in 1986 and now remains on <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors All of the executives blamed the labor turmoil at Eastern for creating `` an atmosphere'' which prompted the unusual scrutiny