<SECOND>AM-Shuttle Test,0558</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thiokol, NASA Enter Final Test Phase Before Shuttle Flights Resume</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The third full-scale firing of a redesigned solid fuel booster rocket for the space shuttle was scheduled for Wednesday with deliberate flaws built in to test safety features. The two-minute firing of the 126-foot-long, 1.2 million-pound booster was scheduled for 3 p.m. EDT at <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION>'s Wasatch Operations plant 25 miles west of <LOCATION> Brigham </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. `` This is a really important milestone in the resumption of flight,'' said company spokesman <PERSON> Rocky </PERSON> <PERSON> Raab </PERSON>. `` In a sense, it's the culmination of the redesign effort of two years. If all three of the -LRB- final -RRB- tests proceed satisfactorily, the launch preparations proceed.'' The horizontal test is designed to reveal any weaknesses in booster, which was redesigned after the Jan. 28, 1986, explosion of the shuttle Challenger. The disaster, which killed Challenger's seven-member crew, was blamed on a flawed booster rocket seal that allowed blazing exhaust to escape through a joint in the side and ignite the shuttle's external liquid fuel tank Wednesday's test is the first in the last series of firings planned by <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> before the shuttle's first post-Challenger launch, scheduled for mid-August. Other full-scale tests are scheduled for June and July. The rocket for Wednesday's test was assembled with deliberate flaws in sealing material in the joints between segments of the booster. Flawed seals have been tested previously in short-duration tests, but never in a full-scale firing, <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> said. In one joint, a defect was cut into the surface of a J-shaped seal where sections of insulation meet inside the rocket casing. The defect could let hot gas penetrate the insulation and hit the innermost of three O-rings. In the short-duration tests, the defect sealed itself during firing and gas did not reach the O-ring. In another joint a small `` blowhole'' was created in the adhesive that binds the insulation to the rocket casing. In short-duration tests, hot gases have followed the blowhole to a new O-ring, but have not gone beyond it. The test comes at a critical time for <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION>. The company is <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION>'s sole supplier of booster rockets, and views a successful launch as a sign the stigma of the Challenger tragedy can be set aside. While praising <PERSON> Morton </PERSON> <PERSON> Thiokol </PERSON>'s work in the redesign effort, <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> also has asked <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for a $ 1.2 million government plant to build its own boosters. Though not related to the shuttle program, the company's image also was tarnished by the deaths of five employees in a Dec. 29 fire that destroyed a first-stage MX missile rocket motor. State safety inspectors cited <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> for alleged safety violations, which are being contested by the company. But both <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Force </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Morton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Thiokol </ORGANIZATION> investigators concluded the workers violated company safety rules by being in the building during a critical stage of the fueling process that normally is carried out by remote control. <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> said confidence at the company remains high. `` The morale here is extremely good as far as the redesign and success we've had to date,'' <PERSON> Raab </PERSON> said. `` What most people do n't realize is this redesign effort is about three times as intricate as the original design process, and is being completed in half the time.
