<HEAD>Authorities Offer Evidence In RFK Assassination</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: Leads with 6 grafs to update with formal release of material,
picking up 6th graf pvs, ``Among the xxx</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A polka dot dress, bullets taken from victims and a hand-scrawled notation that `` RFK must die'' were among pieces of evidence put on display today as officials opened secret records on the assassination of <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. The exhibits mounted on boards and in glass cases were samples of the voluminous files examined by state archivists and were put on display to illustrate key points in the investigation as authorities released the material. The police files on <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s shooting could shed new light on persistent questions about whether <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bishara </PERSON> <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON> was the only gunman in the shooting. Was <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> shot from in front or behind? Were there eight shots or more in the pantry of the Ambassador Hotel? And how close was the gunman whose bullet found its fatal path into <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s brain? Those questions and others raised by conspiracy theorists and scholars may be addressed in some 50,000 pages of documents, interviews with 4,000 witnesses, and 2,500 photographs being released today by <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Secretary of State March <PERSON> Fong </PERSON> <PERSON> Eu </PERSON>. `` It has been almost 20 years since that awful night at the Ambassador -LRB- Hotel -RRB-, a night which ended one life and changed so many others,'' <PERSON> Eu </PERSON> said as she formally ordered the materials made public. Among the disputed facts verified by the documents was an admission by police that they destroyed key evidence in the case, including ceiling tiles, a door jamb and thousands of photographs taken in the Ambassador Hotel kitchen where <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> was shot on June 5, 1968. An official record in the evidence showed that 2,410 photographs were burned on Aug. 21, 1968. It gives no reason for their burning. The polka dot dress was one of many purchased by police in an effort to jog the memories of witnesses on a point of contention _ whether a girl in a polka dot dress was seen running from the Ambassador Hotel shouting, `` We shot him.'' That report was never verified. One entire case of evidence contained items from Sirhan's <LOCATION> Pasadena </LOCATION> home Among the items was the now-famous diary in which <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON> scrawled in pencil his plans to kill the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> senator. `` My determination to eliminate RFK is becoming more the more of an unshakeable obsession,'' he wrote. Under a series of doodles was the statement, `` RFK must die.'' Also included was sign-in sheet from a <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gabriel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> gun club which showed that <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON> visited there on June 4, 1968. The key question is whether <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON>, a Jordanian immigrant serving a life sentence for the crime, was the lone assassin of the Democratic presidential hopeful. On the eve of the release of the files, <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON>'s attorney, <PERSON> Luke </PERSON> <PERSON> McKissack </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON> expects nothing to contradict his frequently-stated claim that he was a lone gunman. <PERSON> McKissack </PERSON> said that although <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON> maintains he does n't remember shooting <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON> believes he was motivated by anger over the Arab loss in the 1967 Arab-Israeli war <PERSON> McKissack </PERSON> said that <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON>, who is serving his sentence at <LOCATION> Soledad </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Prison </LOCATION>, has given up hope that he will ever be paroled. Eu and <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Archivist <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> say they hope the release of the <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> investigative file will satisfy the public's right to know everything about the event. `` There should no longer be any speculation about what the police found,'' <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> said. The release follows years of demands for public access to the information. `` This is a kind of vindication of citizens' efforts to force this material out,'' said <PERSON> Gregory </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON>, a political scientist on leave from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wisconsin </ORGANIZATION> who has devoted himself to studying <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s killing. Stone equated its importance with the 1964 publication of the <ORGANIZATION> Warren </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'s investigation of the assassination of President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s brother. The only things withheld from disclosure, <LOCATION> Eu </LOCATION> said, were autopsy photos, criminal `` rap sheets'' and fingerprint cards, juvenile case records, internal police personnel records and records that originated with the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> or police departments outside <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION>'. <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> would release its own file at an unspecified time. <ORGANIZATION> Eu </ORGANIZATION>'s spokeswoman, <PERSON> Melissa </PERSON> <PERSON> Warren </PERSON>, said her office had been inundated with calls since announcing the impending release, including many from <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s home state, and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, which he represented as a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> senator. A summary of <ORGANIZATION> Los </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Angeles </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Police </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> files released in 1986 contained a police conclusion tht <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON> was the lone assassin. It found no evidence of a second gunman or a conspiracy. <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON> admitted the killing at his 1969 trial but has claimed he has no memory of the actual shooting. He blames his memory loss on alcohol. Names and details considered sensitive at the time were deleted from the 1986 summary. It did not fully address questions raised about forensic evidence involving the gun, autopsy reports and witness recollections. Witnesses told of seeing <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON> step from behind a steam table into <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>'s path as the senator walked toward him. But <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Coroner <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Noguchi </PERSON> testified at <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON>'s trial that <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> was killed by a shot fired behind his right ear. Conspiracy theorists suggested that a second gunman fired at Kennedy from behind while <PERSON> Sirhan </PERSON> stood in front of him.
