TION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> to spend the day. <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> was a distant third in public opinion surveys, despite a costly effort designed to reinvigorate a campaign that has been moribund since Super Tuesday six weeks ago. He spent primary morning campaigning in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> as aides passed the word that they expected the senator to gain less than 10 percent of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> vote _ a performance that would raise questions about his ability to continue. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, normally the most cautious of candidates, predicted in the final hours of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> campaign that he would score a victory that would place him firmly on the path toward the nomination. `` It's been a terrific, exciting, interesting couple of weeks and I hope if all goes well today, a sign of things to come,'' he said. Interesting hardly began to describe the multi-million dollar campaign to appeal to the state's many and far-flung ethnic and religious groups. The state's two prominent Democrats captured their share of the limelight: <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> endorsed <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> when he was n't attacking <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, and Gov <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON> declined to endorse anyone while finally ruling out accepting a draft.
