<HEAD>Lyng No Direct Link Between Reagan Veto, Canadian Trade Accord</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> might veto a massive trade bill now before <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, but that action would n't directly affect the free-trade agreement between the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said Tuesday. `` There's nothing that tells me that they're connected,'' <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said. If there is a veto of the sweeping trade bill, <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s veto message would `` describe some reasons that have nothing whatsoever to do with the free trade agreement with <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, as far as I can see.'' Lawmakers are near final action on the 1,000-page trade bill, but there have been veto threats over parts the administration find objectionable, including a provision that would require 60-day notice of plant closings and large-scale layoffs. The U.S.-Canada trade pact was signed Jan. 2 but still requires approval by the Canadian parliament and the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. If approved, the treaty will take effect Jan. 1, 1989, and will gradually eliminate all tariffs between the two countries and address non-tariff barriers. According to the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, U.S-Canada trade was about $ 124 billion in 1986, of which $ 4.6 billion was agricultural. <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> appeared at a news conference with Canadian minister of agriculture, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wise </PERSON>, following private discussions. Wise said he was pleased by <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON>'s view of the trade bill and said there is `` the absolute need and the absolute necessity for us to join forces'' in ongoing global talks under the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, or <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>. `` In fact, I think, were it not for the leadership taken by <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> ... we probably would n't be at the stage that we are now in the <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> Round of multinational trade negotiations,'' Wise said. Both he and <PERSON> Lyng </PERSON> said the U.S.-Canada free-trade agreement would help push the cause of global reform. `` It would be extremely helpful, I think, to both of us, in sending a very legitimate and a very concrete message to our other trading partners, particularly at <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>,'' Wise said. In a joint statement later, the two agricultural leaders pledged to work together `` to ensure that the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> ministerial meeting in May and the <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> economic summit in June provide the necessary political impetus'' for a midterm review of the <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Round </LOCATION> next December in <LOCATION> Montreal </LOCATION>.
