<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A Soviet newspaper on Tuesday blamed high infant mortality in the Central Asian republic of <LOCATION> Turkmenia </LOCATION> on widespread incest among rural residents who intermarry to avoid paying huge dowries demanded by tradition. The youth newspaper <ORGANIZATION> Komsomolskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION> quoted a doctor in the village of <LOCATION> Yagtylyk </LOCATION> as saying that at one nearby collective farm, there are 90 families in which the parents are close relatives, and 71 of them had borne children who died within a year. The newspaper did not make clear how much of the republic's high incidence of infant mortality was attributable to incest, but said it was `` a high percentage.'' A Soviet sociology journal last year reported that the infant mortality rate in <LOCATION> Turkmenia </LOCATION> is more than twice the Soviet national average, which itself ranks 50th in the world, behind most developed countries. The journal, <ORGANIZATION> Sociological </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, said 58.2 of every 1,000 children born in the <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asian </LOCATION> republic die within a year. The national infant mortality rate in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> in 1986 was 25.4 per 1,000. Infant mortality in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> that year was 10.4 per 1,000 births. `` They knock us doctors for the high infant mortality rate,'' <PERSON> Khodzhamurad </PERSON> <PERSON> Makhemov </PERSON>, a pediatric specialist in <LOCATION> Turkmenia </LOCATION>'s Takhtinsky region told the newspaper `` Yet we are powerless in the case of the death of a child of related parents.'' The report referred to the case of a 30-year-old woman in the region who married her first cousin and gave birth to eight children. Five of them died before reaching age one. <ORGANIZATION> Komsomolskaya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pravda </ORGANIZATION> said 164 cases of infant mortality attributable to incest had been found in the one village, <LOCATION> Yagtylyk </LOCATION>, the population of which was not given and is too small to be included in the annual national economic report. The article speculated, however, that a similar situation existed throughout the rural regions of the republic of about 3.3 million people. Intermarriage in the republic has not fallen off in recent years, the newspaper said, blaming the practice on `` those who support dowry ransoms, the buying and selling of Turkmenian girls.'' Rural families that can not afford to pay thousands of rubles to an outside family encourage their children to marry within, the newspaper said. The article quoted local marriage office workers as saying they are powerless to prevent intermarriage, and called for changes in the republic's legal code to deter close relatives from marrying. It noted, however, that traditions in rural regions are not so easily broken, and that many of the related couples who arrive at public offices to register their weddings do so only after they `` in fact have already become husband and wife.'' <LOCATION> Turkmenia </LOCATION>, like most of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION>, is populated mostly by Moslems, who marry in religious ceremonies and register with Soviet authorities as a formality. The article, titled `` Marrying ... a Brother,'' also called on teachers and health care workers to inform rural residents of the genetic dangers involved in bearing children with a close relative.
