<HEAD>College Janitor Leaves $1 Million Endowment Behind</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BETHANY, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A self-educated janitor who wore his lawyer's hand-me-downs and lived frugally while investing in the stock market has left at least $ 600,000 to the college where he mopped floors for 30 years. <PERSON> Lawrence </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hummel </PERSON>, who died March 22 at age 82, had amassed $ 1 million with investment knowledge gleaned in part from discussions with professors and from economics classes he audited at <ORGANIZATION> Bethany </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>. `` If you saw him and talked with him, noticed his demeanor and the way he dressed, you might confuse him with, the only word thing I can think of is, a bum,'' said his lawyer, <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gompers </PERSON> of Wheeling. `` But he was n't. He was a warm, compassionate person who cared about people. I would give him some of my old clothes to wear. If I did n't, I know he would never buy any for himself.'' <PERSON> Hummel </PERSON> lived frugally, investing money from the sale of his share of the family dairy farm in 1953 to his late brother, <PERSON> George </PERSON>, along with wages from the private, 800-student college in northern <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>. He worked at <LOCATION> Bethany </LOCATION> from 1953 to 1983. `` He knew the stock market inside and out. He was always at the college library reading The <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> to follow the stock market,'' said <PERSON> Gompers </PERSON>. The college will receive an initial $ 600,000 from the estate, <PERSON> Gompers </PERSON> said. A trust fund for a disabled nephew will get $ 400,000, the balance of which will revert to the college on the nephew's death A niece and two other nephews each received $ 2,000. `` I never imagined he had that kind of money,'' said <PERSON> Forrest </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirkpatrick </PERSON>, dean of the faculty. `` I taught economics and business at <LOCATION> Bethany </LOCATION> for many years and <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hummel </PERSON> would be sitting and waiting for my car to arrive and he wanted to talk about stocks,'' <PERSON> Kirkpatrick </PERSON> said. `` He asked me general questions and I had no idea how much he was investing. I have no idea what his stock portfolio is either.'' <PERSON> Hummel </PERSON> sat in on every lecture that <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Gresham </PERSON>, former <LOCATION> Bethany </LOCATION> president, gave on economics. He often asked <PERSON> Gresham </PERSON> about investments and asked what things at the college were worthy of support. What <PERSON> Gresham </PERSON> best remembers about <PERSON> Hummel </PERSON> is how hard he worked. `` It was past time to quit many times when I saw him,'' <PERSON> Gresham </PERSON> said. `` It would sometimes be dark and he would still be working.'' <PERSON> Hummel </PERSON> had lived at home on the family farm until 1953, a year after his mother's death. Strained relations with his brother led him to sell out. He never married. He lived above a garage where he kept old lawnmowers for parts to rebuild other mowers. He would spend money only when necessary. Associates said not much distracted him from his work, except mention of one particular former president. `` It was common knowledge that the way to get <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> really involved in a conversation, or to start an argument with him, was to mention former President <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brunnell </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bethany </PERSON>'s director of financial aid. `` He had no use for FDR's ` New Deal.''' `` He despised <PERSON> Roosevelt </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Gompers </PERSON> said. `` He did n't like the idea of somebody being able to get something without working for it.''
