<HEAD>House Votes Symbolic Approval of INF Treaty</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> voted 393-7 on Tuesday to place its symbolic stamp of approval on the new treaty banning medium-range nuclear weapons worldwide. The action has no practical effect since the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has exclusive rights to consent to the ratification of treaties. But it does put the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on record as overwhelmingly endorsing the Intermediate-range Nuclear Forces treaty shortly before the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> opens debate on the agreement. The resolution voicing support of the treaty, which was concluded by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and Soviet leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> last December, also made a series of non-binding policy statements in which the House: _ Declared that the president should continue to provide a credible nuclear deterrent force, including maintaining nuclear weapons in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> to help ensure the security of the <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> alliance _ Called on the president to provide leadership to strengthen <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION>'s conventional forces and modernize the alliance's nuclear deterrent forces in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> _ Urged the administration to seek verifiable conventional arms agreements resulting in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Pact arms reductions in those areas where pact forces have superior strength _ Called for the creation of a comprehensive arms control strategy _ Endorsed the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration's effort to negotiate with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> effectively verifiable reductions in strategic, intercontinental nuclear forces _ Declared the president should act appropriately to deal with any Soviet violations of the new INF treaty, including withdrawing from it if the violations are serious _ Called on the president to propose ways of resolving existing alleged Soviet arms control violations `` and to address any future Soviet arms control violations in a decisive manner. The INF treaty requires the destruction of all <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Soviet missiles with a range of between 300 miles and 3,400 miles. It bans flight tests of any missiles within that range. And it provides for on-site inspection to verify compliance. Most such weapons are deployed in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> but the treaty imposes a worldwide ban. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> resolution stated that the treaty sets an important precedent by requiring the Soviets to destroy more weapons than the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in order to eliminate all such medium-range missiles. It applauded verification requirements as being `` extremely stringent.'' `` The INF Treaty vindicates the importance of <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> security cooperation and illustrates the ability of the members in <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> to act in concert to accomplish meaningful reductions in <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> nuclear arms,'' the resolution declared. Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Burton </PERSON>, R-Ind., one of the few <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members to speak against the treaty, said it should be rejected because the Soviets can cover European targets with long-range weapons, and because, he contended, <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> is certain to cheat `` The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> sucks us into agreements and later violates them,'' <PERSON> Burton </PERSON> asserted. `` This is another tragic mistake.''
