<HEAD>USDA Seeking Advice on Designing Wheat Program</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Public comments are being sought on how to design the 1989 wheat program, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday. One the biggest decisions will be whether to include an acreage reduction program, or ARP, in next year's program. That involves how much of a farmer's wheat base must be idled in order to qualify for 1989 price supports and other program benefits. For the 1988 wheat crop, as an example, participating farmers had to reduce plantings by 27.5 percent of their wheat base. The 1985 farm law requires <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> to announce the following year's wheat ARP no later than June 1 Comments can be sent by May 16 to: Director, Commodity Analysis Division, USDA-ASCS, Room 3741-S, P.O. Box 2415, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> 20013.
