<HEAD>Officials, Israelis Honor Ghetto Fighters on 45th Anniversary</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 1st graf to DELETE reference to nationalities.</NOTE>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prayers and songs filled the air Tuesday as thousands remembered the Jewish men and women who fought <ORGANIZATION> Nazi </ORGANIZATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and died in the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> ghetto 45 years ago. Late in the day, anti-Israeli <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> students marched to the main monument of the <ORGANIZATION> Warsaw </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ghetto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Uprising </ORGANIZATION> and a <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> delegation laid a wreath. The ceremony in which prayers, songs and flowers were offered in memory of the dead took place at midday on the broad plaza in front of the Ghetto Fighters Monument. At 4:30 p.m., about 25 Arab and African students arrived at the same site carrying banners criticizing Israeli conduct in the occupied territories of the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. They were joined by a delegation from the <ORGANIZATION> Palestine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> diplomatic mission to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. As police looked on, the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> group laid a wreath of white lillies two yards from the wreath presented by the state of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The wreath, draped with a colorful Arab scarf, said, `` From the fallen in the Palestinian uprising to the heroes of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> Ghetto Uprising.'' Exactly 45 years ago Tuesday, heavily armed squadrons of Nazi troops entered the walled Jewish quarter of <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, bent on the quick annihilation of the last 70,000 inhabitants. Instead, they were routed by the starving, poorly armed residents, who started a doomed three-week struggle. Before the main cerresenting veterans groups, Jewish communities worldwide and Polish organizations laid wreath after wreath of flowers at the foot of the monument, a bold relief of armed fighters crouched together facing their foes. The monument, near the city's heart, was the very first erected in the destroyed left bank of <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> after the war. As a crowd of about 4,000 Poles and Israelis stood side by side under the leaden sky, a cantor sang Kaddish, the Jewish song of mourning. And Rabbi <PERSON> Isser </PERSON> <PERSON> Frankel </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tel </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aviv </LOCATION> prayed for the victims of the ghetto and the Nazi Holocaust in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Later, when the Polish officials and military honor guard withdrew, Israelis in the crowd burst into singing of their national anthem, Hatikvah -LRB- The Hope -RRB-. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> do not have full-fledged diplomatic relations. Deputy Prime Minister <PERSON> Itzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Navon </PERSON>, in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> on a visit considered private, addressed the crowd and expressed thanks to Polish authorities for the ceremony. He also spoke of the Holocaust in which 6 million Jews were put to death in World War II, 3 million of them Polish Jews. `` We have to remember, yes, but not a paralyzing memory,'' he said in English. `` Not only remember the past, but we should derive a new determination from that tragedy to continue living.'' An assembly at <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>'s Palace of Culture and Science took place later in the day, with speeches marking the anniversary. Polish leader Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> was absent from the main ceremony, but met Tuesday with a delegation of the visiting Jewish leaders. About 3,000 people from <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and around the world have come to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> for the observances beginning April 14, fewer than the 4,500 originally expected. Jewish visitors to <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> objected five years ago when <LOCATION> Palestinian </LOCATION> diplomats were allowed to lay flowers at the main ceremony marking the 40th anniversary of the ghetto uprising. This year, Polish officials did not invite diplomats to take part in the ceremony at the monument. But representatives of several nations held private wreath-layings later in the day. The last diplomatic group was led by deputy chief of the <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> mission in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Shawki </PERSON> <PERSON> Al-Omari </PERSON>. <PERSON> Julius </PERSON> <PERSON> Spiegel </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> watched the scene and said afterward he had no objections to the wreath-laying. `` They have a right. I have no sympathy for terrorism, of course, but I have some sympathy for the Palestinian people. I think it was quite dignified,'' he said. The Polish state-run news agency <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, distributed a text of a letter from <ORGANIZATION> PLO </ORGANIZATION> Ambassador <PERSON> Abdullah </PERSON> <PERSON> Hijazi </PERSON> to Polish officials likening Nazi fascism in World War II to Israeli `` fascism'' in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION>. The letter expressed `` deepest respect for the fallen of the <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> ghetto.''
