<HEAD>Life Is a Lonely Moonwalk for Michael Jackson</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs lead to CORRECT proper name to Doh, sted Dough. Inserts
1 graf after 15th, `Areheart, who...' to add quote that editors
didn't pressure Jackson on subjects.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOLORES BARCLAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> pranced, danced and rocked at an age when most kids are still molding Play Doh. An international star and millionaire by adolescence, his life has remained shrouded. His new autobiography, `` Moonwalk,'' hopes to rip through that cloak. It does n't. What we have here is a failure to titillate. The 283-page book, to be released this week by <PERSON> Doubleday </PERSON>, does not name lovers, explain the megastar's affection for the Elephant Man, detail massive plastic surgery and skin whitening, talk about the oxygen pressure chamber he purportedly wanted to prolong his life, or serve up any other delicious show biz dish. Rather, `` Moonwalk'' is a gentle excursion into the 24 years <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> has spent as a performer. The title refers to the sliding dance step he popularized. `` I was interested in being able to talk about how I feel in a book that would be mine _ my words and my voice,'' the 29-year-old star says. `` I hope it will clear up some misconceptions.'' Misconceptions are as plentiful in <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s life as screaming teen-agers at his concerts. The media, it seems, has not been kind to little <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>. `` I do n't understand why they feel the need to make up things about me,'' he writes. `` I take some small pride in thinking that I've come out pretty well, all things considered. ... It's a difficult life. Very few manage any semblance of a normal childhood.'' He admits to having two nose jobs and a chin cleft. However, he said he has not had his cheeks or eyes altered or a skin peel. He acknowledges long-standing friendships with <PERSON> Tatum </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Neal </PERSON>, <PERSON> Brooke </PERSON> <PERSON> Shields </PERSON>, <PERSON> Liza </PERSON> <PERSON> Minnelli </PERSON>, <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Taylor </PERSON> and <PERSON> Diana </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> _ but there is no kiss and tell. The closest he gets is a passage about a date with <PERSON> O'Neal </PERSON>. They went to a club in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> called On the Rox, and the young actress grabbed his hand. `` This probably would n't mean a lot to other people, but it was serious stuff to me. She touched me,'' he says in the book. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> was asked to do the book in 1984 by two Doubleday editors _ <PERSON> Jacqueline </PERSON> <PERSON> Onassis </PERSON>, who wrote the dedication page, and <PERSON> Shaye </PERSON> <PERSON> Areheart </PERSON>, who worked closely with the reclusive star and helped him write. `` He was someone we admired and thought was a real musical genius, and he had had a long and fascinating career, considering his age,'' <PERSON> Areheart </PERSON> said in an interview. `` I think the book reflects the <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> I've come to know. He's very sensitive, very loyal, very kind. `` He's every inch a professional; he's that way in every aspect of his life. He's very articulate, very intelligent, very creative, very lovely.'' <PERSON> Areheart </PERSON>, who has been a Doubleday editor for nine years, said both she and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> were satisfied with the result. `` I did n't put any pressure on him about subjects he wanted to discuss in the book,'' she said. `` I wanted him to write a book that reflected things he wanted to share with people. I thought he was amazingly candid and warm and did an excellent job.'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s honesty is illuminated in his feelings about his loneliness, his family, how his career was managed and his missed childhood. He started performing when he was 5 and recalled coming home from school, dropping his books, going to the studio, returning home around midnight and sometimes never even having time for a snack. There was a park across the street from the Motown studio, and he used to watch other youngsters at play. `` I'd just stare at them in wonder _ I could n't imagine such freedom, such a carefree life _ and wish more than anything that I had that kind of freedom, that I could walk away and be like them. So there were sad moments in my childhood,'' he said. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is the seventh of nine children born to <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> and <PERSON> Katherine </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Gary </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ind </LOCATION>. He performed as lead singer with his older brothers as the <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> 5. They released 26 albums for Motown and Epic. Their father, a steel mill worker who played with a local rhythm and blues band, was extremely strict with the young performers. `` We'd perform for him and he'd critique us,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> writes. `` If you messed up, you got hit, sometimes with a belt, sometimes with a switch. ... Dad would make me so mad and hurt that I'd try to get back at him and get beaten all the more.'' When he turned 21, his father's management contract expired, and <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>, dissatisfied with how his career was going, especially with Motown's refusal to allow the <ORGANIZATION> Jacksons </ORGANIZATION> to write and produce, fired him.
