<HEAD>About 1,000 Cubans Move Step Closer To Deportation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 About 1,000 Cubans in federal custody have been determined a risk to the community by the <ORGANIZATION> Immigration </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Naturalization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, bringing them one step closer to deportation, officials said. The <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> will begin informing the prisoners this week that they are considered `` non-releasable,'' <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> <PERSON> Austin </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> spokesman in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said Monday. The agency's action follows an agreement last year between the government and rioting Cuban prisoners in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>, which called for a review of the cases of 3,800 Cubans in detention at the time. But in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, a lawyer who was present at the signing of the agreement complained that prisoners were not allowed to present evidence or witnesses during the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> review. `` It's a paper review. It's a joke,'' said <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> <PERSON> Penalver </PERSON>. The prisoners also will not get hearings during the appeal process, he added. The prisoners, who came to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in the 1980 boatlift from the <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> port of <LOCATION> Mariel </LOCATION>, had committed crimes in this country and served out their prison terms before the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> detained them indefinitely. In addition to the 1,000 judged non-releasable, about 2,100 of the detainees have been released or approved for release, <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> officials said. The rest still are being reviewed. Once they get their notices, the prisoners have 30 days to appeal to the <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION>. If that fails, they can appeal to a special <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> panel. Anyone failing both appeals can remain in detention indefinitely. But many of the non-releasable detainees also will receive deportation notices, said <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Korten </PERSON>. The deportation process includes two further chances at appeal. `` I think this is due process, and then some,'' <PERSON> Korten </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Korten </PERSON> would not say when deportation notices would be sent, or how long the appeals could take. The prisoners rioted last fall, days after the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> announced on Nov. 20 that an immigration pact with <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> had been renewed. Under the accord, up to 20,000 Cubans could come to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> each year as immigrants and up to 3,000 more could arrive as refugees. <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION>, in turn, agreed to take back at least 2,545 <ORGANIZATION> Mariel </ORGANIZATION> felons in INS custody. The news sparked riots at prisons in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> and in <LOCATION> Oakdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> La </LOCATION>. Many of the detainees had spent years in <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> detention and expected to be released under an <ORGANIZATION> INS </ORGANIZATION> review that started last June.
