<HEAD>Head of Securities Group Concerned About Lack of Market
Cooperation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The head of the securities industry's largest trade group told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday that despite progress in some areas, he remains very concerned by lack of cooperation between stock and futures exchanges. `` My deep concern is that things are moving so slowly in coming up with the coordination between the various major markets,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bachmann </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Phelan </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Leo </PERSON> <PERSON> Melamed </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> last week that they likely were within 30 days of reaching an agreement on coordinating market halts when stocks or stock futures rise or fall too sharply. But <PERSON> Bachmann </PERSON>, who is chief executive officer of <ORGANIZATION> Edward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Jones </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> brokerage firm, told the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that the pace of reform by the exchanges has been `` painfully slow.'' `` Exchanges, while they're quasi-public institutions, are still very much like businesses and competitive advantage is very important,'' he said. Thus, they are `` torn between loyalties'' when considering measures to prevent another stock market crash. <PERSON> Bachmann </PERSON> said he finds market halts `` very distasteful,'' but the `` lesser of two evils'' when compared with `` the destruction of our markets.'' <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Damgard </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, the trade group for futures brokers, said he favors `` natural trading halts'' such as price limits. However, stocks and futures industries remain split over the level of margins, the amount of money needed to control an investment. The <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> is pushing for higher futures margins, while the futures exchanges say their margins, raised after the crash, are now high enough. <PERSON> Bachmann </PERSON> advocated the creation of a new panel of senior exchange officials, which, under the oversight of the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>, would attempt to resolve such policy disagreements. <PERSON> Bachmann </PERSON> opposed a proposal by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>, D-Wis., that would create a supercommittee of federal regulatory agencies to decide policy conflicts by majority vote Instead, he backed the <ORGANIZATION> SEC </ORGANIZATION>'s bid for authority over stock futures, which currently rests with the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>. Authority over futures margins should go to the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, which already sets stock margins, <PERSON> Bachmann </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Damgard </PERSON> also opposed <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON>'s proposal, which was introduced last month with the support of <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Brady </PERSON>, a Wall Street investment banker and former senator who headed a presidential task force that studied the crash. <PERSON> Damgard </PERSON> said it would be inappropriate for independent regulatory agencies to be forced to bend to the wishes of other regulatory agencies. He recommended that <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> refrain from tinkering with the current division of regulatory turf but said more cooperation could be fostered by continuing a White House working group, which is planning to report its recommendations next month. <PERSON> Damgard </PERSON> said such a group would allow agencies to bring `` subtle pressures on one another without making one party knuckle under.'' He also said futures margins are best set by the individual exchanges. However, <PERSON> Proxmire </PERSON> told <PERSON> Damgard </PERSON>: `` It seems to me what you're calling for is, if not chaotic, at least indecisive.
