<HEAD>Milwaukee Swears In New Mayor</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JONATHAN YENKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MILWAUKEE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> swore in its first new mayor in 28 years Tuesday as <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Norquist </PERSON> took over from the retiring <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Maier </PERSON> and pledged `` to shake things up a little.'' <PERSON> Norquist </PERSON>, who was elected April 5 by a comfortable margin, took the oath of office and replaced the longest serving big-city mayor in the country. `` After 28 years of leadership from Mayor <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Maier </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> is prepared to build on his accomplishments _ and to improve upon them where we can,'' <PERSON> Norquist </PERSON> said in his inaugural address at City Hall before about 200 city and state officials and supporters. <PERSON> Maier </PERSON>, 70, a past president of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mayors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cities </ORGANIZATION>, announced last year he would not seek re-election because of his age. After <PERSON> Norquist </PERSON> was sworn in, <PERSON> Maier </PERSON> wished his successor good luck. `` I know you have the courage and vision to do the job,'' <PERSON> Maier </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Norquist </PERSON>, 38, whose campaign themes stressed the need for change, said he planned to seek broader cabinet-government powers. One proposal would allow the mayor to hire and fire certain city officials who now have set terms of office. <PERSON> Norquist </PERSON> also immediately replaced five <PERSON> Maier </PERSON> appointees on the <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sewerage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> and called for the panel to fight water pollution. But one of <PERSON> Norquist </PERSON>'s biggest challenges will be grappling with lingering racial divisions in the inner city, where blacks suffer from high rates of unemployment and welfare. `` <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> has always been proud of its racial and ethnic diversity,'' he said. `` But not all racial and ethnic minorities have shared equally in our progress. `` City government can be and must be a leader in breaking down the barriers of discrimination and bringing this city together.'' <PERSON> Norquist </PERSON> pledged to open city government to minorities, and of his 12 staff appointments, three are black and one is Hispanic. <PERSON> Norquist </PERSON> also said creating jobs would be a top priority. `` All of the economic development tools and resources at our disposal will be targeted toward creating jobs and keeping them here in <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION>,'' he said. <PERSON> Norquist </PERSON> said he planned to alter the structure of city government to cut expenses and hold down property taxes. `` I said many times during this campaign that <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> is at a crossroads,'' he said. `` Which path we take will determine whether <ORGANIZATION> Milwaukee </ORGANIZATION> takes its place as one of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s truly great cities in the 1990s, or whether it settles for second-class status.''
