<HEAD>Persian Gulf Clash Largest Yet in U.S. Bid To End Tanker Attacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Gulf Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Monday's naval battle in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> marked the most heated conflict in the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> effort aimed ostensibly at calming the `` tanker war'' between <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intervention nearly a year ago came when many administration analysts believed <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> was in danger of losing the war it began with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> in September 1980, a fear that has faded. The naval engagements on Monday coincided with claims by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> that it had retaken the <LOCATION> Faw </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION>, which it lost in 1986 in what many observers considered to be <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s major victory in the Iran-Iraq war. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> on Tuesday denied it had lost <ORGANIZATION> Faw </ORGANIZATION>, but noisily claimed that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> helicopters had flown air support for <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> troops, allowing it to blame `` the Great Satan'' for what could prove to be a major Iranian defeat in the ground war. <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> denied that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces flew in support of Iraqi troops. He and other administration officials portrayed the naval engagements on Monday as a kick in the teeth that they hoped would keep Iranian ships, speedboats and mines out of the gulf. In the wake of the fighting Monday, the two-man crew of a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> helicopter was missing and an unknown number of Iranians were dead. That was thought to be the most casualties in the tanker war since an Iraqi warplane mistakenly fired on the USS Stark, killing 37 <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> sailors on May 17, 1987. Many members of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> expressed support for the latest <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> actions. But the fighting renewed talk on Capitol Hill of invoking the War Powers Resolution, under which <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would have 60 days, or at most 90 days, to approve the deployment of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> forces in a war zone. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration fended off congressional efforts to invoke the War Powers resolution last year, but in doing so sent mixed signals about why it had agreed in the winter of 1986-87 to reflag 11 Kuwaiti oil tankers and provide them naval escorts in and out of the gulf. The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, Sen. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunn </PERSON>, D-Ga., led criticism of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy last spring, saying `` we have basically taken a strong tilt toward <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> That ought to be debated on its own merit and not under the illusions that we are protecting the free flow of oil.'' Administration officials said the goal of the escorts was to protect the flow of oil out of the gulf, but also acknowledged they wanted to restore <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> credibility among the Arabs following disclosures that <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> had sold arms to <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. An Iranian victory in the war, they said, would endanger <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> states along the gulf, a fear that was reinforced by riots by Iranians pilgrims to Mecca on July 31. And administration officials said they met the <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> request for protection in order to prevent the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> from providing the escorts and thereby increasing <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> influence in the region. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> effort soon became a contest of wills between the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration and the regime of <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, and the Iranians appeared at times to have the upper hand. The escorts actually began last July 22, as four <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships sailed with two U.S.-flagged Kuwaiti tankers, the Gas Prince and the <LOCATION> Bridgeton </LOCATION>. As the convoy neared an oil loading terminal in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, a mine explosion rocked the <LOCATION> Bridgeton </LOCATION>, a 400,000-ton supertanker. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships crept the remainder of the way in the wake of the <LOCATION> Bridgeton </LOCATION>, which one <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officer likened to a `` deep draft mine sweeper.'' <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> called the debacle `` an irreparable blow to <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> military and political prestige,'' and said the mine had been laid by `` invisible hands.'' Although <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> for the most part avoided attacking <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vessels directly, its mines and speedboats continued to plague gulf shipping. Then, on Oct. 15, an Iranian Silkworm missile fired from <ORGANIZATION> Faw </ORGANIZATION> struck a U.S.-owned vessel, the <LOCATION> Sungari </LOCATION>, and the next day another Silkworm hit a reflagged <LOCATION> Kuwaiti </LOCATION> tanker, the <LOCATION> Sea </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Isle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, blinding its American captain, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Hunt </PERSON>. On Oct. 19, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> struck back. Four <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> warships fired 1,065 rounds from five-inch guns at an Iranian oil rig, destroying it. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, then still winning the ground war, refrained from a direct response. But over the winter, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> failed to launch its annual <LOCATION> Kerbala </LOCATION> offensive along the southern front, and there were reports that the <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> regime was having trouble finding `` martyrs'' to fill the ranks. Then <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> launched its surprise offensive to retake Faw. Confronted with defeat on land, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> responded with force to the new American attack on oil platforms in the gulf _ an attack very similar to the one <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> ignored last October. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vigilance had tightened since the attack on the Stark 11 months beforehand, and the apparent American military success seemed likely to fend off any moved in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> recall the 25 to 30 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> naval vessels in and around the gulf.
