<FIRST>r a AM-HabitatforHumanity     04-19 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Habitat for Humanity,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Habitat To Build 20 Atlanta Homes In Largest Project To Date</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Habitat for Humanity announced Tuesday it will build 20 homes for <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s working poor in a five-day crash project starting June 27, the 12-year-old volunteer agency's most ambitious project. The effort, named the <PERSON> Jimmy </PERSON> <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> Work Project'88 after Habitat's best-known volunteer, is intended `` to fill a void between a market economy that does not reach down to some economic classes and a government with other spending priorities,'' said project director <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON>. <PERSON> Carter </PERSON> said Habitat `` arouses the conscience of the world to the problem of the homeless'' and to the `` disgrace in our own rich nation of the homeless situation.'' The Americus-based Habitat has built more than 4,000 homes for the working poor on a non-profit, no-interest basis since 1976 and expects to complete 2,000 this year. It has chapters in 277 <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> cities and 26 other countries. Recipients of the homes, who have to help build them, pay back the cost usually over 20 years with mortgages averaging $ 118 a month. The money goes into a revolving fund used to build more houses. Most of the labor is volunteer. The houses are wood-frame structures designed to be simple but adequate with all of the basics and few frills. Habitat has built 24 homes in <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> since it started in the city in 1983 and hopes to complete 75 by 1990. City figures show 31 percent of <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION>'s housing to be substandard, compared with a nationwide average of 8 percent. `` Habitat is doing what the federal, state and local governments should be doing,'' said Mayor <PERSON> Andrew </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>, who also is active in the Habitat organization. `` Habitat is showing us the way.'' So far 10 families have been picked for the 20 homes to be built in the $ 600,000 project. The first house has already been built to serve as the temporary project office. After construction is over, <PERSON> Evelyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> will move into the three-bedroom house with her two children. The <ORGANIZATION> Oglethorpe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> housekeeper has lived all her life in the down-at-the-edges southeast <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> neighborhood where the block of homes will be built. `` This means I can keep my roots here,'' she said. ` We helped frame it up and insulate it.'' `` There was a lot I did n't know and they showed me how,'' she said. `` Now if something goes wrong maybe I can fix it myself.'' Habitat also will build five row houses in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> starting June 20 and has announced a 12-week, 1,200-mile march from <LOCATION> Portland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Maine </LOCATION>, to <LOCATION> Atlanta </LOCATION> starting June 26 during which Habitat volunteers plan to build 120 homes and collect $ 1.2 million in donations to initiate more construction.
