quired in the act,'' <PERSON> Kleeman </PERSON> said. In addition, the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> study said the committees need better documentation of financial disclosure statements made by panel members, and need a better review process to make sure ethical questions are answered. Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, chairman of the panel, said the Pentagon has taken steps to improve its oversight of the committees. But he added that the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION>'s `` compliance ... remains open to question'' with a requirement for documenting why people are picked. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooke </PERSON>, deputy assistant secretary of <ORGANIZATION> defense </ORGANIZATION> for administration, testified that the <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> has tried to improve its oversight of the panels. `` Problems regarding the administration of DoD advisory committees sometimes surface,'' he said. `` When they do, we address them promptly.'' <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Carroll </PERSON>, general counsel for the <ORGANIZATION> SDIO </ORGANIZATION>, admitted that his office had found `` a weakness in our internal management controls'' which delayed appointments of consultants. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Parnas </PERSON>, a computer scientist at <ORGANIZATION> Queen </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Ontario </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, testified that three years ago he was offered $ 1,000 per day to serve on a panel advising the SDIO on computer software. He said he was appointed despite the fact he told <ORGANIZATION> Pentagon </ORGANIZATION> officials he already was a part-time employee of the <ORGANIZATION> Naval </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION>.
