<SECOND>AM-Wheat-Soviets,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Large Soviet Grain Purchases Brighten U.S. Farm Prospects</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Financial prospects for American farmers continue to brighten, and one reason is a pickup in grain exports this year, an <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> report said Tuesday. Large purchases by the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, particularly wheat sold at subsidized prices, have played an important role. Overall, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>'s total grain imports are at a three-year high, despite bumper harvests the last two seasons, the report said. `` The gain is primarily from larger wheat purchases,'' the department's <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said. `` Aided by the Export Enhancement Program and Soviet demand for milling-quality wheat, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> share of import volume is likely to rise to about half this year, up from less than 1 percent in 1985-86.'' The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is expected to import 32 million metric tons of grain from all foreign sources in the international marketing year that runs through June 30, 1988. That would be the most since imports were a record 55.5 million tons in 1984-85. The wheat share of this year's imports is estimated at 22 million tons, the most since 1984-85 when wheat rose to 28.1 million tons. A metric ton is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels of wheat. Soviet wheat imports dropped sharply in 1985-86 to 15.7 million tons, when the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> share declined to a trickle. Under a five-year agreement, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is committed to buy at least 4 million tons of wheat and 4 million tons of corn annually. The pact expires Sept. 30 and covers the year that began last Oct. 1. Although the agreement year is three months out of step with the July 1-June 30 marketing year, it does show a similar trend in Soviet grain imports. For example, Soviet wheat purchases fell short of the pact's minimum in 1984-85 when they dropped to 2.9 million tons, and in 1985-86 when they were only 200,000 tons That coincided with the `` less than 1 percent'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> share cited in the latest report. The Export Enhancement Progam allows exporters to sell designated commodities to specified countries at reduced prices and then collect free USDA-owned commodities as bonuses, or subsidies. Subsidized wheat sales to the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> began a year ago. So far <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> has bought more than 8.8 million tons for delivery in 1987-88, the final year of the grain pact. In addition, the Soviets have bought 4.1 million tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> corn, 818,400 tons of soybeans and 1.3 million tons of soybean meal for delivery through Sept. 30.
