<HEAD>Administration Fights Lawsuit By Polio Victim</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> admnistration, supporting sweeping legal immunity for the government, urged the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday to kill a lawsuit in behalf of a boy who contracted polio after receiving a dose of federally approved vaccine. Some justices reacted skeptically to arguments by <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> lawyer <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kellogg </PERSON>, who said the government should be shielded from paying damages. `` If you win, you might as well repeal the -LRB- Federal -RRB- Tort Claims Act,'' Justice <PERSON> Byron </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> White </PERSON> told <PERSON> Kellogg </PERSON>. The act permits the government to be sued in limited instances when officials negligently cause personal injuries. The law does not surrender government immunity for injuries resulting from an official's `` discretionary function or duty.'' <PERSON> Kellogg </PERSON> urged the court to protect the government from suit `` even if a specific -LRB- federal -RRB- employee is negligent'' _ and is not exercising discretion. The court is expected to announce by July whether it will revive a suit in behalf of polio victim <PERSON> Kevan </PERSON> <PERSON> Berkovitz </PERSON>, who was less than three months old on May 10, 1979 when his pediatrician in <LOCATION> Charleroi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, gave him a dose of <LOCATION> Orimune </LOCATION>. The drug, manufactured by <ORGANIZATION> Lederle </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratories </ORGANIZATION>, is a form of <PERSON> Sabin </PERSON> oral vaccine. <PERSON> Orimune </PERSON> was licensed by the government in 1963. <PERSON> Kevan </PERSON> was stricken with polio within a month and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Communicable Disease Center determined he contracted the disease from the vaccine. He is paralyzed and deformed and breathes with the help of a respirator. Ms. <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Viakley </PERSON>, a lawyer representing the <PERSON> Berkovitz </PERSON> family, urged the court Tuesday to revive the suit to allow the family to prove that it may have been `` pure, sheer negligence'' by government workers that caused the child's polio. She alleged that in licensing the vaccine, federal workers approved it even though the number and size of lesions it caused exceeded the government's standards. It was not a discretionary decision by the government that the defective vaccine was safe, she said. `` The allegation is that the numbers -LRB- of lesions -RRB- did n't add up,'' Justice <PERSON> Sandra </PERSON> <PERSON> Day </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Connor </PERSON> later said to <PERSON> Kellogg </PERSON>, the government lawyer. He did not dispute that interpretation. But <PERSON> Kellogg </PERSON> said even when an employee is negligent, the government agency he works for may be using its discretion in approving the vaccine. The 3rd U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> threw out the <PERSON> Berkovitz </PERSON>'s suit last year The appeals court said the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> is exempt from the suit because the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> exercised policy-making authority _ in effect, its own discretion _ when it initially decided to verify test results by vaccine manufacturers. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>'s decision on how to go about testing the safety of polio vaccine is a discretionary act that immunizes the government from suit, the appeals court said. The administration has argued that if the government can be sued in such cases, it will be forced into becoming an insurer of vaccines and may withdraw from licensing them. Federal officials said <PERSON> Sabin </PERSON> oral vaccine, administered routinely to all children in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, has all but eliminated polio even though each year a few who take the vaccine have adverse reactions. The case is <PERSON> Berkovitz </PERSON> vs. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, 87-498.
