<DATELINE>SHENANDOAH, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This former coal-mining community has taken the extraordinary step of filing for bankruptcy to get out from under a $ 450,000 debt. While a standing-room-only crowd watched, the borough council voted 5-2 Monday to file under Chapter 9 of the federal bankruptcy law, which allows the community to hold off its creditors while it works out a plan to pay its debts. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> Dubroff </PERSON>, a lawyer handling the bankruptcy filing, said that the municipality is not the first in the nation to seek Chapter 9 protection but that the tactic is rare. Council President <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Slezosky </PERSON> said the community of about 7,000 residents, more than 60 percent of them retired or on fixed incomes, can not dig itself out of debt without help. He blamed the borough's debts on the previous administration's `` sloppy'' business practices and unwillingness to raise taxes or cut services while costs rose Councilmen <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Litwak </PERSON> voted against the move. `` I do n't relish bankruptcy,'' said <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>. He said the initial cost of filing is $ 25,000 and the lawyer's fee $ 195 an hour. `` We're not gaining anything. All we are doing is taking taxpayers' money and giving it to lawyers.'' <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON> said he would prefer that the borough borrow $ 425,000 to pay off its bills and then adopt some belt-tightening measures. But <PERSON> Slezosky </PERSON> said that require the borough to raise its real estate tax 60 percent. `` One of the easiest things we could have done, and we could have done it two months ago, was to borrow $ 425,000, but not come out of this for 10 years,'' <PERSON> Slezosky </PERSON> said. A declaration of bankruptcy, if aproved by a federal bankruptcy judge, would prevent the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> from adding fines and penalties to the $ 122,000 the borough owes in taxes withheld from employees' paychecks. <PERSON> Slezosky </PERSON> said some of the paperwork for the reorganization plan, such as a five-year tentative budget, already has been prepared. Representatives of the state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> said last week that filing for bankruptcy automatically will place the borough under the agency's distressed communities program. <PERSON> Slezosky </PERSON> said he hopes the bankruptcy action will qualify the borough for state grants and no-interest loans available under that program. The <ORGANIZATION> DCA </ORGANIZATION> is expected to place some restrictions on how the borough spends money and levies taxes until its financial difficulties are resolved, <PERSON> Slezosky </PERSON> said. <ORGANIZATION> DCA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Reddig </PERSON> said the agency would ask borough officials to reconsider a bankruptcy filing until all avenues are exhausted through the state's programs. He said a bankruptcy filing would be the first his agency is aware of by a <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> municipality. Borough records showed only a $ 69,000 debt, but an independent audit ordered in January by the council's new Republican majority uncovered almost $ 400,000 in unpaid bills from the past administration, <PERSON> Slezosky </PERSON> said. A recent tax-anticipation loan received to pay current bills pushed the borough's total debt to about $ 450,000, <PERSON> Slezosky </PERSON> said.
