<HEAD>Little Red Lighthouse Considered for Landmark Status</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN SHANAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A little red lighthouse brought to life in a 1942 children's story was proposed for landmark status Tuesday by a 9-year-old who clambered up to the microphone at a hearing to retell the tale of the proud beacon. Standing on a chair at the <ORGANIZATION> Landmarks </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Preservation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> hearing, <PERSON> Jonny </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldin </PERSON> said that his father, City Comptroller <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldin </PERSON>, read him `` The Little Red Lighthouse and the Great Gray Bridge'' when he was `` a little boy.'' `` I found it hard to imagine it really existed,'' <PERSON> Jonny </PERSON> said at the City Hall hearing. But his father later took him to see it on the bank of the <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in the shadow of the <LOCATION> George </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bridge </LOCATION> in upper <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. `` We should make sure that it is always there for boys and girls to enjoy forever,'' <PERSON> Jonny </PERSON> said. Supporters of making the 67-year-old lighthouse known technically as <PERSON> Jeffrey </PERSON>'s Hook Light a landmark say the beacon recalls the age of mariners in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> and has special significance to children of all ages. Once a structure is designated a landmark, changes in it require commission approval. <PERSON> Gene </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Norman </PERSON>, commission chairman, said it could take several months to examine staff studies before deciding whether The Little Red Lighthouse should become a landmark. The children's story by <PERSON> Hildegarde </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoyt </PERSON> <PERSON> Swift </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lynd </PERSON> <PERSON> Ward </PERSON> tells how the lighthouse coped with suddenly being overshadowed by the bridge. `` You know the story,'' <PERSON> Jonny </PERSON> told the commission. `` The lighthouse is proud of its job warning ships and tugboats and barges not to come too close to the rocky shore of the <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION>.'' However, the <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Washington </PERSON> <PERSON> Bridge </PERSON> is built later, the story goes, and the beacon is in danger of being closed because the bridge has a warning light on one of its towers. `` At the end of the book, though, the lighthouse is still seen as necessary for safe navigation, and the bridge calls it ` Little Brother','' young <PERSON> Goldin </PERSON> related. Real life was n't as kind to the lighthouse. Six years after the 1942 book was published, the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> took the light out of service. Built in 1921, it was a replacement for a simple light pole with two 10-candlepower oil lanterns. The bridge opened in 1931. The lighthouse is a cylindrical steel and cast-iron structure, 40 feet high and 14 -LCB- - feet in diameter Resting on a concrete slab, it rises 61 feet above the water. The commission also is considering a proposal to make a 60-foot-high <ORGANIZATION> Pepsi-Cola </ORGANIZATION> neon sign on the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> waterfront in <LOCATION> Queens </LOCATION> a landmark. Built in 1936, it is considered by the commission staff to be an excellent example of neon display technology that began to transform outdoor advertising in the 1920s. Its designation as a landmark was opposed by <ORGANIZATION> Queens </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Borough </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Claire </PERSON> <PERSON> Shulman </PERSON>, who said it could delay development of a $ 155 million project for residential, commercial and recreational use of the area. Former Parks Commissioner <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, an attorney for <ORGANIZATION> Pepsico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, asked for a delay in any designation so the soft drink firm could study the proposal.
