<HEAD>End of TV Season Has Networks Evaluating Extent of Erosion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 4th graf, `NBC topped ...' to ADD weekly rating. Picks
up 5th graf pvs, `NBC ended ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> won its third television season in a row Tuesday and is already looking toward another win next season when its Summer Olympics coverage could give it a jump on the competition if the writers' strike continues. If the 6-week-old strike is n't settled soon, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> might not have new shows ready for air in September and could be forced to continue summer reruns _ and that could speed a continuing defection of viewers to cable and other alternatives <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>, meanwhile, will start the season with the historically high-rated Olympics, and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s Vice President for Research Projects <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaffe </PERSON> said Tuesday that advertising interest in the Olympics is `` picking up.'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> topped off the season by winning the final week, though the 60th Annual Academy Awards on <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> was the No. 1 show of the week, according to the <ORGANIZATION> A.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nielsen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> figures. For the week, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> had an average rating of 13.9, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> 13.5 and CBS 11.8. The rating is a percentage of the nation's 88.6 million homes with television. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> ended the season with an average, prime-time rating of 16.0. <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>, which had been third for three years running, eked out second with a 13.7, thanks to the World Series, Super Bowl and Winter Olympics. CBS was third for the first time ever, with 13.5. The rating is a percentage of the nation's 88.6 million households with televisions. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> had never won a season before 1985-86. This was <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s biggest win yet, and the biggest margin of victory for any network since <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> won in 1963-64 But Nielsen ratings showed the three-network average down 9 percent from last year. That figure was disputed by <PERSON> Jaffe </PERSON>, who said his own comparison of more extensive local-market surveys showed a network decline of only 3 percent. He attributed the discrepancy to inaccuracies in <LOCATION> Nielsen </LOCATION>'s new people meter audience measurement system. Last week, <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> released preliminary figures from a competing ratings company, <ORGANIZATION> AGB </ORGANIZATION>, that showed CBS coming in slightly ahead of <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON> is still the ratings company used by advertisers to negotiate advertising rates, though. CBS has estimated that the lower people meter figures will cost the networks a combined $ 50 million in advertising revenues. The three networks have hired a consulting firm to scrutinize the new ratings system, said <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Rubens </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> vice president for research. The results are expected sometime this summer. Whether 9 percent or 3 percent, though, the networks are losing viewers to cable, independent stations and VCRs. <PERSON> Jaffe </PERSON> said the decline is reversible if networks can put on enough popular shows like `` The Cosby Show,'' which increased total network viewing on Thursday night. `` The 3 percent is not immutable,'' <PERSON> Jaffe </PERSON> said. `` There is no law of nature that says the networks will decline 3 percent every year, ad infinitum.'' `` The Cosby Show'' was the No. 1-rated show for the third year in a row, followed by its spinoff, `` A Different World,'' <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Cheers'' and `` Golden Girls,'' <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Growing Pains,'' `` Who's the Boss <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Night Court,'' CBS' `` 60 Minutes'' and `` Murder, She Wrote,'' and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s new show, `` The Wonder Years.'' Of the two new shows that made the top 10, both were significantly helped by their popular lead-ins, `` A Different World'' by `` Cosby'' and `` Wonder Years'' by `` Who's the Boss?'' The only other new shows to make even the top 30 were <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` My Two Dads'' at 21st, `` In the Heat of the Night,'' at 19th, and `` Aaron's Way'' at 30th. The latter two premiered late in the season. Despite the lackluster performance by the new shows, <PERSON> Jaffe </PERSON> predicted a third of them will be renewed, following the pattern of previous years. The networks have parted company with big-event, multipart miniseries. Of 12 miniseries last year, all but two were two-parters. The top-rated `` Elvis and Me'' on <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> had rating of 24.5. `` The <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Jillian </PERSON> Story'' on <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> was the top-rated TV movie with 23.8. News ratings are measured quarterly, not by season, but beginning with the traditional television season in September when <PERSON> Nielsen </PERSON> converted to the people meters, `` NBC Nightly News'' dropped into a third-place slump. Last week, the `` CBS Evening News'' was No. 1 with a 10.1 and 21 share, narrowly edging <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` World News Tonight'' with 9.9 and 20 `` NBC Nightly News'' had an 8.7 and 18. The share is a percentage of sets in use.
