<HEAD>Sudan Says It Will Not Allow Any Influx of Ethiopian Refugees</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Prime Minister <PERSON> Sadek </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> said Tuesday that <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> was `` saturated'' with refugees and he would not accept the expected influx of hundreds of thousands of people fleeing from neighboring <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>. Western relief officials expressed fear there could be heavy loss of life among <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s refugees. <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> said he discussed the situation with <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>'s Marxist government and with the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> of High Commissioner for Refugees and other relief organizations. He said the talks were aimed at organizing aid shipments to the affected people in the Tigre and <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION> regions in northern <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION>, or at setting up camps inside <LOCATION> Ethiopia </LOCATION> near the border with <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION>. Secessionist warfare in the two regions complicates delivery of relief to millions of people suffering because of famine and drought. In a 30-minute interview at his <LOCATION> Khartoum </LOCATION> headquarters, the prime minister told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>: `` We think that <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> has been saturated and we can not take any more refugees.'' He said he made that known last October. The <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> agency estimates there are around 900,000 refugees in <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> including 677,000 Ethiopians. <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> puts the figure at close to 2 million. <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> was elected prime minister in April 1986, a year after a military coup overthrew President <PERSON> Gaafar </PERSON> <PERSON> Nimeiri </PERSON>. Western relief officials here, speaking on condition of anonymity, say from 2 million to 3 million Ethiopians in Tigre and <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION> will be affected by an expected Ethiopian government offensive against rebels. The officials expect refugees by the hundreds of thousands to move toward eastern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> within the next month. They said there is no stockpile of relief food in the drought-affected areas. The Ethiopian government recently banned relief organizations from working in the northern zones. <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> said <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> suggested it can help relief agencies send food to Tigre and <LOCATION> Eritrea </LOCATION> across the Sudanese border, or set up camps within <LOCATION> Ethiopian </LOCATION> territory to receive refugees. One relief official said he feared that once the rainy season begins next month, it would be extremely difficult to move enough food aid to eastern <LOCATION> Sudan </LOCATION> to handle the expected influx, whether it was in Sudanese or Ethiopian territory. `` We will be hamstrung, and there could be large numbers of fatalities,'' the official said. Over the weekend, <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> handed in his Cabinet's resignation to form a new coalition government representing a greater number of political parties. The five-man sovereign council, which acts in place of a president, accepted the <ORGANIZATION> Cabinet </ORGANIZATION>'s resignation but kept <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> in power so he could form a new Cabinet. <PERSON> Mahdi </PERSON> said the new coaltion will include his centrist <ORGANIZATION> Umma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>; the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Unionist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Umma </ORGANIZATION>'s coaltion partner for the past two years; the <ORGANIZATION> Moslem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>; the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Parties </ORGANIZATION>, and