<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> remembered its more than 16,000 war dead in Memorial Day ceremonies Tuesday and Prime Minister <PERSON> Yitzhak </PERSON> <PERSON> Shamir </PERSON> told the nation's enemies: `` All those who hurt us will be hurt manifold.'' Sirens sounded throughout the country Tuesday night, bringing activity to a standstill for one minute as Israelis remembered the soldiers killed in wars with their Arab neighbors. President <PERSON> Chaim </PERSON> <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON> ignited a memorial torch at the Western Wall, holiest site of Judaism, in a ceremony attended by relatives of fallen soldiers. `` The whole nation is aware of the heavy loss, the loss of life, the hopes that went up in the smoke of war,'' <PERSON> Herzog </PERSON> said. `` We have to be aware that this is the price we pay for our freedom and our independence.'' Memorial Day ends Wednesday night with another torch-lighting ceremony at <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Herzl </LOCATION> that starts the celebration of <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s 40th Independence Day Memorial Day always is the day before Independence Day. Israeli authorities increased security for the two holidays, fearing Palestinian attacks on Israeli targets in connection with the 4-month-old Arab uprising in the occupied <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>. Soldiers erected roadblocks in the occupied territories Tuesday night and officials said only Arabs with special permits would be allowed into <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> until Independence Day celebrations end Thursday night. Police Commissioner <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Krauss </PERSON> said extra police were posted throughout the country to prevent possible terror attacks and about 1,000 officers would patrol <LOCATION> Jerusalem </LOCATION> until the Moslem sabbath ends Friday. `` There is information that terror organizations will try to carry out attack