<HEAD>Soviet Arms and Other Supplies Flowing Into Kabul</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tons of Soviet supplies including arms and ammunition are being flown into <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> as Soviet troops prepare to withdraw, Western diplomatic sources said Tuesday. The diplomats, speaking in <LOCATION> Islamabad </LOCATION> on condition of anonymity, said their contacts in the Afghan capital reported nightly arrivals of Soviet AN-12 and IL-76 transports at the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> airport the past week. They said the mood in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> generally was calm in the wake of the April 14 signing of an accord in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> for the withdrawal of the estimated 115,000 Soviet military personnel in <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. The sources reported East European diplomats were saying the Soviet troops probably would first pull back from the eastern area of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> when the withdrawal begins May 15. The Soviets sent troops into <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> in December 1979 to help the Marxist government fight anti-communist rebels. Although the Soviets are to withdraw under the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> agreement, the civil war is expected to continue. Rebel leaders said they would fight on and <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> plans to continue providing aid to the rebels while the Soviets support government forces. The Western diplomats said some of the new Soviet supplies are beging moved south of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> in truck convoys, possibly for storage. There also have been reports of heavy fighting east and south of the capital. The sources said that on April 11, a Soviet convoy with more than 450 vehicles including tanks, mobile rocket launchers and other armored equipment headed for <LOCATION> Logar </LOCATION> province, immediately south of <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>. Guerrilla activity has intensified this spring in provinces bordering <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION>, according to various reports. The rebels usually launch operations as the winter snow melts, but guerrilla leaders vowed this year to step up the war because of the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> accord that was framed without their participation. Prospects of a Soviet pullout have strengthened the Afghan currency to 167 Afghanis to the dollar compared to 210 in February, possibly in anticipation of a strong demand from returning refugees, the sources said. They also said the price of Russian vodka on the local market has doubled in recent weeks to the equivalent of $ 7.50 a bottle, with Soviet personnel apparently stocking up before returning home.
