<BYLINE>By ED BIRK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A pre-dawn tornado exploded through this rural <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> community Tuesday, killing four people, destroying homes, throwing people from their beds and leaving much of a college campus in ruins. Only rubble was left in some neighborhoods after the tornado cut a swath 12 miles long and at least a half-mile wide about 4:30 a.m. Eighteen people suffered injuries requiring hospital treatment. The mobile home of two of those who were killed vanished from its lot, leaving only foundation blocks. Families were thrown out of bed while windows exploded and their homes collapsed on top of them. `` I woke up with a roaring sound and as soon as I woke up, the windows blew out on both sides of my bed, and the roof came down on top of me,'' said <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON> <PERSON> May </PERSON>, who was pinned in the debris for three hours. His neighbor, <PERSON> Diane </PERSON> <PERSON> Dempsey </PERSON>, said she and her husband, <PERSON> Pat </PERSON>, had only moments to rush their three children, ages 4 to 11, into the bathroom before the tornado hit. `` They were screaming ` are we dying, are we dying?''' she said. `` Then it was over as soon as it started.'' It was <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s worst tornado since 1966 when a twister crossed the state from <LOCATION> Clearwater </LOCATION> to <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION>, killing 11 and injuring 400 people. In 1962 a tornado on the <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Panhandle </LOCATION> killed 17 people and injured 100. Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> flew to inspect the scene and said he intended to sign an emergency order allowing state and federal aid. `` It's been tragic,'' said <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>. Lawmen from the state and surrounding counties were already on hand, and state prisoners were expected soon to help with the cleanup, said Sheriff <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Peavy </PERSON>. The twister's destructive path started in front of a shopping center and headed straight into <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Community </LOCATION> <LOCATION> College </LOCATION>, where it `` totaled the new library and took the roof off the auditorium,'' <PERSON> Peavy </PERSON> said. College President <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> McCoy </PERSON> estimated damage at between $ 20 million and $ 25 million. Three of the campus' 14 buildings were destroyed and nine heavily damaged, he said. It also demolished numerous homes, blew the roof off a nearby church, overturned cars and knocked down trees, <PERSON> Peavy </PERSON> said. It ripped apart the only obstetrical clinic serving a four-county area around <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION>, leaving 350 to 400 mothers a year without a place to have their babies, said <PERSON> Betsy </PERSON> <PERSON> Stone </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Tri-County </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>. No one was injured there, however. The worst damage was in the vicinity of <LOCATION> Pinetta </LOCATION>, a cross-roads neighborhood near <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION>. `` I almost fell to my knees it was so strong,'' said <PERSON> Otis </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, 69. His son's home across the street was destroyed. Also in <LOCATION> Pinetta </LOCATION>, the bodies of <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lavelle </PERSON> <PERSON> McCullough </PERSON> were thrown 100 yards and their mobile home disappeared, leaving behind only a dozen cinder blocks on a bare patch of ground. Mrs. <PERSON> McCullough </PERSON>'s sister, <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Butler </PERSON> of nearby <PERSON> Jennings </PERSON>, surveyed the damage a few hours after learning her sister had died. `` It did n't leave any of it. Not even a dish,'' she said disbelievingly. `` You'd never know there was a trailer here.'' Sheriff's spokesman <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Botino </PERSON> identified the two other victims as <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dearmiste </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinesett </PERSON>. Of the 18 injuries, two of the more seriously hurt were flown 50 miles to <LOCATION> Tallahassee </LOCATION> Memorial Regional Medical Center. <PERSON> Brad </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON>, 14, was in serious condition Tuesday after surgery for a punctured kidney, and <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Kay </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> was in fair condition with a chest injury, a spokesman said. Ms. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>'s age was unavailable. Two others remained in good condition in <LOCATION> Madison </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Memorial </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>, administrator <PERSON> Jeannie </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> said. About 100 miles to the west, two tornadoes touched down in <LOCATION> Jackson </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, causing two minor injuries and destroying three houses and a mobile home, as well as heavily damaging five other homes, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Mader </PERSON>, the county emergency management director. The same storm that spawned the tornadoes swept through south <LOCATION> Georgia </LOCATION> late Monday and early Tuesday, ripping off roofs, tearing down trees and injuring at least four people in mobile homes that were tossed about by strong winds.
