<HEAD>Dukakis Got NY Boost From Jewish Voters, White Catholics</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: New throughout</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Support from Jewish voters and a strong boost from white Catholics lifted <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> to victory in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> primary Tuesday, while <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s support came chiefly from black voters, polls said. Racial division was a prominent feature of the race, with <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> winning a huge proportion of the black vote but just a moderate share of white votes, polls said. Still, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s white vote was more than twice its 1984 level. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' three-quarter share of the Jewish vote countered <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>'s black support, and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> led well but not overwhelmingly among Hispanics, polls said. That left <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> whites as a swing vote, and many chose <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. In incomplete returns, <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> exit polls said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> won about 70 percent of the white <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> vote, roughly 75 percent of the Jewish vote and 60 percent of the smaller group of white Protestants. The numbers could change slightly as final results came in. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> won about 95 percent of the black vote, which made up about a quarter of the Democratic turnout, the ABC-Post, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News-New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> polls said. Jews and white Catholics each made up about 25 percent of the total as well. `` The Jewish and black cancel each other out, then the ethnic <PERSON> Catholic </PERSON> white vote is an important balance,'' said pollster I.A. <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> of the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Times. `` It is going very strongly for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>.'' Racial and religious antipathy marked the primary race _ Mayor <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> I. </PERSON> <PERSON> Koch </PERSON> said Jews would `` have to be crazy'' to support <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> because of his position on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> _ and polls indicated that bad blood lingered. In early results from the <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> Times exit poll, nearly two-thirds of the Democratic voters said they believed there was `` an element of racism involved in the vote against <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>,'' while about another third said they believed <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> is anti-Semitic. `` There's a very strong racial element here _ bitter racial antagonism, I'd say,'' <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> said. ABC News pollster <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Muzzio </PERSON> called it `` a dual electorate'' in which <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> won every demographic and socioeconomic group when blacks were factored out. `` It's the same old song: Blacks voting overwhelmingly for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, whites less monolithic, but still, in this case, solidly for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> poll said <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> won just 18 percent of the non-Jewish white vote; <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> had it at roughly one-fifth, which would be about the same he got in the last two primaries, <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>. Among all whites, Jews included, the polls had <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> with about 15 percent. As expected, black turnout was highest in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, accounting for 34 percent of the total in the <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATIO