went for <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> by a slim margin, 48 percent to 44 percent for <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. Liberals made up 44 percent of the total, the poll said. Moderates, a third of the total, favored <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> over <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> by 56-31; conservatives, 12 percent of the total, split 56-23. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> did better with younger voters, the polls said, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> better with the older. Those most concerned with issues such as drug abuse or helping the poor and elderly backed <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>; those concerned with the federal deficit and experience in office favored <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. Pre-election polls never showed much movement toward Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tennessee </LOCATION>; his peak was 12 percent in a <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> poll late last week, after his endorsement by <PERSON> Koch </PERSON>. He did best among conservative Democrats, the CBS-Times poll said, but was third even there to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. `` <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> just did n't play well here at all,'' said <PERSON> Pama </PERSON> <PERSON> Mitchell </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> CBS </ORGANIZATION> poll analyst. The polls had a margin of sampling error of about 4 percentage points.
