<BYLINE>By OLDEMAR RAMIREZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN JOSE, Costa Rica (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A fragmentation grenade blew up outside the American-Costa Rican Cultural Center Tuesday, wounding two Americans and four other people, Costa Rican authorities said. Red Cross officials identified the Americans as <PERSON> Alice </PERSON> <PERSON> Feister </PERSON>, a professor at the Cultural Center from the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION> area, and <PERSON> Shelly </PERSON> <PERSON> Bartain </PERSON>, a student from <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Feister was seriously wounded, but `` she's expected to pull through,'' said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Krischick </PERSON>. <PERSON> Krischick </PERSON> said earlier Tuesday that the explosion was believed caused by a malfunctioning power line transformer. A preliminary report prepared by the <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Directorate </ORGANIZATION> said the explosion was caused by a fragmentation grenade. Three cars were damaged, the report said. <PERSON> Hernan </PERSON> <PERSON> Garron </PERSON>, the public security minister, told The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> officials had no suspects in the incident. He called the explosion `` a terrorist act.'' <PERSON> Garron </PERSON> said the grenade apparently was thrown onto a sidewalk near the Cultural Center. It may have been gone off underneath a car, one of the three automobiles parked near the complex that were heavily damaged. <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Luis </PERSON> <PERSON> Alate </PERSON>, an explosives expert with the <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>, said the device appeared to be an M-67 fragmentation grenade, capable of inflicting serious damage within a 100-yard range. Police said they had no witnesses. One person, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said he was near the site, heard a loud explosion and later saw a cloud in the vicinity of the Cultural Center. He said one person next to the nearby Anglo-American school appeared to have been hurt by the blast. <PERSON> Krischick </PERSON> said <PERSON> Feister </PERSON> suffered a severe artery wound and was operated on immediately at <LOCATION> Calderon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Guardia </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hospital </LOCATION>. She was reported in fair condition. <PERSON> Bartain </PERSON> suffered head and knee lacerations but was said to be in good condition. She was expected to return to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> on Wednesday, a doctor at the hospital said. Her hometown was not immediately available. <PERSON> Krischick </PERSON> said Tuesday evening that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials had been unable to confirm that the explosion was caused by a grenade. However, he noted Costa Rican officials `` were collecting evidence all day.'' `` We have n't had the opportunity to review the evidence,'' <PERSON> Krischick </PERSON> said. `` We will continue to review the situation.'' The spokesman, contacted by telephone, said the explosion occurred shortly after 8 a.m. -LRB- 6 a.m. EDT -RRB- about 50 yards south of the cultural center building in the eastern <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Yoses </LOCATION> district The structure was not damaged, he said. President <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Arias </PERSON> visited the injured in the hospital and later condemned the incident. `` This country, which is a haven of peace, one day could turn into a <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> invaded by terrorism and violence if we do n't adopt energetic measures to prevent it.'' The explosion follows an attack on the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Consulate in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> April 7 by students enraged by the forced extradition of a suspected drug dealer to the <LOCATION> Unit