<HEAD>Books in 13 Indian Languages for 283 Million Readers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Arvind </PERSON> <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON> should be the envy of most book publishers. As director of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Book </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION>, 44-year-old <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON> heads an organization with a potential market of 283 million Indians. But not too many would like to work <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON>'s seven-day week as he tries to juggle 13 Indian languages and keep ahead of critics who say the trust publishes too few books in any one of them. The trust was set up in 1957 to produce and encourage the production of good literature at moderate prices _ a sweeping objective considering the size of the reading public and the diversity of languages. <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s 800 million people speak more than 1,600 dialects, and 15 languages are listed as official in the country's constitution. The 13 in which the trust publishes rant state. Some of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s languages, little known outside the country, are spoken by more people than some European tongues. Sixty million people speak Marathi and 62 million Telegu, almost as many as the 63 million people who speak Italian in <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION> and far more than the 11 million who speak Greek or the 9 million in <LOCATION> Sweden </LOCATION> who speak that language. The trust's translations of Indian works include such books as `` Tin Malayalam Natak'' and the <LOCATION> Punjabi </LOCATION> version of `` Three Malayalam Plays,'' set in the shady jungles of <LOCATION> Kerala </LOCATION>. The translation involves a change in script _ <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s languages also are written in 13 different scripts _ and sees the book traveling 1,240 miles north to the dusty plains of <LOCATION> Punjab </LOCATION> where, <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON> says, it is doing good business. Good business because the Punjabi translation adds 14 million potential buyers to the 22 million Malayalam-speaking population. A translation of a book from any other Indian language to Hindi, the national language, adds 153 million people to the potential market. The trust has recently published a book of Punjabi folk tales in <LOCATION> Urdu </LOCATION>, the Telugu novel `` What Was Left'' in <LOCATION> Punjabi </LOCATION> and the Hindi novel `` Darkness'' in <LOCATION> Urdu </LOCATION>, Gujarati, Marathi and Tamil. The story about <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s partition became a popular TV series. The trust also publishes many books in English which, though not an official Indian language, is spoken by most educated Indians. These range from historical works such as a biography of Guru <PERSON> Nanak </PERSON>, the first prophet of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s Sikh faith, to books about <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s rivers, its Hindu temples and its orchids. Despite its exotic output, the trust has received severe criticism. A government committee complained the organization had published only 3,101 books since 1957 and has spent most of its funds on staff salaries. The trust receives a $ 3 million grant from the government. `` There were heavy losses due to underpricing and incorrect pricing of its publications,'' the government review said. <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON> agrees but only in part. He says more books should have been published and he is planning a 70 percent increase in production this year which would add 250 titles. `` But we are not a commercial enterprise,'' he says. `` There will be losses because the books are underpriced as per government orders.'' The increase in production, <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON> says, is only a token effort to tackle the problem: `` It's like a few drops of rain in a desert.'' Most of the additional titles will be in English and Hindi. But efforts will be made to increase translations into other Indian languages for what <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON> calls `` unifying the country through literature.'' Language has been a prickly subject in <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>. Riots have broken out in south <LOCATION> India </LOCATION> over what people view as the forcible imposition of Hindi, which is mainly spoken in the country's north. The trust steers clear of potential disputes by appointing advisory boards for each language to decide which books to publish. The trust's other responsibilities include participating in the government's plans to make 80 million more Indians literate by 1995. This means providing books for primary schools and adult education centers in more than 500 cities and towns. Only 35 percent of <LOCATION> India </LOCATION>'s people can now read and write. But <PERSON> Kumar </PERSON> says the trust by itself can not fulfill the government's literacy campaign. `` We can support it but we can not hug it too hard,'' he says. `` We can not succeed on our own. We have to float on a current and that current will have to come from the people.''
</TEXT>
