<HEAD>When Interest Rates Rise, Should You Sell Stocks?</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 There's a wise old saying that when interest rates show signs of rising, it's a good time to consider moving your investments from stocks to bonds. It may be one of those times now. Believing in the theory is one thing, but believing in it strongly enough to make a basic investment change is a matter of a vastly different magnitude, since commissions and steep capital gains taxes could be involved. Still, since the theory seems to make sense, the temptation is there. When interest rates rise, the returns from bonds become relatively more attractive. As investors shift, the prices of stocks tend to become depressed. And as rates rise, corporate earnings may fall, depressing stocks further. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Perritt </PERSON>, a former <ORGANIZATION> DePaul </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> professor and current president and editor of the newsletter Investment Horizons, is among those who wondered if reality performed according to theory, and so he put the theory to the test. Using changes in the prime interest rate as a guide _ it was an arbitrary decision; others measures could have been used _ he traced the stock market's reactions from March 25, 1970. For experimental purposes, he assumed that on that date a 100 percent commitment was made to the <ORGANIZATION> Standard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Poor's 500-stock index and maintained until May 11, 1971, when the prime rate rose to 5.5 percent from 5.25 percent. The commitment was then sold, and no stock investments were made until October 20, 1971, when the prime rate fell to 5.75 percent from 6 percent. Thereafter, he sold when the prime rose and bought when it fell. The result: A 462 percent gain in value, dividends excluded, which is more than double the 196 percent capital appreciation earned on a buy-and-hold strategy employed over the entire period. He concludes: `` Even if commissions and income taxes are accounted for, the prime rate portfolio readjustment strategy yields a significantly higher overall rate of return relative to implementation of a buy-and-hold strategy.'' But the story does n't end there. In fact, a very big question arises: What might have happened if you were n't able to hold the portfolio intact for that long period of time? What if you had needed to cash in? Answer: You might not have done very well, since the strategy would not have yielded the best results on all occasions. In fact, says <PERSON> Perritt </PERSON>, there were five periods when the strategy would have placed the investor in the stock market during times of declining stock prices. Similarly, on six occasions the strategy would have resulted in the investor sitting on the sidelines during periods of rising stock prices. Question: Would you, or most other investors, have been able to follow a strategy that failed to work on so many occasions, confident that over longer periods of time it would work out for the best? <PERSON> Perritt </PERSON> concedes it would have taken extreme patience for investors to have followed the theory, one of the reasons being it would have kept them on the sidelines for periods as long as 25 months. And, he acknowledges, the one investment axiom that has long stood the test of time is `` whatever has worked well in the past will most likely not work continuously in the future.'' Nevertheless, he expresses the opinion that `` history often contains lessons which, if learned and practiced, can improve one's well-being. This, he believes, is the case with the historical relationship between interest rates and stock market prices.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday, April 20.</NOTE>
