<BYLINE>All-American Methodists Seeking Their Idenity</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Often called the most typical of American denominations, <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodism </ORGANIZATION> detects a blurring of its identity and is seeking to define it more clearly. That's an objective of the church's governing general conference, which starts next Tuesday in <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Louis </LOCATION> and has before it proposed new summations of doctrine and mission. The 10,000-word doctrinal paper has stirred controversy, suggesting that theology _ the heart of belief _ is going to be a volatile topic of the 11-day meeting. Other issues, such has challenges to the 9.1-million-member denomination's stand against homosexual practice and against ordaining active homosexuals, have gained the most attention. But the proposed doctrinal exposition deals with the rudimentary expression of the church's character. At issue is the document's backing away from previous strong affirmations of diversity, or `` pluralism,'' in concepts and approaches, a variety that some see as reflecting vagueness. The new doctrinal paper seeks `` to move away from glorification of pluralism,'' says the Rev <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Heitzenrater </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Dallas </LOCATION>, vice chairman of the commission that prepared the document. But some contend it is too restrictive. `` We believe that the proposed substitute to our current statement would move our church into a narrow sectarian and repressive stance,'' says a group of about l00 clergy. Others, however, maintain the tightening up is needed to counter a tendency toward ambiguity about belief. In any case, writes the Rev. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Neuhause </PERSON> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, a Lutheran, a tradition strong on theology: `` Whatever happens, it is certain that within <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodism </ORGANIZATION> today there is a seriousness about theology and church doctrine that did not exist a couple of years ago. `` That in itself is a most promising sign.'' Generally considered the most representative of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> denominations, Methodism took root at the country's origins, and moved west with the population, with Methodist circuit-riders common on the American froniter. The church is spread through all sections of the country, both rural and urban. Mostly middle class, it has only about 4 percent ethnic minority members, although it lately has emphasized ministry to them. The denomination initially arose in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> under <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wesley </PERSON>'s leadership with a special mission _ to serve the working classes and socially neglected <PERSON> Wesley </PERSON>'s spirit-filled verve, not doctrinal exactitude, marked the movemenmt. Methodism retains much of its socially activist urge. But the scene now has changed, become more complex in a multi-cultural nation, and some say the church's vision and direction have clouded. Two scholars of Methodist-related <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Divinity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> maintain that the denomination, the nation's second largest <ORGANIZATION> Protestant </ORGANIZATION> body next to <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Baptists </ORGANIZATION>, is no longer just one church, but seven of them. In a 1985 study, `` The Seven Churches of Methodism,'' professors <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> and <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Willimon </PERSON> say regionalism characterizes the denomination rather than any overall cohesion. `` Regional differences are a fact of life, and unless church leaders recognize and deal with those tensions, any attempts to have homogeneous ministries will be imposssible,'' says sociologist-researcher <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>. He and <PERSON> Willimon </PERSON> say the denomination now consists of these seven `` churches'': The <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> `` Yankee church,'' declining and absorbed in ecclesiastical tinkering; the `` Industrial Northeast'' church, once strong, but retreating to small towns; the `` Midwest Church,'' still a stable stronghold, the `` Church South,'' conservative and cohesive; the `` <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>,'' lively and fastest growing, the `` Frontier Church'' still with a frontier spirit, and `` the <ORGANIZATION> Western </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>,'' something of an enigmatic mixture. The denomination, second largest in the nation next to Southern Baptists and Roman Catholics, emphasizes its variety in its present doctrinal statement, adopted in 1972, saying: The `` theological spectrum ranges over all the current mainstream options and a variety of special-interest theologies'' and the church sees `` positive virtues of doctrinal pluralism even within the same community of believers ... `` The viability of all doctrinal opinion demands that the processes of theological development must be kept open-ended.'' In the proposed new doctrinal statement, developed in four years of work by a 22-member committee, puts the emphasis on Scripture as `` the primary source and criterion for authentic Christian truth and witness.'' The other three guides that <PERSON> Wesley </PERSON> put alongside Scripture _ tradition, experience and reason _ are described as aiding in grasping the meaning of Scripture, subordinate to it. `` <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Methodists </ORGANIZATION> as a diverse people continue to strive for consensus in understanding the gospel,'' the document says. `` Our task is to articulate our vision in a way that will draw us together as a people in mission. `` In the name of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> we are called to work within our diversity while exercising patience and forebearance with one another.''
</TEXT>
