<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Star Watch: The Always Prepared Olivia de Havilland</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB THOMAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Veteran actress <PERSON> Olivia </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Havilland </PERSON> believes that preparation is the key to success in everything. It partly explains why she kept a cool head during the pre-Academy Award gridlock while others around her were losing theirs. The scene around the Shrine Auditorium on the afternoon of April 11 was one of panic: bumper-to-bumper limos in all directions; nominees Meryl Streep and <PERSON> Glenn </PERSON> <PERSON> Close </PERSON> -LRB- nine months pregnant -RRB- abandoned their limos to tramp down the city streets in their evening gowns. So did <PERSON> Olivia </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Havilland </PERSON>. But unlike scores of others in the same plight, she exhibited her customary Melanie-like calm. `` One limousine after another disgorged its passengers,'' she recalled with a lilting laugh. `` There was a whole parade of people in black tie and evening dress striding along, and I wish you could have seen the bemused households along the way. They stood there not believing what they were looking at: this marvelous procession. Out came a few discreet cameras, snapping the spectacle. `` One sight I thought very droll: These stretch limousines look very invincible, the white ones especially, but there was one of them in the most undignified position, with its nose up in the air, resting on a tow truck.'' Miss de Havilland arrived at the Shrine on time _ she was the third presenter and recipient of a standing ovation. The reason for her calm, she said, was preparation. `` I went down to the Shrine twice on Friday and for the run-through on Saturday,'' she said. `` I wanted to be sure where everything was. There were numerous details you needed to know for things to go smoothly. Thank heaven I did. `` Walking the eight blocks, my dress had to be held, and the sensitive material crumpled. I knew exactly where the wardrobe was. I needed powdering, and I knew where the makeup was. I also knew the number of my table -LRB- at the Board of Governors Ball -RRB-, and I think we were the first to be seated.'' What was her reaction to best actress <PERSON> Cher </PERSON>'s revealing appearance? `` Oh, I think she's such a rascal,'' Miss de Havilland said amusedly. `` She has the most beautiful figure in the world, and a marvelous face. I must say I thought she was wearing black velvet. Then I realized she was just wearing lace _ and nothing else! I let out a gasp, and then I thought, ` Oh, is n't she funny. She put that on just to make people do that.''' The Shrine Auditorium held special significance for Miss de Havilland. Forty-two years ago on the same stage she won her first Academy Award as best actress for `` To Each His Own.'' Three years later she collected her second Oscar for `` The Heiress.'' The name <PERSON> Olivia </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Havilland </PERSON> evokes a flood of memories for anyone familiar with films. She would be an icon if she had made only one movie: the eternal `` Gone With the Wind.'' However, she is famed for much more, from `` A Midsummer's Night Dream'' to `` Hush ... Hush, Sweet Charlotte.'' She has been a star since 1934, when she arrived in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> as a 17-year-old from <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. She and her sister, actress <PERSON> Joan </PERSON> <PERSON> Fontaine </PERSON>, were born in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. She co-starred seven times with <PERSON> Errol </PERSON> <PERSON> Flynn </PERSON>, romanced with <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Hughes </PERSON> and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Huston </PERSON>, feuded with her sister, married novelist <PERSON> Marcus </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodrich </PERSON> who was 18 years her senior. The marriage resulted in son <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> and divorce. Daughter <PERSON> Gisele </PERSON> was born from the marriage to French magazine editor <PERSON> Pierre </PERSON> <PERSON> Galante </PERSON>. They were divorced in 1979. While she reveres her <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> past, that's not where she lives. Strikingly beautiful at 71, she is very much a woman of today. Her home remains an elegant townhouse near the <LOCATION> Bois </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bologne </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>, but she travels to locations for such TV movies as `` Anastasia'' and this month's `` The Woman He Loved.'' The actress is now becoming acquainted with the world of rock music since her daughter became engaged to French pop idol <PERSON> Johnny </PERSON> <PERSON> Halliday </PERSON>. `` He is a national institution,'' Miss <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Havilland </PERSON> marveled about the singer, who is 13 years older than <PERSON> Gisele </PERSON>. `` I saw him and <PERSON> Gisele </PERSON> just before I left, and I said, ` You'll have to excuse me, but I have to start being very informed. I asked, from his point of view, the most inane question: ` What is the difference between a mandolin and a guitar?' He was very polite about it.''' The thought of <PERSON> Melanie </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkes </PERSON> attending a rock concert may seem bizarre, but it happened. While she was filming `` The Woman He Loved'' in <LOCATION> Villefranche </LOCATION>, the producer arranged a three-hour drive so she could attend a Halliday concert in <LOCATION> Marseilles </LOCATION>. She sat with <PERSON> Giselle </PERSON> up front next to the sound and light controls. `` <PERSON> Gisele </PERSON> was very anxious to see how her mother would react to a rock concert,'' the actress said. `` I had never attended one. Very soon after the music began, it's such an impelling rhythm that I found myself going -LRB- knees bobbing -RRB- and my feet started to tap away. I could not keep still.'' After the concert, <PERSON> Halliday </PERSON>, <PERSON> Gisele </PERSON> and Miss de Havilland were taken by motorcycle-escorted limousine to a quiet bistro. `` That was the night he asked me for <PERSON> Gisele </PERSON>'s hand,'' the actress said. `` I was startled because it was only the second time I had met him. I said, ` W ... w ... well ... yes.'''
