<HEAD>AP WEEKEND ENTERTAINMENT AND ARTS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Music Makers: More Talking Heads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> was in a hotel bathtub in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> when he wrote lyrics for `` No More Flowers'' for the Talking Heads. This is just one bare fact the group revealed when talking about themselves in an interview to promote their latest LP, `` Naked.'' <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>, the group's lead singer and lyricist, was in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> to visit his wife, costume designer <PERSON> Adele </PERSON> <PERSON> Lutz </PERSON>, who was doing a play there. `` I would work with this microcassette recorder,'' he said. `` I would have it sitting just outside the tub. I would reach out and speak into it. I'd be singing in the tub. I'd catch a phrase that I thought was apropos; I'd put it on the little recorder.'' The album is on their new label, Fly Records. It jumped onto Cashbox magazine's best-selling album chart at No. 20 on April 2. `` This record actually goes back to our earliest songs and albums ` Remain in Light' -LRB- 1980 -RRB- and ` Speaking in Tongues' -LRB- 1983 -RRB-, where we would each contribute ideas,'' said drummer <PERSON> Chris </PERSON> <PERSON> Frantz </PERSON>. `` We rented a rehearsal studio in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and each threw out ideas. We had a little cassette recorder and had all our instruments there. We'd take an idea, play it and play it, trading instruments, until it fell apart. Then we'd strike up a new idea. We ended up after 10 days with many snippets of songs. `` We went to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> into a recording studio and commenced to put them all together into song form.'' They went to <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> for several reasons. They laid down tracks with Paris-based Third-World musicians who play <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Zuok </LOCATION> and Algerian-Moroccan rai. <PERSON> Frantz </PERSON> said they also wanted to hang out together, which they're more apt to do in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> than in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> where they have different sets of friends. `` My feeling is that lately there has been less openness here,'' said <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>, the group's lead singer and lyricist. `` I wanted to get away from that feeling. There is that kind of vibe here that whatever is Top 10 in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is all there is. There is a lot going on in other places.'' <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>, <PERSON> Frantz </PERSON> and <PERSON> Tina </PERSON> <PERSON> Weymouth </PERSON> met at the <ORGANIZATION> Rhode </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Island </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Design </ORGANIZATION>, and still design their striking album packages. They added <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> to the trio and put out their first album in 1977. <PERSON> Wally </PERSON> <PERSON> Badarou </PERSON>, who played keyboards on `` Speaking in Tongues,'' found the <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> studio and brought in other musicians. `` One guitarist had a big smile the entire time he was playing with us,'' <PERSON> Weymouth </PERSON> said. `` When you're putting down music with that kind of heartfelt feeling, you know it's coming across in the record.'' <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> said the album has two moods. `` This organic, larger band is primarily on the first side of the album,'' he said. What Weymouth terms `` the more experimental or ominous'' songs are on Side 2. After 15 basic tracks were recorded, <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> improvised melodies and then wrote the words. `` I heard a story about a <LOCATION> French </LOCATION> screenwriter who, when it was time to write a script, would rent a hotel room at the <PERSON> Rafael </PERSON> and lock himself in the bathroom,'' <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> said. `` His secretary would deliver food. He did n't allow himself to go out of there until it was all done. He could barely afford to stay there. He had to work every day. `` I tried lyrics for all 15. On some the words and melodies were n't quite right. It was nice that we had enough. There was one about marijuana _ it's a great song. Too bad. It was lagging behind in the race for the record so it did n't make it.'' <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>, who is British, married the American <PERSON> Lutz </PERSON> last July in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON> has a son who is 1 years old, and <LOCATION> Weymouth </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Frantz </PERSON>, who are married, have two sons, who are 5 and 2. Since they all have individual commitments to pursue the next Talking Heads project probably will be another album instead of a tour. `` I put together ` Storytelling Giant,' a compilation of all the band videos, and shot some extra material to go between them, to kind of link them. `` I hope to direct another movie, with <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON>, in the summer in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. That's still in the planning stage. We did something a couple of years ago, ` The Knee Plays.' I think that's going into a theater in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>'s last film was `` True Stories,'' a musical romp about an `` average'' <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> town. <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON> also composed music for some scenes in <PERSON> Bernardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Bertolucci </PERSON>'s `` The Last Emperor,'' which won nine Acaemy Awards. <PERSON> Harrison </PERSON>, who produced the <ORGANIZATION> BoDeans </ORGANIZATION>' `` Inside Looking Out,'' is putting together a band to tour behind the album he just released on <ORGANIZATION> Sire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Records </ORGANIZATION>, ` Casual Gods.' `` I did ` Casual Gods' in <LOCATION> Wisconsin </LOCATION> in a basement studio,'' he said. `` My mother was ill and my father had passed away. I went back to <LOCATION> Milwaukee </LOCATION> to take care of her whenever I could be there. I found a basement studio I could rent by the week rather than by the hour, owned by the younger brother of someone I had grown up with. `` Musicians would pass through town or I used local musicians. I was paying for it myself. When I was offered a production job I would always do it. That caused my record to extend over the years. I think it made it much better. The songs are more diverse and I think my singing got better.'' <LOCATION> Weymouth </LOCATION> said she and <PERSON> Frantz </PERSON> just finished `` Conscious Party'' by <PERSON> Ziggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Marley </PERSON> and the Melody Makers. It is their only production outside of the <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Club </PERSON>. `` We are going into the studio to finish up our third <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Club </PERSON> record,'' <PERSON> Frantz </PERSON> said. `` After it's released in June, I think we'll tour in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. We're in demand in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>. `` <PERSON> Ziggy </PERSON> <PERSON> Marley </PERSON>, who's 19, writes all the material. His brother <PERSON> Steve </PERSON>, 15, sings one song. <PERSON> Cedella </PERSON> is 20. <PERSON> Rita </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON>, who's a mother of two, sing backgrounds.'' The Melody Makers, formed by the late reggae king <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Marley </PERSON>, have been around since <PERSON> Ziggy </PERSON> was 8. `` It's hard for me to imagine doing all this when I was 19,'' remarked <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>.
