<HEAD>Armstrong Sale To Lead Armtek In Search Of More Automotive-related
Businesses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Armtek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> says it will be looking to acquire additional automotive-related businesses once it completes the sale of its <ORGANIZATION> Armstrong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tire </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> to <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Pirelli </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION>. Armtek announced Monday it had agreed to sell <ORGANIZATION> Armstrong </ORGANIZATION> Tire to <ORGANIZATION> Pirelli </ORGANIZATION>, one of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s largest tiremakers, for $ 190 million cash. Armtek will use most if not all of the proceeds to reduce its long-term debt, which stood at about $ 300 million the end of the first quarter, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> N. </PERSON> <PERSON> Sievers </PERSON>, director of corporate planning and investor relations. <PERSON> Armtek </PERSON> also will seek additional acquisitions to pursue its goal of becoming a leading worldwide supplier of materials, components and systems to automotive and industrial markets, company officials said. `` We will not stray at all from our automotive focus,'' <PERSON> Sievers </PERSON> said. Armtek is the parent of <ORGANIZATION> Dayco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Products </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a supplier of engineered drive systems, including automotive and industrial belts and hoses; <ORGANIZATION> Blackstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a maker of heat exchange systems and components, and <ORGANIZATION> Copolymer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rubber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a producer of specialty polymers. <PERSON> Sievers </PERSON> said growth prospects were good for all three companies. Armstrong Tire, founded 75 years ago, employs about 2,700 people. The comp