<HEAD>Report: Enhanced Oil Recovery Projects Down 28 Percent in Two
Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TULSA, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The number of enhanced oil recovery projects operating in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> fell by 28 percent over the past two years due to the sliding price of crude oil, according to an industry magazine. The projects, which are aimed at boosting oil recovery from known reservoirs, suffered from crude prices that were too low to provide incentives for expansion and from a lack of capital to invest in new projects, the Oil and <ORGANIZATION> Gas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION> reported in its Monday issue. The Journal's report came as about 1,000 industry representatives attended a three-day symposium on enhanced oil recovery methods beginning here on Monday. Oil prices, which remain in the $ 18-a-barrel range, are forcing larger American producers away from high-cost enhanced oil recovery methods and into areas with quicker payoffs, said <PERSON> Lowell </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, chairman of the <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION> symposium and head of research for <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Production </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> Tulsa </LOCATION> facility. A Journal survey indicated 366 active <ORGANIZATION> EOR </ORGANIZATION> projects in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, compared with 512 projects at the same time two years ago. Over the same period, production from enhanced recovery operations increased slightly to 637,000 barrels of oil a day. Enhanced oil recovery techniques include the the injection of steam, gases or liquids into oil-producing formations. Thermal recovery methods, mostly steam injection, account for about 73 percent of the additional production resulting from <ORGANIZATION> EOR </ORGANIZATION> operations, the Journal said. Some $ 960 million will be spent on enhanced recovery projects planned for 1988 and 1989 in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and elsewhere, based on investment information for 76 projects during that period, the magazine stated.
