<HEAD>First City: Tender Offer Successful</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH RENDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Officials of <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bancorporation </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> announced today that the company's tender offer for debt holders to submit their securities was successful, paving the way for a $ 1.6 billion federal bailout plan. Last month, the company _ which officially becomes the <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Acquisition </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> under the plan _ lowered the required participation level from 90 percent to 70 percent. In making today's announcement, however, company officials declined to confirm that senior and subordinated debt holders had surrendered 70 percent of the bank holding company's debt. <LOCATION> First </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> officials announced last week they planned to complete the deal by today. A Monday afternoon deadline, the company's sixth, passed without word from <LOCATION> First </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> on whether the company had completed the last obstacle to finish the reorganization plan. As of last week, 66.1 percent, or $ 149.3 million, of the bank's $ 225.8 million in bonds had been tendered First City needs at least $ 158 million of the outstanding debt tendered to complete the deal. <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> investor <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Abboud </PERSON>'s effort to rescue Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> with the help of $ 970 million from the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deposit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> has been slowed by bondholders' reluctance to part with the debt First City senior debt holders have been offered 45 cents on the dollar for their debt, while subordinated debt holders have been offered 35 cents. Bonds not tendered by the deadline become the obligation of the revitalized <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> and would be worth more than what <PERSON> Abboud </PERSON> is offering. The bailout plan, announced in September, calls for $ 970 million in assistance from the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION>, a spinoff of $ 1.79 billion in book value of poorly performing assets and $ 500 million infusion of capital raised privately by a group headed by <PERSON> Abboud </PERSON>. Also on Monday, <ORGANIZATION> CNN </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> reported that <PERSON> Abboud </PERSON> has agreed to put up more than $ 500 million in private money through new stock underwritten by <ORGANIZATION> Donaldson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lufkin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Jenrette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp </ORGANIZATION>. The report said <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has pledged $ 100 million _ under certain conditions _ as part of that sum. A First City spokesman said he was not aware of <PERSON> Drexel </PERSON> <PERSON> Burnham </PERSON> <PERSON> Lambert </PERSON>'s involvment with <PERSON> Abboud </PERSON>. Calls to the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> investment company from The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> were not returned. <LOCATION> First </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, with 59 banks in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and one in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, grew quickly during the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> oil boom, but was hit by energy and real estate losses when oil prices plummeted. For 1987, the state's fourth-largest bank holding company posted a $ 1.1 billion loss. In a 10K report filed late last month with the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> reported it expected to lose $ 43 million by the time the reorganization is completed. If the <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> does n't redeem enough bonds, the <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> says it will resort to an alternative that will hurt bondholders more than <PERSON> Abboud </PERSON>'s proposal. The <ORGANIZATION> FDIC </ORGANIZATION> wo n't say what the alternatives are, but analysts suspect the agency would declare <ORGANIZATION> First </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> insolvent, seize it under its emergency powers and then turn it over to <PERSON> Abboud </PERSON>. If that happens, bondholders would get wiped out. Another alternative would be to declare First City bankrupt and negotiate with bondholders in court.
