<HEAD>Futures Prices Fade After Runup On Persian Gulf Fighting</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 6 grafs to UPDATE with morning activity; uppicks
6th graf pvs: U.S. Navy...</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Oil futures prices dropped sharply today, as profit-taking continued in the wake of the runup that erupted on Monday's explosion of U.S.-Iran fighting in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION>. In midday trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, stood at $ 18.12 per 42-gallon barrel, down 15 cents from Monday's closing price. May contracts for wholesale unleaded gasoline were trading at 52.40 cents per gallon, down 0.90 cent, while wholesale heating oil contracts were down 0.85 cent at 49.65 cents per gallon. Analysts said selling hit the market from the start, continuing a trend that began early Monday afternoon. Anticipating that diminished <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> oil supplies might send prices higher, many traders rushed to buy Monday despite widespread realization that any shortfall could easily be diminished by other world producers, analysts said. As a result, when the initial excitement died down, prices slipped back because of profit-taking and technical factors, they said. <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> vessels destroyed two offshore Iranian oil platforms, sank a defending Iranian patrol boat and bombed two Iranian navy frigates in retaliation for a mine attack that nearly sank a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vessel. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> attacked oil facilities off <LOCATION> Sharjah </LOCATION> and fired on at least two <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vessels. <PERSON> Jayne </PERSON> <PERSON> Ball </PERSON>, an analyst at the <ORGANIZATION> Dean </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Witter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reynolds </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> investment firm, said prices soared on those reports, even though `` there's an overall recognition that if you shut down the Gulf, there's not so big an impact'' on world oil supplies, because of the number of other producers has grown. But the markets still worry to the point that `` anything that happens in that area has got to have an impact on prices,'' she added. Ms. <PERSON> Ball </PERSON> said the failure of the May crude contract to move above $ 19 discouraged traders, who then began the afternoon selloff. The May crude contract expires at Wednesday's close, and so `` a lot of people took advantage of the higher prices and sold off,'' said <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> McKiernan </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> McKiernan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> commodities trading firm.
