<HEAD>Harvey Mackay Shows How to Swim with the Sharks and Survive</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARREN MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At age 26, on his way to becoming a best-selling author, <PERSON> Harvey </PERSON> <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> bought a failing envelope company with 12 employees, annual sales of $ 200,000 and a few pieces of broken-down equipment. He did n't change the company's name to <ORGANIZATION> Mackay </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Envelope </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> for 2 -LCB- years, he says, `` because I did n't want the <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> name on it if I went bankrupt.'' Today that company has 350 employees, sales of approximately $ 35 million and modern plants in both <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iowa </LOCATION>, and for the past 10 years <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> has traveled around the world giving seminars for other businesses. Now the 55-year-old <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> businessman has written a book outlining his philosophy on how to become successful and the insights he's gleaned from his experiences. `` Swim With the Sharks Without Being Eaten Alive'' was published March 23. By mid-April, 150,000 copies had been sold, the book was on back order and was No. 2 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> best-seller list in the `` how-to'' category. The book's success was no accident. `` I traveled around the country visiting bookstores and talking with people in the industry'' before starting to write the book two years ago, <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> said. His research showed many books fail because they are n't available in the bookstores So when he went to <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrow </PERSON> & amp; Co.. Inc. in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> to talk about a contract, he asked for a first printing of 100,000 copies `` I'm an unknown, first-time author from the flyover state of <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. I wanted to make sure there were enough,'' he remembers with the dry wit characteristic of the book. But <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> also was prepared to show <PERSON> Morrow </PERSON> officials how he could help them. `` I told them I knew about 2,000 presidents and chief executive officers of major companies throughout the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and said I would mail the book to those people,'' <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> said. `` They had to know I had made a personal commitment to help them market the book,'' he said. <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> told them he was willing to take time off from his business for an extended book tour and said he would put on a two-hour seminar for the company's sales force. During the seminar, `` I would not talk about my book,'' he said. But the presentation meant the sales force would know <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON>, and those same sales people would then be selling his book to the bookstores. `` It was a two-way street _ good for them and a big break for me,'' he said. When the contract was written, <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> had a $ 150,000 budget for promotion, a six-figure advance -LRB- he wo n't disclose the exact amount -RRB- and a 100,000 first printing. After he began writing, <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> was invited to bring his manuscript and address a publishing course at <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. One of the professors made his first draft mandatory reading for the class, <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> said, giving him free feedback from the 85 students. Once the manuscript was completed, <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> sent copies to nearly 50 well-known friends asking them to read it and drop him a line telling him what they thought. `` I was hoping for three or four responses,'' <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> said. Forty-five responded _ including former President <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Ford </PERSON>, former Vice President <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Mondale </PERSON>, newsman <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Koppel </PERSON>, feminist <PERSON> Gloria </PERSON> <PERSON> Steinem </PERSON>, Notre Dame football Coach <PERSON> Lou </PERSON> <PERSON> Holtz </PERSON>, actors <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Redford </PERSON> and <PERSON> Eddie </PERSON> <PERSON> Albert </PERSON>, advice columnist <PERSON> Abigail </PERSON> -LRB- Dear Abby -RRB- <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Buren </PERSON>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuomo </PERSON>, Baseball Commissioner <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Ueberroth </PERSON> and evangelist <PERSON> Billy </PERSON> <PERSON> Graham </PERSON>. Their praises of `` Swim With the Sharks'' are printed on the first 15 pages before the title page. `` The book is about preparing to win, preparing to be successful, changing the probability, leveling the playing field so you have the highest probability going for you to succeed,'' <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> said. `` There are all kinds of people who are really trying but are spinning their wheels.'' However, he stresses the difference between being successful and getting rich. `` I believe a successful person is one who measures the standard of his or her own performance by their own potential,'' said <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON>, the top-ranked tennis player in his age group in <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> and a self-described `` language junkie'' who speaks Chinese, Japanese and Arabic. `` Measuring your success by the standards of others does n't work, he quips, because `` every time you catch up with the <PERSON> Joneses </PERSON>, they refinance. The cornerstone of the book is a 66-question customer profile which <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> developed for his own sales people to use to `` become a colleague of the people you're dealing with'' and to help make sales. The profile includes detailed information on the person's education, family and business background, special interests and lifestyle But <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> stressed that sincerity is important in dealing with people. `` You might fool someone in the short term, but not in the long term,'' he said. The book, now in its seventh printing, was written primarily to help people, but also as a legacy for his three grown children, said <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON>, whose wife, <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Ann </PERSON>, has been accompanying him on the book tour. `` There is no greater reward in life than to be able to help another human being. Period. That's what turns me on,'' he said. While <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> had the money and the connections to promote his book, he says it is n't necessary to have money to make money. `` You can take my money, put me in <LOCATION> Tucumcari </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.M. </LOCATION>, with nothing, and I can do it again,'' <PERSON> Mackay </PERSON> said. `` Anyone can do it if they want to do it.''
