<HEAD>Inflation Hits New High In First Quarter Of 1988</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY WILHELM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Retail prices rose faster than average incomes in some cities in the first quarter of 1988 and the nationwide inflation rate hit 11 percent, the government announced Tuesday. The inflation rate, up from a national average of 7.3 percent in 1987, is the highest the government has reported since senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> began reducing central planning and price controls in favor of market reforms in 1978. In 32 large and medium-size cities, retail prices rose 13.4 percent, the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> said, while average per capita incomes in urban areas only rose 13 percent, to more than 90 yuan, or $ 24, per month. Average per capita income for rural residents rose 25 percent, to 50 yuan, or $ 13.50 per month. Top officials have acknowledged widespread popular discontent over the rising prices and have announced corrective measures. But they also have warned that inflation will remain high for several years as <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> strives to develop its backward economy and allow market factors to set prices. <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> <PERSON> Zhongji </PERSON>, director of the statistic bureau's <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Integrated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economy </ORGANIZATION>, told a news conference that the industrial sector maintained its rapid growth in the first quarter, with output up 16.7 percent from the same period last year, to the equivalent of $ 71.5 billion. Industrial output grew 16.5 percent during all of 1987. Vice Premier <PERSON> Yao </PERSON> <PERSON> Yilin </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Planning </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, told a recent news conference that the government's goal was to keep inflation below 10 percent, but added: `` Whether we will be able to achieve it I ca n't tell you.'' His cautious assessment reflected the difficulty of the government's task: to cool demand that is pushing prices up without curbing much-needed economic growth. Uncontrolled investment in often irrational and competing projects and inadequate supplies of such goods as televisions and refrigerators have contributed to inflation. The government has blamed inadquate investment in agriculture for high food prices and short supplies of meat in the cities. <PERSON> Zhang </PERSON> said grain production was expected to remain about the same as last year, or 400 million tons. Despite repeated calls to stress grain production, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has been unable to repeat its record 1984 harvest of 407 million tons.
</TEXT>
