<HEAD>Profit Up At GTE, MCI, Pacific Telesis, U S West</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday reported a record profit and strong gains in long-distance calling volume in its first quarter. Profits also rose at <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telesis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> and U S West. <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION>, the No. 2 long-distance carrier, based in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, said its profit more than doubled to $ 69 million, or 24 cents a share, on revenue of $ 1.13 billion That compared with earnings of $ 25 million, or 9 cents a share, on revenue of $ 955 million for the first quarter of 1987. <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION> said its volume of calls was up 39 percent from a year ago and had increased 14 percent when compared to the fourth quarter. <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION>, the phone company based in <LOCATION> Stamford </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, said its profit rose 8 percent to $ 286 million, or 84 cents a share, from $ 265 million, or 78 cents a share, a year earlier. Revenue rose 7 percent to $ 3.9 billion from $ 3.7 billion. <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> owns local telephone companies that do business in 31 states and is half-owner, with <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, of <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> US </LOCATION> Sprint is the nation's third-largest long-distance carrier behind <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telephone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telegraph </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> MCI </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION>'s results were hurt by a first-quarter pre-tax loss of $ 138 million at <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION>, which <ORGANIZATION> GTE </ORGANIZATION> shared equally with <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Telecommunications </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> US </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sprint </ORGANIZATION>'s revenue rose 23 percent to $ 759 million, while its pre-tax loss was 43 percent less than the year-earlier loss. <PERSON> Pacific </PERSON> <PERSON> Telesis </PERSON>, the San Francisco-based holding company for <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> telephone companies in the West, said its profit rose 28.2 percent to $ 300 million, or 71 cents a share, from $ 234 million, or 55 cents a share, a year ago. Revenue rose 7.9 percent to $ 2.31 billion from $ 2.14 billion a year ago. U S West reported its profit rose 17.8 percent to $ 240.5 million, or $ 1.30 per share, from $ 204.2 million, or $ 1.08 per share, in first quarter 1987. The 1987 quarter included one-time charges of $ 30.2 million stemmnig from an early retirement plan and refunds ordered by the state of <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>. Revenue in the first quarter rose to $ 2.2 billion from $ 2.04 billion in first quarter 1987. U S West is the Denver-based holding company for <ORGANIZATION> Mountain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION>, plus companies involved in directory publishing, cellular communications and other communications and computer products.
