<HEAD>Monsanto Reports Record Earnings For First Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday reported a 52 percent increase in first quarter earnings due to increased demand for its herbicide and other agricultural products. Net income for the three months ended March 31 was $ 210 million, or $ 2.86 a share, on revenue of $ 2.13 billion. That compared with a profit of $ 138 million, or $ 1.76 a share, and $ 1.87 billion in revenue last year. `` Strong demand for Roundup herbicide in new markets around the world was, once again, the major contributor to an excellent performance by agricultural products this quarter,'' <ORGANIZATION> Monsanto </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> said. He said the quarterly results also were boosted by the increased sale of its Alimet animal feed supplement and <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> approval of the use of Lasso <ORGANIZATION> MicroTech </ORGANIZATION> herbicide on corn. NutrSweet, Electronic Materials and Fsher Controls also showed improved sales and margins in the first quarter. Operating income for <ORGANIZATION> Fisher </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Controls </ORGANIZATION> declined, however, because of higher raw material and other manufacturing costs, <PERSON> Mahoney </PERSON> said.
