<HEAD>Dividend Payout, Sign Of Good Times</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Bethlehem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> announced on Tuesday plans to pay more than $ 24 million in overdue preferred stock dividends and to sell 8 million shares of common stock to pare its $ 1.7 billion unfunded pension liability. One Wall Street analyst said the dividends are a sign of <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION>'s faith in the steel industry's recovery after five years of massive losses, plant closings and employment cuts. `` It shows more of a conviction that what is actually happening in the steel markets is going to be more sustainable than most observers believe,'' said <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Donaldson </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lufkin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Jenrette </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` Steel demand is strong, pricing is strong, earnings are going to be strong.'' The recovery seems `` very, very broad-based,'' he said. `` It represents the participation of the steel industry in the so-called reindustrialization of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON> said his enthusiasm for steel industry stocks, especially <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION>'s, runs counter to the market. He called <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> stock undervalued. `` People are looking at the recoveries in the industrial and capital goods markets. They know it's happening, but they do n't believe it will continue,'' he said <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> reported profits in each quarter last year and $ 174 million profit for all of 1987. It was the first annual profit since 1981, and during the interim, <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> lost more than $ 2 billion. The steelmaker said <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has agreed to underwrite the common stock offering, which follows last fall's sale of 12 million common shares and would raise the number of outstanding shares from the current 64.4 million to 72.4 million <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> stock fell $ 1.62 -LCB- per share to $ 19.37 -LCB- in <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> composite trading after Tuesday's announcement. The company's board declared Monday that on June 10 shareholders of record May 10 will be paid arrearages and second quarter dividends of $ 6.25 per share and $ 3.12 -LCB- per share on <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION>'s $ 5 and $ 2.50 cummulative convertible preferred issues respectively. Dividends worth $ 22.5 million were omitted for the second half of 1986 and the first half of 1987. The board also said the company will pay dividends June 11 on convertible preference shares issued to employees under contracts with the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steelworkers </ORGANIZATION> and other unions. The dividends will be paid in additional shares with an aggregate stated value of $ 1.7 million. The dividend covers the period ending April 1. The payments do not cover common stock dividends, which have not been paid since the board declared 10 cents per share for the third quarter of 1985. Unlike the preferred issues, on which dividends accumulate, the common issue does not require the company to pay a dividend. <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> said it would report first quarter income at its annual shareholders meeting next Tuesday.
