<HEAD>Japan May Soon Phase Out Citrus and Beef Quotas</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> may begin phasing out quotas on <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> citrus and beef imports as early as next week to avoid rebuke by an international panel, according to a top American trade official. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> vetoed a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> request two weeks ago for a special investigation of the quotas by the 92-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, but the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> plans to push the issue at <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>'s next council meeting May 4. `` They know we will not allow a dispute panel to be blocked a second time,'' <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Samuels </PERSON>, deputy <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade representative and ambassador to the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION>, said in an interview with the <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION> Monday. Japanese and <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> officials will discuss the matter next week in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Samuels </PERSON> thinks <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> may be ready to agree to a compromise. `` They may not want to go to <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> and be found ` guilty' of policy violations because that might offend their political sensitivities at home,'' the ambassador said. Under a 1984 agreement that expired last month, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> agreed to admit 177,000 tons American beef and 86,400 tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> oranges this year. Pressure from the powerful Japanese agriculture lobby has prevented an elimination of the quotas. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> wants a complete lifting of the quotas, <PERSON> Samuels </PERSON> said, but the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration is willing to accept a gradual elimination over a short period of time.
