<HEAD>Judge Declares Mexican Airline Bankrupt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SERGIO CARRASCO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge declared government-owned <ORGANIZATION> Aeromexico </ORGANIZATION> bankrupt and ordered it into receivership, leaving the airline's more than 9,200 workers jobless Tuesday. The decision followed a strike by the airline's technical workers that shut down the airline on April 12 in protest of management plans to reduce the fleet and route system to bring <ORGANIZATION> Aeromexico </ORGANIZATION> back into the black. The airline filed a petition for bankruptcy on Friday, saying it was losing $ 1 million a day because of the strike. Civil Court Judge <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Higuera </PERSON> <PERSON> Mota </PERSON> issued the bankruptcy decree late Monday, the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> announced. President <PERSON> Miguel </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Madrid </PERSON> said the bankruptcy petition was not an isolated case but part of a new policy to sell, cut out or close down all money-losing companies and agencies owned or operated by the government. `` The country can not give itself the luxury of having inefficient enterprises, which constitute a burden to the entire society,'' de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> said at an appearance Monday in the northern industrial city of <LOCATION> Monterrey </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> has been suffering from acute inflation and other economic ills since 1982, when international prices for oil, its No. 1 export by far, first dropped. The strike had grounded all <ORGANIZATION> Aeromexico </ORGANIZATION>'s 223 daily flights to 42 international and domestic destinations. The <ORGANIZATION> Aeromexico </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technicians </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> called the protest strike after the airline's management announced plans to sell 13 aircraft, saying the sale would leave more than 2,000 ground workers and cabin attendants without jobs. Pilots and cabin attendants have their own unions and did not support the strike. <PERSON> Rene </PERSON> <PERSON> Arce </PERSON>, the union's president, said his organization would fight to keep the airline alive and reiterated that it was interested in trying to buy it. He said the union could muster the support of a number of Mexican and foreign investors, but he did not identify them. <PERSON> Arce </PERSON> estimated the airline would cost $ 200 million to purchase, including $ 70 million in estimated severance pay to workers. In <LOCATION> Monterrey </LOCATION>, de la <LOCATION> Madrid </LOCATION> told reporters that from now on the government `` will demand greater productivity, including some radical re-structuring, as in the case of commercial aviation,'' from its hundreds of money-losing enterprises. <ORGANIZATION> Aeromexico </ORGANIZATION> started business in 1934 and has been owned by the government since 1957. The strike and the bankruptcy have not affected <PERSON> Mexicana </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Aviacion </PERSON>, the other major Mexican airline, which has been controlled by the government since 1982. <ORGANIZATION> Aeromexico </ORGANIZATION> employs 7,200 ground workers and technicians, 1,200 cabin attendants and 800 pilots.
</TEXT>
