<DATELINE>MAPLEWOOD, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mining </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Manufacturing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday reported its first quarter earnings rose 30 percent as sales and productivity increased and the dollar and taxes fell. <ORGANIZATION> 3M </ORGANIZATION> said it earned $ 277 million, or $ 1.22 per share, up from $ 213 million, or 93 cents per share, in the same period a year earlier. Sales for the quarter rose to $ 2.6 billion from $ 2.21 billion. <PERSON> Allen </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON>, chairman and chief executive officer, said <ORGANIZATION> 3M </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and international businesses posted solid results. Earnings benefited from double-digit worldwide unit growth, increased productivity, weakening of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar and a lower effective tax rate. <PERSON> Jacobson </PERSON> said 3M expects another year of higher sales and earnings. `` While the outlook for the economy is somewhat uncertain, we expect to benefit from a strong flow of new products, as well as from continued emphasis on quality, productivity and increased penetration of international markets,'' he said. `` In addition, the weaker dollar and a lower effective tax rate will continue to aid results.''
