ces at <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION>, which paid nearly $ 580 million in late 1986 to halt <ORGANIZATION> Revlon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s repeated takeover attempts. <ORGANIZATION> Gillette </ORGANIZATION> laid off nearly 2,400 workers and sold several unprofitable divisions during restructuring after <ORGANIZATION> Revlon </ORGANIZATION> signed a 10-year agreement not to seek control of the company.
