likely Wednesday, education bill passed.
^By STEVEN KOMAROW</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House on Tuesday approved a nationwide ban on `` dial-a-porn'' telephone pornography services despite arguments that the bill was unconstitutional. The legislation, identical to an amendment approved earlier in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>, was included in an $ 8.3 billion education bill passed 397 to 1 after lawmakers handed <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> leaders a defeat and rejected a less-sweeping anti-porn provision. Final Senate action on the package was expected Wednesday. `` Some may question the constitutionality of this measure,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Ralph </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>. `` But it is the most straightforward.'' Rep. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Dingell </PERSON>, D-Mich., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, called the measure `` extraordinarily shaky'' on constitutional grounds <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON>, legislative counsel of the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberties </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, said the ban `` clearly intrudes on the privacy and the free-speech rights of adult Americans. This is a hopelessly inept way of dealing with the issue of children's access to dial-a-porn, which should be the only matter under consideration.'' He predicted `` years of litigation, and in the process, increased access by children to dial-a-porn.'' The situation would get worse because current <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Communications </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> rules protecting children from telephone pornography would be thrown away in the process, he said. Sen. <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Helms </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.C. </LOCATION>, first won the dial-a-porn ban amendment 98-0 when the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> first passed the otherwise non-controversial education bill. But the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> had included no similar provision in its version of the bill and a compromise, less legally controversial provision was approved by <ORGANIZATION> House-Senate </ORGANIZATION> conferees. While the <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> amendment contained a total ban on the services for adults as well as children, the education bill's provision would have had telephone companies block access to dial-a-porn unless the telephone customer, an adult, specifically requested they be made available. Opponents of the compromise said it was too weak and pointed out that about 12 percent of the nation's telephone exchanges did not have the technology to block out the service to some homes but not to others. In an attempt to satisfy both sides, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> leaders on Tuesday orchestrated the vote on a new, separate but otherwise identical dial-a-porn bill. The plan was to have both versions approved, with the education bill's language available if the total ban failed to pass constitutional muster. The separate bill passed the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> 379-22. But then, in a defeat for Democratic leaders, the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> inserted it into the education bill in place of the compromise. House Republicans carried the day after accusing the Democratic leaders of trying to block the flat-out ban. Rep. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Bliley </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Va </LOCATION>., who sponsored the <PERSON> Helms </PERSON> amendment in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, called the Democrats' process `` a charade'' by lawmakers hoping the ban would be blocked in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> He called the limited protections in the education compromise `` akin to telling someone it's illegal to sell someone drugs, unless someone walks up to them ... and asks for some.'' Voting against the dial-a-porn ban, when it came up as a separate bill, were Reps. <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> Beilenson </PERSON>, D-Calif., <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Berman </PERSON>, D-Calif., <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Bosco </PERSON>, D-Calif., <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Dellums </PERSON>, D-Calif., <PERSON> Julian </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>, D-Calif., <PERSON> Mervyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Dymally </PERSON>, D-Calif., <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON>, D-Calif., <PERSON> Barney </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, D-Mass., <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Gejdenson </PERSON>, D-Conn., <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Augustus </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>, D-Calif., <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Hayes </PERSON>, D-Ill., <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Lehman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., <PERSON> Bruce </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, D-Conn., <PERSON> Peter </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodino </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Roybal </PERSON>, D-Calif., <PERSON> Pete </PERSON> <PERSON> Stark </PERSON>, D-Calif., <PERSON> Gerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Studds </PERSON>, D-Mass., <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Waxman </PERSON>, D-Calif., <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Wheat </PERSON>, D-Mo Not voting were Reps. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Ackerman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> Barnard </PERSON>, D-Ga., <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Biaggi </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Beau </PERSON> <PERSON> Boulter </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Clay </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Mo </LOCATION>., <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Clinger </PERSON>, R-Pa., <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Crockett </PERSON>, D-Mich., <PERSON> Hal </PERSON> <PERSON> Daub </PERSON>, R-Neb., <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON>, R-Ill., <PERSON> Kika </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> la </PERSON> <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Emerson </PERSON>, R-Mo., <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Fields </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Texas </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Garcia </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasich </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ohio </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kemp </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Kleczka </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Wis </LOCATION>., <PERSON> Connie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Fla </LOCATION>., <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Manton </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mollohan </PERSON>, D-W. <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Moody </PERSON>, D-Wis., <PERSON> Constance </PERSON> <PERSON> Morella </PERSON>, R-Md., <PERSON> Major </PERSON> <PERSON> Owens </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Melvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Price </PERSON>, D-Ill., <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Rangel </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Ray </PERSON>, D-Ga., The only lawmaker to vote against the education bill including the dial-a-porn language was Rep. <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Crane </PERSON>, R-Ill.
