<HEAD>Safety Inspectors Say They Were Told To `Generate Numbers'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: New throughout to expand on Bush's role and include reaction
from his office. Edits to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Federal safety inspectors told a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee Tuesday they were instructed last September to `` generate numbers'' through sham inspections emphasizing quantity over improving the quality of the nation's workplaces. `` Because the office was short on numbers for the year, they wanted compliance officers to generate double the number of <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> 1 -LRB- inspection -RRB- reports,'' Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Barry </PERSON>, an industrial hygienist in the agency's <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> regional office, testified Tuesday. <PERSON> Barry </PERSON> and other field inspectors stationed in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> described in the second day of hearings by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> how the <ORGANIZATION> Occupational </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> boosted its inspection totals last year by more than 2,000. The committee, chaired by Sen. <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, D-Mass., has been preparing the hearings for more than a year None of the seven Republicans on the panel have attended the first two days. Before the first witness was called Monday, <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> vowed to `` show that the decision to let workers die ... has been supervised and carried out by the highest levels of this administration.'' Assistant Labor Secretary <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Baroody </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Pendergrass </PERSON> are scheduled to testify before the panel on Wednesday. `` I'm sure we'll be able to set the record straight then,'' <PERSON> Terry </PERSON> <PERSON> Mikelson </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said Tuesday when asked for the agency's response to allegations raised so far in the hearings. Two senior <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> officials testified Tuesday that, because of intervention by Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> last month, they are now rewriting regulations to enable some companies to avoid the expense of venting toxic gases from some workplaces by instead making workers wear less effective personal respirators. Career bureaucrats in <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> believed they had won a seven-year fight with the <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> over the respirator proposal until <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> met on March 22 with <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> officials and <PERSON> Baroody </PERSON>. As a result of that meeting, proposed standards are being prepared for White House approval that would allow greater use of personal respirators for short-term exposure to toxic substances or when the cost of engineered ventilation controls are considered `` excessive,'' the committee was told. The current regulations, in effect since 1981, establish a hierarchy of preferred methods for protecting workers from toxic gases. At the top of that hierarchy are the often-expensive ventilation systems. If ventilation is impractical, employers can alter their work practices such as rotating workers in and out of hazardous areas. At the bottom of the current heirarchy are personal respirators. The Task Force on Regulatory Relief chaired by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in 1981 recommended altering that hierarchy to recognize `` technical improvements in respirators as opposed to the blanket regulation of ventilation systems everywhere,'' said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s press secretary. `` There is no way in my view that respirators can be as protective,'' <PERSON> Sheldon </PERSON> <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON>, deputy director of health standards for <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION>, told the committee Tuesday, acknowledging that <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> calls for new regulations were met with stiff resistence. `` It's a waste of our time as far as I'm concerned,'' added <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Martonik </PERSON>, an official in <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION>'s health standards office. Nonetheless, <PERSON> Martonik </PERSON> testified Tuesday, `` We have finished redrafting it for submittal to <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> for review.'' <PERSON> Weiner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Martonik </PERSON> said the respirator issue was revived as a direct result of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s meeting with <PERSON> Baroody </PERSON>. After the meeting, <PERSON> Baroody </PERSON> wrote a memorandum to <PERSON> Pendergrass </PERSON> about the 48 months of delay on the respirator issue and similar delays on three other changes that had been recommended by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s task force `` <ORGANIZATION> OMB </ORGANIZATION> was critical of the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> for failing to meet its commitments and deadlines,'' <PERSON> Baroody </PERSON> said in the March 28 memo. `` The vice president affirmed this and expressed his personal interest and concern in completing the regulatory agenda established by the task force.'' <PERSON> Hart </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s spokesman, described the meeting as a broad review of each agency's success or failure in carrying out the task force's recommendations. `` The vice president did n't set his sights on this particular regulatory item but on the entire unfilled agenda,'' <PERSON> Hart </PERSON> said. `` In the spirit of let's get going on these items, he said we need to make this part of our agenda for the remainder of the year.'' <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, meanwhile, repeated his charges Tuesday, saying that career <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> employees were instructed by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration officials `` to generate misleading data that give the appearance of zeal as a cover for neglect.'' `` We're going to have a new administration after this fall and, hopefully, we can get this agency back on track again,'' he said after Tuesday's hearing. <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON> <PERSON> Vallon </PERSON>, an industrial hygienist in <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Irving </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, office, told the committee Tuesday that she produced 25 <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> inspection reports from a three-day visit to a construction site last September. Ms. <PERSON> Vallon </PERSON> said she believes she was told by supervisors to inspect the site because of a large number of subcontractors on the job and her office was nearing the end of the fiscal year and had not met its quota of inspections. `` They did n't exactly say it, but I drew that conclusion,'' she said in response to a question from <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION>. `` We were under constant pressure to get numbers.'' In response to another question from <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION>, Ms. <PERSON> Vallon </PERSON> agreed with his assertion that the inspection program `` essentially was a sham.'' <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> records show that the number of its inspections rose from 59,452 in fiscal 1986 to 61,466 last year but were still 3 percent below what they were in 1980, the last year of President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>'s administration Inspections of manufacturing plants also have declined by 45 percent in the past seven years but inspections of construction sites have increased by 35 percent over the same time to 35,495 last year. <ORGANIZATION> OSHA </ORGANIZATION> officials have repeatedly defended that record as switching the agency's resources to where the greatest hazards exist _ construction. Unions, however, have maintained that the policy also has allowed the agency to `` inflate'' its enforcement activity by counting each subcontractor on the site as a separate inspection. `` Most sites average seven to eight contractors, meaning that in reality only 4,500 to 5,000 construction sites were visited,'' <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Steelworkers </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> told the committee earlier.
