<HEAD>Reagan Calls For Long-Term Investment In Space</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to UPDATE with speech being delivered.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on Tuesday took issue with critics of administration space plans and asked <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people to `` join me in making the long-term investment required to advance <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> leadership in space.'' `` Can we afford to stop our exploration and wait for others to pass us?'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> asked in a speech at the annual government-industry dinner of the <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. `` The space station is vital to our leadership in space and contributes to our pre-eminence in manned space flight,'' the president said. `` Some say we ca n't afford the space station.'' But, he asked, `` can we afford to jettison the next generation of technical spin-offs?'' `` Tonight I ask <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and all the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people to join me in making the long-term investment required to advance <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> leadership in space,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> said. `` We must begin that investment by funding the increases I've proposed for our civil space program.'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also said it was administration policy `` to encourage private sector investment and involvement in outer space.'' `` We will help develop a highway to space by using private launch services to the greatest extent feasible, and we are working to win legislation to limit liability for commercial launch providers,'' he said. `` It's a future beyond the most distant star in our dreams that beckons us,'' <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> told the electronics executives. `` And to those who say it ca n't be reached, that it's impossible, I'd just point toward your industries and ask if a few years ago they thought what you are doing today would also be impossible.'' The president also put in a plug for the Strategic Defense Initiative, or Star Wars, his proposal for a space-based defense against nuclear missiles. `` Five years ago I proposed SDI and, much to my satisfaction, we have made tremendous progress in that research,'' he said. `` We must not stop dreaming because a few naysayers insist on limiting our options for a safe and secure future.''
</TEXT>
